surveys.narrative: THE 1992 WAE CATCH INDEX (9.0 FISH PER GN, 1.43 LBS. MEAN WEIGHT PER GN) WAS ABOVE THE HISTORICAL MEANS (7.81 FISH PER GN, 1.29 LBS. MEAN WEIGHT0 PER GN) AND WAS AVERAGE COMPARED TO OTHER LAKE CLASS 27 LAKES (9.67, 75% QUARTILE). THE AGE- CLASS DISTRIBUTION APPEARS BALANCED WITH THE EXCEPTION OF A WEAK 1991 YEAR CLASS (NO STOCKING IN 1991). A STRONG 1986 YEAR CLASS SHOULD CONTINUE TO PROVIDE QUALITY FISH > 18.0 INCHES. PSD VALUES HAVE BEEN CONSISTENT THE LAST THREE SURVEYS AND ARE IN THE 30-60% RANGE FOR A BALANCED POPULATION. WAE GROW RATES ARE BELOW-TO-AVERAGE WHICH IS TYPICAL FOR GREEN LAKE. THE NOP CATCH INDEX (2.58 FISH PER GN, 2.83 LBS. MEAN WEIGHT PER GN) WAS SLIGHTLY BELOW THE HISTORICAL MEAN FOR NUMBERS (2.83 FISH PER GN, 2.61 LBS. MEAN WEIGHT PER GN) AND ALSO BELOW AVERAGE COMPARED TO OTHER LAKE CLASS 27 LAKES. THE HIGH PSD VALUE (>60) REFLECTS THE POOR NATURAL REPRODUCTIVE SUCCESS OF NOP IN GREEN LAKE THE LAST FEW YEARS. HOWEVER, THE RSD-P OF 12 (PREFERRED FISH >28 INCHES/ STOCK SIZE FISH > 19 GREEN LAKE TO PRODUCE POTENTIAL TROPHYS. GROWTH RATES APPEAR BELOW AVERAGE COMPARED TO THE LOCAL AREA AND PREVIOUS SURVEYS. BLC WAS ABSENT FROM THE GILL NET SETS AND ONLY 1 FISH WAS CAUGHT IN THE TRAP NETS IN 1992, EVEN THOUGH THE 1990 YEAR CLASS APPEARED MODERATE-TO-STRONG IN THE 1991 SURVEY. BLC GILL NET INDEX HAS BEEN BELOW AVERAGE THE LAST THREE SURVEYS. SMB GILL NET INDEX (0.33 FISH PER GN) WAS AVEAGE COMPARED TO THE OTHER LAKE CLASS 27 LAKES. THE SMB TRAPNET INDEX WAS 0.07 IN 1992 COMPARED TO 4.87 FISH IN 1991 AND 1.13 FISH IN 1990. SMB ( 7.0 INCHES. FALL CISCO GILLNET CATCH INDEX (85.1 FISH PER GN) WAS ABOVE THE HISTORICAL MEAN (76.7 FISH PER GN). THE AVERAGE SIZE OF CISCO HAS BEEN ABOUT 11.0 INCHES THE LAST THREE SURVEYS. THE STRONG 1989 YEAR CLASS IS STILL APPARENT IN THE 1992 SURVEY. THERE ALSO APPEARS TO BE MODERATE 1991 AND 1990 YEAR CLASSES OF CISCO. CISCO GROWTH RATES APPEAR AVERAGE FOR GREEN LAKE. THE CISCO POPULATION HAS REBOUNDED FROM THE PARTIAL 1988 SUMMERKILL AND HAS REMAINED STABLE THE LAST THREE YEARS.

A population assessment of Green Lake was conducted in late July of 2005. Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegill. Green Lake receives high recreational use during the summer months. Aquatic vegetation is generally limited in the lake. Low densities of Eurasian water milfoil have been documented in Green Lake primarily near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, and several isolated areas since 2000. Efforts to chemically eradicate Eurasian water milfoil have been unsuccessful. Widespread and extensive matting of Eurasian water milfoil is unlikely to occur through out Green Lake. A Highway 23 four-lane construction project began in 2003 adjacent to Green Lake and was completed in the fall of 2005. Significant runoff (sediment) from the Highway 23 construction project drained into Green Lake during several large rainfall events in late June and early July of 2003. One of the positive aspects of the Highway 23 project was the construction of storm water retention ponds along the Highway 23 corridor to reduce or slow future runoff into Green Lake. Water clarity was poor during late August of 2003 (secchi=4.83 feet), but good during July of 2004 (secchi=13.5 feet) and July of 2005 (secchi=9.5 feet). Green Lake is managed primarily for walleye, northern pike, tullibee, bluegill, and smallmouth bass. Walleye fingerling stocking is contingent in Green Lake after successive walleye natural reproduction or fry stocking failures.Experimental regulations for northern pike, smallmouth bass, and largemouth bass were enacted in Green Lake during 1997 as part of a statewide research study. The goals were to evaluate the success or failure of certain types of experimental regulations, and produce trophy fisheries of bass and northern pike in Green Lake. The northern pike experimental regulation (24 inch maximum size limit) prohibited the harvest of fish 24 inches and greater. The smallmouth and largemouth bass regulation was originally catch and release only. However, the bass regulation was modified to a 14 inch maximum harvest size limit in 2001. The bass regulation was modified again in the 2003 fall to a 14 inch maximum harvest size limit with one bass over 21 inches allowed. The bass regulation was changed because of increasing numbers of smallmouth bass and the perceived negative effects on the walleye population in Green Lake. A public input meeting in regards to the Green Lake experimental regulations occurred during the 2005 fall. In December of 2005, the DNR decided to end experimental regulation for both smallmouth bass and northern pike and return to statewide regulations as of the May 13, 2006 for northern pike and May 27, 2006 for bass. This decision was based both on public input and the analyzed data collected from netting and creel surveys.Bluegill numbers were moderate in 2005 (28.57 fish/trapnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, but below the historical average (49.49 fish/trapnet) for Green. The 2005 bluegill average size was small to moderate (0.14 pounds and 5.7 inches) from the trapnets. The largest bluegill captured was 8.5 inches in the 2005 assessment. Black crappie numbers were moderate to abundant in 2005 (1.67 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and above the historical average (0.57 fish/gillnet) for Green. The 2005 black crappie average size was small to moderate (0.20 pounds and 7.0 inches) from gillnets. The black crappie historical average length is 7.7 inches from gillnets in Green. Northern pike numbers were low to moderate in 2005 (2.33 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and slightly below the historical average (2.91 fish/gillnet) for Green. The 2005 northern pike average size was moderate (3.30 pounds and 24.0 inches) from gillnets. The northern pike historical average length is 22.4 inches from gillnets. The northern pike captured in 2003-2005 surveys were notably lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. The DNR creel clerk and local anglers observed low to moderate numbers of dead northern pike floating in Green Lake from spring to mid summer of 2005. The majority of these fish died from a bacterial disease known as columnaris. Low numbers of forage fish (yellow perch and tullibee) were documented in Green Lake surveys from 2003-2005. Northern pike growth rates were within or below the normal ranges for Green. The 2002 northern pike year class comprised 38% of the 2005 total northern pike assessment catch. The largest northern pike captured was 33.5 inches in the 2005 assessment.Smallmouth bass numbers were high in 2005 (2.75 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and above the historical average (2.00 fish/gillnet) for Green. The 2005 smallmouth bass average size was large (2.22 pounds and 15.6 inches) from gillnets. The smallmouth bass historical average length is 13.4 inches from gillnets for Green. The 2000 and 1999 smallmouth bass year classes comprised 35% and 25% respectively of the total 2005 smallmouth bass assessment catch. Smallmouth bass growth rates were below the normal ranges for Green. Crayfish, an important smallmouth bass forage species, were caught in low numbers in 2005 (0.2 crayfish/gillnet). No crayfish were caught in the 2004, 2003 or 2002 gillnets. The crayfish historical average catch rate is 11.4 crayfish/gillnet for Green. The largest smallmouth captured was 18.5 inches in the 2005 assessment.Tullibee "cisco" numbers were low to moderate in the 2005 (0.75 fish/gillnet) summer compared to the normal range of similar lakes, but below the historical average (2.57 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. The 2005 summer tullibee average size was moderate (0.40 pounds and 9.4 inches) from gillnets. Yellow perch numbers were low in 2005 (8.08 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and below the historical average (18.41 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. The 2005 yellow perch average size was small (0.09 pounds and 6.3 inches) from gillnets. The yellow perch historical average weight is 0.13 pounds from gillnets. Yellow perch growth rates were within the normal ranges for Green. The 2002 yellow perch year class comprised 82% of the 2005 total yellow perch assessment catch.Walleye numbers were low in 2005 (4.42 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and below the historical average (9.00 fish/gillnet) for Green. The 2005 walleye average size was moderate (1.74 pounds and 16.0 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average length is 14.7 inches from gillnets. The 2000 and 2004 year classes (stocked and natural reproduction) comprised 19% and 22% respectively of the total 2005 walleye assessment catch. Walleye growth rates were generally above the normal ranges for Green. A 2005 fall electrofishing survey was conducted to evaluate walleye natural reproduction and a 2005 walleye fry stocking (3.76 million) in Green Lake. There were no young of year "YOY" walleye captured in 2005. Other walleye naturally reproducing area lakes also had generally low YOY walleye catch rates in 2005 fall electrofishing surveys. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average catch rate and length are 15.90 YOY/hour and 6.8 inches respectively. The Spicer Area YOY walleye historical average catch rate is 68.66 YOY/hour from lakes fry stocked and lakes with natural reproduction. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY walleye for Green occurred in 1994 (54.00 YOY/hour, 6.2 inches average size). Walleye frylings (666 fish, 2.4 pounds), fingerlings (5,466 fish, 264 pounds), yearlings (11,863 fish, 3,433 pounds), and adults (356 fish, 673 pounds) were stocked into Green during early October of 2005 in response to poor walleye natural reproduction and fry stocking results for 2003-2005. Green Lake has been stocked annually with walleye fry from 2000-2005 except for 2002. Various combinations of walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked yearly (2,000 - 4,000 pounds/year) since 2000 into Green Lake. During the 1990's, walleye fry were stocked in 1996 and fingerlings/yearlings/adults were stocked in 1994, 1992, 1990.Rock bass numbers were abundant in 2005 (10.83 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and above the historical average (7.26 fish/gillnet) for Green. The 2005 rock bass average size was small to moderate (0.34 pounds and 7.5 inches) from gillnets. The rock bass historical average weight is 0.43 pounds from gillnets.Largemouth bass numbers were moderate in 2005 (0.75 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, but above the historical average size (0.21 fish/gillnet). The 2005 largemouth bass average size was small (0.76 pounds and 10.4 inches) from gillnets. The largemouth bass historical average weight is 0.65 pounds from gillnets. Largemouth bass growth rates were below the normal ranges for Green. The 2002 largemouth bass year class comprised 40% of the 2005 largemouth bass Green Lake assessment catch.Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on a periodic basis, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives, and stocking various fish species as warranted. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the 2006 spring ice out for northern pike, 2006 fall for walleye natural reproduction, and 2006 summer for all fish species by survey nets. A creel survey is proposed for the 2006-07 winter and 2007 summer.

A resurvey of Green Lake was conducted in late July of 2008. Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Water levels were normal during the early summer, but low by the fall of 2008. Water clarity was good (8.0- 10.0 feet) for Green Lake in the 2008 summer. Total phosphorus level was low (0.014 ppm) during early June of 2008. Ice out was late in 2008 (April 30th). Dissolved oxygen levels were above 4.0 ppm in depths down to 32 feet during late July of 2008. The shoreline is fully developed with the exception of the outlet area on the east side of the lake. There were 641 homes, 2 county parks, 1 bed & breakfast, 2 resorts (11 cabins), 13 apartment buildings, and 26 homes in a common interest community located within a connected bay (Indian Beach). The immediate watershed is varied with the City of Spicer, residential homes, wetlands, hardwood lots, and agricultural row crops. There are approximately 48 inlets (mostly small tiles) that drain into Green Lake. The Middle Fork of the Crow River (Nest Lake outlet) is the largest inlet that flows into Green Lake along the north shore at the Ye Olde Mill Inn Dam and exits along the east shore of Green Lake. Nutrient runoff is low to moderate primarily from nearby residential and city sources, and upstream sources from the Middle Fork of the Crow River via Nest Lake. Numerous storm water retention ponds were built during the 2003 State Highway 23 Four-Lane Project along the west side of Green Lake. There are six public access sites and one shore fishing site (outlet) on the lake. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegill. Green Lake receives high recreational use during the summer months. Green Lake is managed primarily for walleye and secondarily for northern pike, yellow perch, tullibee, bluegill, and smallmouth bass.

Overall aquatic vegetation trends for mean abundance and frequency occurrence were generally greater in 2008 than previous surveys. There were 27 aquatic vegetation species/groups sampled in 2008 compared to 22 in 1994, 31 in 2003, and 21 in 2007. Water level and precipitation conditions were normal during the early summer, but dry conditions were the rule during the late summer of 2008. Water clarity was poor during the late summer of 2003 (4.83 feet) compared to 1994 (7.50 feet), 2007 (7.20 feet) and 2008 (9.0 feet). Aquatic vegetation densities generally increase during low water due to increased water clarity conditions and light penetration to substrate surface areas that were previously inaccessible. The maximum depth of vegetation was the greatest in 2007 (40 feet) compared to 2008 (31 feet), 2003 (30 feet) or 1994 (35 feet). The 2008 aquatic vegetation species trends for frequency occurrence and mean abundance include increases of river pondweed, curly-leaf pondweed, Eurasian milfoil, flat-stem pondweed, Fries' pondweed, water celery, stonewort, Robbins' pondweed, muskgrass, narrow-leaf pondweed, and bladderwort. Chara (muskgrass) frequency occurrence was slightly higher in 2008 (98%) than 2007 (94%), 2003 (96%) and 1994 (92%). Mean abundance of muskgrass was 49.0% for 2008, 32.1% for 1994, 29.3% for 2003, and 44.3% for 2007. Stonewort (nitella) appreciably increased in 2008 (50% occurrence, 24.3 mean abundance) compared to previous surveys. Vegetation species that were relatively unchanged in frequency occurrence or mean abundance from 2003 to 2007 were curly-leaf pondweed, northern milfoil, and hardstem bulrush. Current notable vegetation species that trends decreased in frequency occurrence and mean abundance included filamentous algae, sago pondweed, water moss, variable-leaf pondweed, hardstem bulrush, clasping-leaf pondweed, leafy pondweed, naiad, and waterlily species.

Low densities of Eurasian water milfoil have been documented in Green Lake primarily near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, and several isolated areas since 2000. Efforts to chemically eradicate various Eurasian water milfoil stands were overall unsuccessful in 2000, 2001, 2007, and 2008. Eurasian milfoil occurred in 20% (10 transects) of the 2008 transects, 16% (8) of the 2007 transects, and 4%(2) of the 2003 transects. It is not surprising that frequency occurrence has increased probably due to the ease of Eurasian milfoil fragmenting and colonizing new suitable areas. Mean abundance of Eurasian milfoil within the transects increased from 1.3% in 2003, to 5.3% in 2007, and to 6.0% in 2008. It appears that Eurasian milfoil mean abundance has increased at a slower rate from 2007 to 2008 than from 2003 to 2007. Widely scattered Eurasian milfoil stands were observed in off shore "break" areas at a mean depth of 8.6 feet during 2007. Most large stands of Eurasian milfoil on Green Lake have been located near storm water inlets. Watershed projects that may reduce sediment and nutrient inputs from storm water inlets will be important for controlling Eurasian milfoil in these patchy areas. Widespread-extensive matting of Eurasian water milfoil is unlikely to occur through out Green Lake due to frequent windswept conditions, the presence of relatively low nitrogen (ammonium) nutrient levels and unsuitable dominant substrates (boulder, rubble, gravel) present in the majority of shoalwater areas.

Experimental regulations for northern pike, smallmouth bass, and largemouth bass were enacted in Green Lake during 1997 as part of a statewide research study. The goals were to evaluate the success or failure of certain types of experimental regulations, and produce trophy fisheries of bass and northern pike in Green Lake. A public input meeting in regards to the future of Green Lake experimental regulations occurred during the 2005 fall. In December of 2005, the DNR decided to end all experimental regulations on Green Lake (largemouth bass, smallmouth bass and northern pike) and return to statewide regulations on May 13, 2006 for northern pike and May 27, 2006 for bass. This decision was based both on public input and the analyzed data collected from netting and creel surveys.

Bluegill numbers were moderate to abundant in 2008 (47.60/trapnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green Lake (25th=28.04, 50th=47.60, 75th=65.77 fish/trapnet) for Green Lake and similar lakes. The Green Lake bluegill historical average catch rate is 49.28 fish/trapnet. The 2008 bluegill average size was small (0.13 pounds and 5.54 inches) from the trapnets. The bluegill historical average weight is 0.12 pounds from trapnets. The 2008 catch rate of quality size (6.00 inches) and larger bluegill was high (16.80 fish/trapnet) and above the historical average (11.65 fish/trapnet). The 2008 catch rate of preferred size (8.00 inches) and larger bluegill (0.40 fish/trapnet) was low. Bluegill growth rates were below the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 2-5, but within the normal ranges for ages 1 and 6-8. The 2005 year class comprised 35% of the 2008 total bluegill gillnet and trapnet catch. Low young of year "YOY" bluegill numbers (3.30 fish/seine haul) were captured in the 2008 shoreline seine hauls.

Black crappie numbers were moderate to abundant in 2008 (1.58 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green Lake (25th=0.08, 50th=0.42, 75th=1.54 fish/gillnet) and similar lakes. The Green Lake black crappie historical average catch rate is 0.81 fish/gillnet. The 2008 black crappie average size was moderate (0.60 pounds and 9.50 inches) from gillnets. The black crappie historical average length is 7.88 inches from gillnets. The 2008 catch rate of quality size (8.00 inches) and larger black crappie was moderate (1.17 fish/gillnet) and above the historical average (0.26 fish/gillnet). Black crappie growth rates were between the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-4, and above the normal range for age 5. Growth rates were within the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-2 and above the normal ranges for ages 3-6. The 2005 black crappie year class comprised 65% of the 2007 black crappie survey catch and 50% of the 2008 survey catch. No YOY black crappie were captured in the 2008 shoreline seine hauls.

Northern pike numbers were low in 2008 (1.92 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green (25th=2.25, 50th=2.75, 75th=3.25 fish/gillnet) and similar lakes. The Green Lake northern pike historical average catch rate is 2.78 fish/gillnet. The 2008 northern pike average size was moderate (3.65 pounds and 24.92 inches) from gillnets. The northern pike historical average weight and length are 3.09 pounds and 23.13 inches from gillnets. Northern pike captured in 2003-2006 surveys were notably lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. Large northern pike (>24 inches) condition factors (Fulton K-factor) were near or below the Green normal range (0.591 - 0.662 K-factor) for 2008 (0.605 K-factor) and every year since 1999 except 2001 and 2002. Low numbers of forage fish (yellow perch and tullibee) were documented in Green Lake surveys from 2003-2008. The 2008 catch rate of preferred size (28.00 inches) and larger northern pike was low to moderate (0.42 fish/gillnet) and near the historical average (0.43 fish/gillnet). Spearing pressure and harvest of large northern pike was high during the 2006-07 winter following the return to statewide regulations. Northern pike growth rates were within or above the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-3 and below the 25th quartiles for ages 4-6. Growth rates were generally near or above the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-6. The 2004 year class comprised 31% of the 2008 northern pike gillnet and trapnet catch.

Smallmouth bass numbers were moderate in 2008 (1.67 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for Green Lake (25th=0.54, 50th=1.67, 75th=2.58 fish/gillnet) but above the normal range for similar lakes. The smallmouth bass historical average catch rate is 1.97 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2008 smallmouth bass average size was moderate (1.81 pounds and 14.24 inches) from gillnets. The smallmouth bass historical average weight and length are 1.55 pounds and 13.44 inches from gillnets. The 2008 catch rate of preferred size (14.00 inches) and larger smallmouth bass (1.00 fish/gillnet) was similar to the historical average (1.27 fish/gillnet). Several moderate smallmouth year classes (2005, 2001, 2000) comprised the 2008 smallmouth bass gillnet catch. Smallmouth bass growth rates were below the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 2-7. The 2008 smallmouth bass condition factor (Fulton K-Factor) was 1.410. Smallmouth bass condition factors have been near or below the Green normal range since 2000. YOY smallmouth bass numbers was low in 2008 shoreline seine hauls (0.90 fish/seine haul, 1.93 inches average length). Crayfish, an important smallmouth bass forage species, were not captured in 2008 or 2007, low numbers in 2006 (0.1 crayfish/gillnet) and 2005 (0.2 crayfish/gillnet). No crayfish were caught in the 2004, 2003 or 2002 gillnets. The crayfish historical average catch rate is 9.0 crayfish/gillnet for Green.

Tullibee "cisco" numbers were moderate to abundant in the 2008 summer (2.58 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for Green Lake (25th=0.50, 50th=1.00, 75th=2.68 fish/gillnet) similar lakes. The tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 2.42 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. All of the tullibee were captured in one gillnet station located along the east portion of the lake located in 30-40 feet deep. The 2008 summer tullibee average size was large (1.42 pounds and 14.35 inches) from gillnets. The tullibee historical average weight is 0.51 pounds from gillnets. Tullibee growth rates were below the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-2, within the normal ranges for ages 3-6, and above the normal range for age 7. The 2004 and 2003 year classes each comprised 37% of the 2008 tullibee summer gillnet catch.

Yellow perch numbers were low in 2008 (4.75 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green Lake (25th=6.67, 50th=15.80, 75th=23.13 fish/gillnet) and similar lakes. The yellow perch historical average catch rate is 16.54 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2008 yellow perch average size was small (0.11 pounds and 6.31 inches) from gillnets. The yellow perch historical average weight is 0.13 pounds from gillnets. The 2008 catch rate of quality size (8.00 inches) and larger yellow perch was low (0.25 fish/gillnet). Yellow perch growth rates were generally below both the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-4. The 2005 (52%)and 2004 (36%) yellow perch year classes comprised the majority of the 2008 yellow perch gillnet catch. The 2008 yellow perch condition factor (Fulton K-Factor) was 1.084. Yellow perch condition factors have been near or below the Green normal range since 2003. YOY yellow perch abundance was low (0.20 fish/seine haul, 1.85 inches average length) in the 2008 shoreline seine hauls.

Walleye numbers were moderate in 2008 (8.17 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green Lake (25th=7.69, 50th=9.42, 75th=9.96 fish/gillnet) and similar lakes. The walleye historical average catch rate is 9.12 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2008 walleye average size was moderate (1.56 pounds and 15.35 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average weight and length are 1.26 pounds and 14.66 inches from gillnets. The 2008 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches) and larger walleye (3.92 fish/gillnet) was near the historical average (3.87 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. An unexpected number of older walleye from the 1994, 1995, 2000, and 2001 year classes were captured in the 2008 gillnets and trapnets. The walleye year classes of 2006 (30%), 2005 (23%), and 2004 (19%) comprised the majority of the 2008 gillnet catch. The 2004 year class (stocked and natural reproduction) comprised 41% of the total 2007 walleye assessment gillnet catch. The recent walleye year classes since 2001 are probably due mostly to stocking. Walleye growth rates were generally below the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-3 and within the normal ranges for ages 4-8. However, growth rates were near or above the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-9. The 2008 walleye condition factor (Fulton K-Factor) was 0.932. Walleye condition factors have been above the Green Lake normal range since 1999.

A fall electrofishing survey of Green Lake was conducted during early October of 2008. The 2008 fall electrofishing survey was conducted to evaluate walleye natural reproduction and a 2008 walleye fry stocking in Green Lake. Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked walleye fry (approximately 1.03 million/year) were stocked during 2007 and 2008. The walleye fry were stocked as a 10% return of walleye eggs taken for the statewide propagation program. There were low young of year "YOY" walleye numbers (7.00 YOY/hour, 5.97 inches average length) captured in 2008. Marked fish from 2007 and 2008 fry stockings accounted for 43% of YOY walleye catch and 33% of the yearling walleye catch in the 2008 fall electrofishing. Marked yearling walleye accounted for 29% of the 2008 summer yearling walleye gillnet catch. A marked three-year old walleye from a small stocking (666 frylings) was also captured in the 2008 summer gillnets. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average catch rate and length are 14.29 YOY/hour and 6.79 inches. The Spicer Area YOY walleye historical average catch rate is 76.32 YOY/hour from lakes fry stocked and lakes with natural reproduction. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY walleye for Green occurred in 1994 (54.00 YOY/hour, 6.15 inches average size). Walleye fingerlings (51,641 fish, 3,105 pounds), yearlings (5,016 fish, 209 pounds), and fry (1,028,856 fish) were stocked into Green during early April-November of 2008. There were 30,787 marked OTC stocked in Green during the fall of 2008. Green Lake has been stocked annually with walleye fry from 2000-2008 except for 2002. Various combinations of walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked yearly (2,000 -4,000 pounds/year) since 2000 into Green Lake. During the 1990's, walleye fry were stocked in 1996 and fingerlings/yearlings/adults were stocked in 1994, 1992, 1990.

Rock bass numbers were abundant in 2008 (13.83 fish/gillnet) and the highest recorded value for Green Lake. The 2008 rock bass abundance was above the normal ranges for Green Lake (25th=4.48, 50th=8.11, 75th=10.25 fish/gillnet) and similar lakes. The rock bass historical average catch rate is 7.59 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2008 rock bass average size was moderate (0.40 pounds and 7.63 inches) from gillnets. The rock bass historical average weight is 0.43 pounds from gillnets.

Largemouth bass numbers were moderate to abundant in 2008 (0.92 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green (25th=0.00, 50th=0.13, 75th=0.50 fish/gillnet) and similar lakes. The largemouth bass historical average catch rate is 0.53 fish/gillnet for Green. The 2008 largemouth bass average size was moderate (0.87 pounds and 11.18 inches) from gillnets. The largemouth bass historical average weight is 0.65 pounds from gillnets. Largemouth bass growth rates were generally below the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-6, but within the normal ranges for ages 7-8. The 2005 largemouth bass year class comprised 46% of the 2008 largemouth bass assessment gillnet and trapnet catch. YOY largemouth bass abundance was low (2.40 fish/seine/haul, 1.83 inches average length) in the 2008 shoreline seine hauls.

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the 2009 fall for walleye natural reproduction, and 2009 summer for all fish species by survey nets.

A population assessment of Green Lake was conducted in early August of 2010. Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Water levels were normal to high during the 2010 summer. Water clarity was moderate (8.5 feet) for Green Lake on August 2, 2010. The 2010 summer weather was moderate during the early months, but warm by late July and early August. Dissolved oxygen levels were below 2.0 ppm in depths below 30 feet during early August of 2010. A combination of inadequate oxygen levels (< 2ppm) and potentially lethal high temperatures (> 72 F) in water depths below 30 feet were conducive for a tullibee "cisco" fish kill during a relatively short time period of early August of 2010, but no dead fish were observed in Green Lake. A minor summerkill of cisco occurred during the same time period on nearby Lake Koronis in 2010. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegill. Green Lake receives high recreational use during the summer months. Green Lake is managed primarily for walleye and secondarily for northern pike, yellow perch, cisco "tullibee", bluegill, and smallmouth bass.

The threats of present (Eurasian water milfoil, curly-leaf pondweed) and potential exotic invasive species introductions (i.e. zebra mussels, quagga mussels, spiny water flea, faucet snail, etc.) are of a major concern to local residents in Kandiyohi County. Eurasian water milfoil "EWM" was first documented in Green Lake at several isolated sites during 2000. Initial DNR attempts to chemically eradicate EWM were unsuccessful. Eurasian water milfoil has spread throughout the lake in scattered stands especially near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, storm water inlet areas and off shore "break" areas since 2000.

The lake association has continued to chemically and physically eradicate various EWM stands in recent years with relatively minimal long term success. New developments in chemical control of EWM (i.e. granular triclopyr treatment) were attempted in Green Lake during 2010, but initial results appear to be also unsuccessful in eradicating EWM probably due to continual mixing and wave action, which probably dilutes the herbicide concentrations in EWM infested areas. EWM and curly-leaf pondweed tend to thrive in disturbed areas (i.e. previously chemically or mechanically treated areas, storm water inlets) or during years of minimal snowfall and maximum light penetration when competition from native species is minimal. Many large stands of EWM on Green Lake have been located near storm water inlets. Watershed projects that may reduce sediment and nutrient inputs from storm water inlets will also be important for controlling EWM in these patchy areas. Widespread-extensive matting of EWM on the surface is unlikely to occur throughout Green Lake unlike some milfoil infested lakes with protected bay areas (i.e. Minnetonka) due to frequent windswept conditions, the presence of relatively low nitrogen (ammonium) nutrient levels and unsuitable dominant substrates (boulder, rubble, gravel) present in the majority of shoal water areas of Green Lake. DNR Aquatic invasive species interns will continue to randomly monitor boats entering and leaving the many access sites in an attempt to educate and prevent the spread of exotics into Kandiyohi County Lakes.

Experimental regulations for northern pike, smallmouth bass, and largemouth bass were enacted in Green Lake during 1997 as part of a statewide research study. The goals were to evaluate the success or failure of certain types of experimental regulations, and produce trophy fisheries of bass and northern pike in Green Lake. In December of 2005, the DNR decided to end all experimental regulations on Green Lake (largemouth bass, smallmouth bass and northern pike) and return to statewide regulations on May 13, 2006 for northern pike and May 27, 2006 for bass. This decision was based both on public input and the analyzed data collected from netting and creel assessments.

Bluegill numbers were moderately abundant in 2010 (49.33/trapnet) compared to the normal ranges of Green Lake and similar lakes. The Green Lake bluegill historical average catch rate is 48.43 fish/trapnet. The 2010 bluegill average size was moderate (0.17 pounds and 5.86 inches) from the trapnets. The bluegill historical average weight is 0.12 pounds from trapnets. The 2010 catch rate of quality size (6.00 inches) and larger bluegill (24.10 fish/trapnet) was high compared to the historical average (12.20 fish/trapnet).

Black crappie numbers were moderately abundant in 2010 (2.25 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges of Green Lake and similar lakes. The Green Lake black crappie historical average catch rate is 0.90 fish/gillnet. The 2010 black crappie size was small (0.33 pounds and 7.63 inches) from gillnets. The black crappie historical average length is 7.95 inches from gillnets in Green.

Northern pike numbers were moderately abundant in 2010 (2.92 fish/gillnet) compared the normal range and historical average (2.73 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake, but below the normal range for similar lakes. The 2010 northern pike average size was moderate from gillnets (3.28 pounds and 23.17 inches) and similar to the historical average size (3.11 pounds and 23.21 inches). Total numbers of larger (>24 inches) northern pike appear to have rebounded in 2010 compared to 2008-09. Northern pike captured in 2003, 2004 2005, 2007 and 2009 assessments were notably lean in appearance (poor condition) compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. However, condition factors improved in 2010 for northern pike and were above the Green Lake normal range. Low numbers of forage fish (yellow perch, white sucker and tullibee) were generally documented in Green Lake assessments from 2003-2010. Northern pike growth rates were within the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-7. The 2007 year class comprised 33% of the 2010 northern pike gillnet and trapnet catch.

Smallmouth bass numbers were abundant in 2010 (2.25 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green and similar lakes. The smallmouth bass historical average catch rate is 1.94 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2010 smallmouth bass average size was moderate (1.37 pounds and 12.51 inches) from gillnets. The smallmouth bass historical average weight and length are 1.57 pounds and 13.48 inches from gillnets for Green Lake. The 2010 catch rate of preferred size (14.00 inches) and larger smallmouth bass (1.08 fish/gillnet) was slightly below the historical average (1.22 fish/gillnet). The smallmouth bass condition factor was low in 2010. Smallmouth bass condition factors have been near or below the Green Lake normal ranges since 2000. The 2005-2008 year classes each comprised about 20% of the 2010 smallmouth bass gillnet catch. Smallmouth bass growth rates were below the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-8.

Crayfish, an important smallmouth bass forage species, were not captured in 2002-2004 and 2007-2009. Low numbers of crayfish were captured in 2010 (0.3 crayfish/gillnet), 2006 (0.1 crayfish/gillnet) and 2005 (0.2 crayfish/gillnet). The crayfish historical average catch rate is 7.9 crayfish/gillnet for Green.

Tullibee "cisco" were moderately abundant in the 2010 summer (4.92 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green Lake and similar lakes. The tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 2.43 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. A majority of the tullibee were captured in two summer gillnet stations located along the east and south portions of the lake at a depth of approximately 30 feet. The 2010 summer tullibee average size was small (0.69 pounds and 10.46 inches) from gillnets. The tullibee historical average weight is 0.57 pounds from gillnets. Summerkill potential was high during late July of 2010, but there were no reports of dead tullibee floating in Green Lake.

There were low numbers of tullibee (3.8 fish/gillnet) captured in the 2010 fall special assessment. The 2010 tullibee average size was small (0.77 pounds and 11.66 inches) for Green in the 2010 fall. The fall tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 79.9 fish/gillnet and 12.44 inches for Green Lake. The 2010 fall tullibee condition factor (1.096) was below the 25th quartile for Green Lake. Tullibee growth rates were below the Green Lake 25th quartiles for ages 1-5. The 2007 and 2006 year classes comprised 41% and 27% of the 2010 fall tullibee catch in Green Lake. The lack of adult tullibee on the spawning grounds from early November to early December of 2010 as sampled by both DNR and private netters during the open season is not a good indication for the long term sustainability of the tullibee population in Green Lake. Hopefully, cool summers will occur during the next several years, which may result in a good hatch and survival of tullibee in Green Lake if adequate brood stock numbers are still present.

Yellow perch numbers were low in 2010 (2.17 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green Lake and similar lakes. The yellow perch historical average catch rate is 15.41 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2010 yellow perch average size was moderate (0.11 pounds and 6.49 inches) from gillnets. The yellow perch historical average weight is 0.13 pounds from gillnets. The 2010 catch rate of quality size (8.00 inches) and larger yellow perch was nonexistent (0.00 fish/gillnet). Yellow perch condition factors have been near or below the Green Lake normal range since 2003. Yellow perch growth rates were within the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-3, but below the normal range for age 4. The 2007 yellow perch year classes comprised the 88% of the 2010 yellow perch gillnet catch.

Walleye numbers were moderately abundant in 2010 (11.00 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green Lake and similar lakes. The walleye historical average catch rate is 8.95 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2010 walleye average size was moderate (1.26 pounds and 14.72 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average weight and length are 1.26 pounds and 14.68 inches from gillnets. The 2010 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches) and larger walleye (5.08 fish/gillnet) was above the historical average (3.81 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. The 2010 walleye condition factor was below the normal range for Green. Walleye growth rates were below the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-8. Growth rates were generally within the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 3-8 and below the normal ranges for ages 1-2. The recent walleye year classes since 2001 are due mostly to stocking. The 2008 and 2007 walleye year classes each comprised about 25% of the 2010 walleye gillnet and trapnet catch.

A fall electrofishing assessment of Green Lake was conducted during early October of 2010. The 2010 fall electrofishing assessment was conducted to evaluate walleye natural reproduction and a 2010 walleye fry stocking in Green Lake. Two million OTC marked walleye fry were stocked in Green during 2009 and 2010. The walleye fry were stocked in part as a 10% return of walleye eggs taken for the statewide propagation program. There were low young of year "YOY" walleye numbers (11.00 YOY/hour, 6.60 inches average length) captured in 2010. Walleye yearling numbers were moderate (9.00 fish/hour, 9.18 inches average length) in the 2010 fall electrofishing survey. Marked fish from 2009 and 2010 stockings accounted for 55% of YOY walleye catch and 13% of the yearling walleye catch in the 2010 fall electrofishing. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average YOY walleye catch rate and length are 13.54 YOY/hour and 6.76 inches. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY walleye for Green occurred in 1994 (54.00 YOY/hour, 6.15 inches average size). Walleye fingerlings (70,714 fish, 3,086 pounds), yearlings (840 fish, 253 pounds), and fry (2,220,806 fish) were stocked into Green during early April-November of 2010. Green Lake has been stocked annually with walleye fry (1-2 million) from 2000-2009 except for 2002. Various combinations of walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked yearly (2,000 - 4,000 pounds/year) since 2000 into Green Lake. During the 1990's, walleye fry were stocked in 1996 and larger walleye (fingerlings and adults) were stocked in 1994, 1992, 1990.

Rock bass numbers were moderately abundant in 2010 (8.33 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for Green Lake and similar lakes. The rock bass historical average catch rate is 7.67 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2010 rock bass average size was moderate (0.36 pounds and 7.48 inches) from gillnets. The rock bass historical average weight is 0.42 pounds from gillnets.

Largemouth bass numbers were abundant in 2010 (2.83 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green and similar lakes. The largemouth bass historical average catch rate is 0.65 fish/gillnet for Green. The 2010 largemouth bass average size was small (0.66 pounds and 9.68 inches) from gillnets. The largemouth bass historical average weight is 0.67 pounds from gillnets. Growth rates were generally below the normal ranges for ages 1-6. The 2008 largemouth bass year class comprised 36% of the 2010 largemouth bass assessment gillnet and trapnet catch.

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the 2011 fall for walleye natural reproduction, and 2011 summer for all fish species by assessment nets.

A standard survey of Green Lake was conducted during late July to early August of 2020. A targeted fall electrofishing survey was conducted on September 17, 2020 to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye abundance in Green Lake. A targeted fall gillnetting survey was conducted for Walleye (late September) in 2020. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets, and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass). A creel survey was conducted on Green Lake during 2019 summer and 2019-2020 winter.

Green is a large (5,561 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), highly developed (690 homes) and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is currently infested with invasive species such as Curly-leaf Pondweed, Eurasian Watermilfoil and Zebra Mussels. Green is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Smallmouth Bass, Black Crappie (recent years) and Bluegill. There are approximately 48 inlets that enter Green Lake. The Middle Fork Crow River is the largest inlet and enters Green along the north shore and exits along the east side eventually flowing into Calhoun Lake. The 2020 summer was dryer with normal temperatures. Water levels were low during 2020. Direct nutrient runoff into Green is primarily from highway runoff and residential sources, which include lake homes and the city of Spicer. There is also upstream agricultural row crop runoff that enters into the Middle Fork Crow River. There were marginal dissolved oxygen (>3 ppm) and temperature conditions (<74 F) for Tullibee survival at depths of 40-44 feet during 2020 survey. There were adequate dissolved oxygen and temperature conditions at depths of 20-30 feet during 2019 survey, 20-35 feet during the 2018 survey, 27-36 feet during the 2017 survey, and 40-60 feet during the 2016 survey. Submergent vegetation appeared less dense in 2019 than previous survey years. Emergent vegetation such as Hardstem Bulrush is abundant in the outlet bay. A moderate stand of bulrush is present along the southeast shore. Shoalwater substrates are mostly sand, gravel, rubble and boulder. Recent ice on dates were December 19, 2020; December 2, 2019; November 27, 2018; December 12, 2017; December 10, 2016; and December 27, 2015. Recent ice off dates were April 8, 2020; April 23, 2019; May 7, 2018; March 21, 2017; and March 22, 2016 for Green Lake.

The threats of present (Zebra Mussels, Eurasian Watermilfoil and Curly-leaf Pondweed) and potential exotic invasive species introductions (i.e. Starry Stonewort, Quagga Mussels, Spiny Water Flea, Faucet Snail, etc.) are of a major concern to local residents in Kandiyohi County. Climate change and invasive species effects have been noticeable for both habitat and species density changes in Green Lake during recent decades. Periphyton (filamentous algae, diatoms) and dead plant material now cover the boulder/rubble substrates generally all year long with the exception of some narrow (<1 foot deep) windswept near shore areas due to warmer waters and increased near shore nutrient deposition. This has favored warm water species (Black Crappie, Largemouth Bass, Bluegill, Rock Bass) which are nest spawners, unlike broadcast spawners such as Walleye and Tullibee "Cisco". Furthermore, increased densities of submergent vegetation species such as invasive Eurasian watermilfoil since 2000 have provided added habitat/cover for many warm water fish species. Eurasian watermilfoil has spread throughout the lake in scattered stands especially near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, storm water inlet areas and off shore "break" (10-15 feet deep) areas since 2000. It was more prevalent in water depths greater than 10 feet and less frequent in shallower water during 2018-2020. Zebra Mussels have decreased free open water green algal abundance resulting in lower densities of zooplankton, shifted energy and nutrient transfers from open water to bottom habitats, altered predator-prey relationships, decreased fish condition factors and also increased water clarity since 2014. Several other area lakes (Andrew, Diamond, Eagle, Elkhorn, George, Nest, Norway and Games) were recently reported as infested with Zebra Mussels in 2017-2018.

Black Crappie numbers were low in 2020 (0.58 fish/gillnet, 0.20 fish/trapnet). The Black Crappie historical average catch rates are 1.30 fish/gillnet and 0.78 fish/trapnet. The 2020 Black Crappie average sizes were large from gillnets (0.54 pounds and 9.62 inches) and trapnets (0.57 pounds and 10.08 inches). The Black Crappie historical average lengths are 8.00 inches for gillnets and 8.09 inches for trapnets in Green. The largest Black Crappie captured was 10.91 inches.

Bluegill numbers were moderate in 2020 (32.07 fish/trapnet). The Green Lake Bluegill historical average catch rate is 42.78 fish/trapnet. The 2020 Bluegill average size was small (0.09 pounds and 4.69 inches) from trapnets. The Bluegill historical average weight is 0.14 pounds from trapnets. The 2020 catch rate of quality size (6.00 inches and larger) Bluegill (5.87 fish/trapnet) was below the historical average (13.27 fish/trapnet). The largest Bluegill captured was 8.91 inches.

Largemouth Bass numbers were low in 2020 (0.42 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (0.87 fish/gillnet). The 2020 Largemouth Bass average size was large (1.48 pounds and 13.70 inches) from gillnets. The Largemouth Bass historical average weight is 0.73 pounds from gillnets. Largemouth Bass growth rates are slow in Green. The 2018 and 2013 year classes comprised 33% and 25% respectively of the 2020 Largemouth Bass summer survey catch.

Northern Pike numbers were high in 2020 (4.08 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (2.88 fish/gillnet). The 2020 Northern Pike average size was small (1.96 pounds and 20.24 inches) from gillnets. The Northern Pike historical average weight and length are 3.12 pounds and 23.25 inches from gillnets. The 2020 catch rate of preferred size (28.00 inches and larger) Northern Pike (0.25 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (0.46 fish/gillnet). The largest Northern Pike captured was 31.38 inches in 2020 survey. Northern Pike have been generally lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003 Low numbers of forage fish (Yellow Perch and Tullibee) have been documented in Green Lake surveys from 2003-2020. Northern Pike growth rates were generally slow for younger fish (ages 1-4), but near the normal ranges for older fish (ages 5-8). The 2018 and 2017 year classes comprised 44% and 26% of the 2020 Northern Pike summer catch. Northern Pike possession limit regulations for Green in the North-central Zone are as follows: anglers can keep 10 Northern Pike, but not more than two pike longer than 26 inches; and all from 22 to 26 inches must be released. Northern Pike taken by spearing follow the same rules except one pike may be between 22 and 26 inches or two larger than 26 inches.

Rock Bass numbers were abundant in 2020 (11.58 fish/gillnet). The Rock Bass historical average catch rate is 9.22 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2020 Rock Bass average size was large (0.60 pounds and 8.78 inches) from gillnets. The Rock Bass historical average weight is 0.42 pounds from gillnets.

Smallmouth Bass numbers were moderate in 2020 (1.42 fish/gillnet). The Smallmouth Bass historical average catch rate is 1.76 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2020 Smallmouth Bass size was large (2.27 pounds and 15.63 inches) from gillnets. The Smallmouth Bass historical average weight and length are 1.57 pounds and 13.44 inches from gillnets for Green Lake. The 2020 catch rate of preferred size (14.00 inches and larger) Smallmouth Bass was (1.08 fish/gillnet) was near the historical average (1.06 fish/gillnet). The largest Smallmouth Bass captured was 19.09 inches in the 2020 survey. Smallmouth Bass growth rates were slow in Green. There were no dominant Smallmouth Bass year classes in the summer gillnet catch.

Large sized Northern Crayfish, an important Smallmouth Bass forage species, have been present in low numbers since 1999. Moderate numbers of Northern Crayfish were captured in both 2020 (1.92 crayfish/gillnet) and 2019 (2.17 crayfish/gillnet) summer surveys. Low numbers (<1.00 crayfish/gillnet) or no Northern Crayfish were captured from 2002-2018 gillnets. The Northern Crayfish historical average catch rate is 5.08 crayfish/gillnet for Green. Research has identified Crayfish and Pumpkinseed Sunfish as predators on smaller Zebra Mussels. We did observe numerous small sized Northern Crayfish in the stomachs of Smallmouth Bass and Rock Bass. Northern Crayfish numbers may increase in the future due to a new forage species "Zebra Mussel" present in Green. In response, this may also provide a greater forage base "crayfish" for Smallmouth Bass.

Tullibee were not present in the 2017-2020 summer gillnet catches. The Tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 1.82 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. A November targeted gillnet survey was last conducted for Tullibee in 2019. Tullibee numbers were low in 2019 November survey (1.75 fish/gillnet, 13.92 inches). Tullibee numbers were low (0.50 fish/gillnet, 11.25 inches) in the previous 2017 November targeted survey. Tullibee abundance was higher in the 2012 (8.33 fish/gillnet, 13.61 inches) and 2015 (10.33 fish/gillnet, 13.66 inches) fall surveys. The fall Tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 67.43 fish/gillnet and 12.56 inches for Green Lake. Green Lake has not been opened for Tullibee public gillnetting since 2011 due to the low Tullibee numbers sampled in recent years. Tullibee are an important forage fish, especially for larger Northern Pike and Walleye in Green. Tullibee can also provide a secondary fishing opportunity during the winter months.

Yellow Perch numbers were low in 2020 (1.25 fish/gillnet). The Yellow Perch historical average catch rate is 11.43 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2020 Yellow Perch average size was moderate (0.13 pounds and 6.86 inches) from gillnets for Green Lake. The Yellow Perch historical average weight is 0.12 pounds from gillnets. Yellow Perch growth rates were slow in Green. The 2016 year class comprised 50% of the 2020 Yellow Perch summer survey catch.

Local anglers have reported in past years seeing numerous small Yellow Perch amongst the Chara "Muskgrass" beds with cameras during the summer or while spearing in the winter. Our standard gillnets may not effectively sample these small (<5.0 inches) Yellow Perch. Predation pressures from various species (i.e. Rock Bass, Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Walleye, etc.) may have also selected for smaller sized and earlier reproducing Yellow Perch restricted to near bottom habitat containing dense Chara beds in Green. A statewide study will examine Yellow Perch catchability, growth and maturity using small mesh gillnets in Green and other lakes in 2019 and the future.

Green Lake was stocked annually with Walleye fry (1-4 million) from 2000-2013 except for 2002. Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked Walleye fry (1-2 million) were stocked in Green each year during 2000-2001, 2007-2013, 2016, and 2018. Fry were marked with OTC to document the contribution to the Walleye population versus natural reproduction or fingerling stockings in later surveys. In 2020 fall, Green was stocked with Spicer Strain Walleye adults (76 pounds, 39 fish) and yearlings (3,411 pounds, 7,765 fish). Walleye yearlings (701 fish, 150 pounds) and adult (300 fish, 150 pounds) were stocked by private sources in 2019. Various combinations of Walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) from 2000-2017 into Green Lake.

Young of Year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye numbers due to natural reproduction were absent in the 2020 fall electrofishing survey. Low YOY Walleye numbers (<5.00 YOY/hour) were captured in 2013-2019 fall electrofishing surveys. Although, fall electrofishing survey techniques may be less effective for sampling YOY Walleye in large multi contoured lakes with high water clarity. Moderate YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2012 (12.00 YOY/hour, 6.87 inches) and 2011 (31.00 YOY/hour, 6.46 inches average length) fall electrofishing surveys. OTC marked fry captured as fingerlings comprised 40% of the 2013 and 55% of the 2012 fall electrofishing survey catches. OTC marked YOY Walleye (fry stocked) comprised 63.3% (19.62 YOY/hour) of the 2011 fall YOY Walleye survey catch.

Walleye numbers were low in 2020 summer gillnets (4.00 fish/gillnet). The Walleye historical average catch rate is 8.29 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. However, abundant Walleye numbers (8.25 fish/gillnet) were captured in the 2020 September gillnetting survey. The discrepancies between low summer and high fall gillnets catches is due in part to younger fish growing to larger sizes during late summer and early fall, which makes them more susceptible to capture in our fall gillnets. The 2020 Walleye average size was moderate (2.01 pounds and 17.42 inches) from the summer gillnets. The Walleye historical average weight and length are 1.32 pounds and 14.91 inches from summer gillnets. The 2020 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches and larger) Walleye (2.83 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (3.55 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. The largest Walleye captured was 27.17 inches in the 2020 summer survey. Walleye growth rates were slow in Green compared to other area lakes, but within the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-4. A variety of Walleye year classes were captured in the 2020 summer survey. Recent YOY Walleye catch rates from 5-30 fish per hour due to fry stockings or natural reproduction may be adequate for providing a moderate year class in larger or clearer lakes. Recent fry stockings (2013, 2016 and 2018) have contributed between 29% and 57% of the fish caught from fry stocked year classes during the 2020 summer survey. However, Zebra Mussels may negatively affect future Walleye fry stockings and natural reproduction by reducing zooplankton food availability, thus causing poor Walleye first year survival. Continued Walleye fingerling or yearling stockings may be necessary to maintain adequate Walleye numbers in Green. The new Walleye bag limit was reduced from six to three fish on Green Lake starting in 2021. Only 1 Walleye over 20 inches is allowed.

Other species captured included low numbers of White Sucker (0.67 fish/gillnet), Common Carp (0.27 fish/trapnet), Pumpkinseed (0.13 fish/trapnet), Hybrid Sunfish (3.87 fish/trapnet) and Black Bullhead (0.33 fish/gillnet) during 2020. Moderate numbers of large Yellow Bullhead were also captured in 2020 (2.33 fish/gillnet, 0.82 pounds average weight).

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking Walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the fall of 2021 for YOY Walleye abundance, 2022 fall for Tullibee and the summer of 2021 for all fish species by standard survey nets.

A standard survey in Green Lake was conducted during mid-September of 2023 using lake survey gillnets and trapnets. Standard surveys were done during the last week of July or first week of August prior to 2021. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass). Standard surveys have been conducted during or after the fall turnover since 2021. We set 12 gillnets at standard summer stations during mid-September of 2023. A thermocline still existed at the start of the 2023 September survey between 35-45 feet depth. The surface temperature was 71 F with dissolved oxygen of 7.9 ppm. Dissolved oxygen was at least 5.0 ppm down to 35 feet deep. The water temperatures were between 62-57 F and <1.0 ppm dissolved oxygen at depths greater than 45 feet deep. A temperature oxygen profile was also taken on July 28, 2023. Adequate temperatures (<74 F) and dissolved oxygen (>3 ppm) were present for Tullibee survival at depths of 20-40 feet deep during the critical late July and early August time period in Green Lake. Summer temperature and oxygen conditions were more conducive for Tullibee survival during 2013-2019. The month of June had warmer air temperatures (up to 90 F) and drier (< 2 inches of rain) than normal conditions during 2020-2022. July air temperatures were below or near normal during those same years. The 2023 summer was warmer and drier than normal especially for June, but no tullibee summerkills were observed in Green or Koronis. The secchi reading was 10.0 feet during the mid-September survey and 8.0 feet during late July of 2023. Total phosphorus was low (0.018 ppm) on September 11, 2023. A fall night electrofishing survey was conducted on October 8, 2023 to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye abundance in Green Lake. A targeted Tullibee gillnetting survey was conducted in late November of 2023. A creel survey was last conducted on Green Lake during the 2019 summer and 2019-2020 winter.

Green is a large (5,561 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), highly developed (690 homes) and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is currently infested with invasive species such as Curly-leaf Pondweed, Eurasian Watermilfoil (2000) and Zebra Mussels (2014). Green is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Smallmouth Bass, Black Crappie (recent years) and Bluegill. There are approximately 48 inlets that enter Green Lake. The Middle Fork Crow River is the largest inlet and enters Green along the north shore and exits along the east side eventually flowing into Calhoun Lake. Water levels were low during 2020-2023. Direct nutrient runoff into Green is primarily from highway runoff and residential sources, which include lake homes and the city of Spicer. There is also upstream agricultural row crop runoff that enters the Middle Fork Crow River. Submergent vegetation appeared less dense from 2021-2023 than previous survey years. Emergent vegetation such as Hardstem Bulrush is abundant in the outlet bay. A moderate stand of bulrush is present along the southeast shore. Zebra mussels were abundant on shoalwater substrates such as rubble and boulder throughout the littoral areas. Zebra Mussels have decreased free open water green algal abundance. This has resulted in lower densities of zooplankton, shifted energy and nutrient transfers from open water to bottom habitats, altered predator-prey relationships, decreased some fish species condition factors, and increased water clarity since 2014. Several other area lakes (Andrew, Diamond, Eagle, Elkhorn, George, Nest, Norway, and Games) were recently reported as infested with Zebra Mussels during 2017-2018.

Black Crappie trapnet catch rate was high (5.73 fish/trapnet), but low in the gillnets (0.25 fish/gillnet) during the 2023 fall standard survey. The historical average catch rate is 0.97 fish/trapnet. The 2023 Black Crappie average sizes were large for fall gillnets (0.97 pounds and 11.22 inches), but moderate for fall trapnets (0.50 pounds and 9.48 inches). The historical average lengths are 8.11 inches and 8.22 inches respectively from gillnets and trapnets. The 2023 Black Crappie catch rate of preferred size (10.00 inches plus) was moderate (1.33 fish/trapnet). The largest Black Crappie captured was 13.39 inches in the 2023 survey.

Bluegill trapnet catch rate (47.80 fish/trapnet) was similar to the historical average (45.01 fish/trapnet) in the 2023 fall standard survey. Bluegill average size was small (0.12 pounds and 5.34 inches) from trapnets. The historical average length is 5.48 inches from trapnets. The largest Bluegill captured was 8.31 inches. The 2023 Bluegill catch rate of quality size (6.00 inches plus) was low (8.81 fish/trapnet). The 2023 Bluegill catch rate of preferred size (8.00 inches plus) was also low (0.07 fish/trapnet).

Largemouth Bass gillnet catch rate (0.42 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (0.83 fish/gillnet) in the 2023 fall standard survey. The 2023 Largemouth Bass gillnet average size was moderate (1.48 pounds and 13.09 inches). Moderate numbers of small sized Largemouth Bass (1.53 fish/trapnet, 6.71 inches average) were captured in the 2023 fall trapnets. The Largemouth Bass historical average trapnet catch is 0.51 fish/trapnet. The historical average lengths are 10.54 inches and 8.86 inches respectively from gillnets and trapnets. The largest Largemouth Bass captured was 16.54 inches.

Northern Pike gillnet catch rate (2.17 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (2.83 fish/gillnet) in the 2023 fall standard survey. The 2023 Northern Pike average size was moderate (2.83 pounds and 23.07 inches). The historical average length is 23.17 inches. The 2023 Northern Pike catch rate of preferred size (28.00 inches plus) was low (0.25 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (0.43 fish/gillnet). The largest Northern Pike captured was 33.86 inches. Northern Pike possession limit regulations for Green in the North-central Zone are as follows: anglers can keep 10 Northern Pike, but not more than two pike longer than 26.0 inches; and all from 22.0 to 26.0 inches must be released. Northern Pike taken by spearing follow the same rules except one pike may be between 22.0 and 26.0 inches or two larger than 26.0 inches.

Rock Bass gillnet catch rate (6.00 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (9.09 fish/gillnet) in the 2023 fall standard survey. The 2023 Rock Bass gillnet average size was moderate (0.38 pounds and 7.23 inches). The historical average length is 7.77 inches.

Smallmouth Bass gillnet catch rate (1.75 fish/gillnet) was the same as the historical average in the 2023 fall standard survey. The 2023 Smallmouth Bass gillnet average size was moderate (0.85 pounds and 10.80 inches). The historical average length is 13.18 inches. The 2023 Smallmouth Bass fall catch rate of preferred size (14.00 inches plus) was moderate (0.42 fish/gillnet), but below the historical average (1.00 fish/gillnet). The largest Smallmouth Bass captured was 19.37 inches.

Northern Crayfish (important prey species for Smallmouth Bass) numbers were high during the 2023 (10.58 crayfish/gillnet), 2022 (20.50 crayfish/gillnet) and 2021 (16.58 crayfish/gillnet) fall surveys compared to previous surveys from 2002-2020 (<3.00 crayfish/gillnet). Zebra Mussels are an important forage prey for Northern Crayfish. Zebra Mussels may cause a shift to greater numbers of benthic species such as Northern Crayfish and Yellow Perch which would be beneficial to Smallmouth Bass.

Tullibee gillnet catch rate was low (0.67 fish/gillnet) in the 2023 fall standard survey. Tullibee numbers were also low in 2022 (0.08 fish/gillnet) and 2021 (0.17 fish/gillnet) fall standard surveys. Tullibee were absent in the 2020 September and summer gillnet catches. The Tullibee historical average standard survey catch rate is 1.70 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. Tullibee numbers were also low in the 2023 November Tullibee survey (4.00 fish/gillnet, 10.77 inches). The Tullibee average size was small (0.32 pounds and 9.65 inches) in the 2023 fall standard survey. The Tullibee historical average length is 10.67 inches. Tullibee growth rates were within the Green Lake normal ranges. The 2022 year class comprised 50% of the 2023 fall standard survey. Tullibee growth rates were within the Green Lake normal ranges.

Yellow Perch gillnet catch rate was low (5.33 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (10.83 fish/gillnet) in the 2023 fall standard survey. However, the 2023 gillnet catch rate was the highest recorded value since 2006. The 2023 Yellow Perch average size (0.13 pounds and 6.59 inches) was above the historical average size (0.11 pounds and 6.46 inches). The 2023 fall Yellow Perch catch rate of quality size (8.00 inches plus) was low (0.17 fish/gillnet). The largest Yellow Perch captured was 8.98 inches.

Walleye fry have been stocked into Green with mostly Spicer and Pike River strains of varied amounts (0.5 to 2.5 million fish) from 2000-2013. Approximately 1 million Spicer strain fry were most recently stocked in 2016 and 2018. Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked fry were stocked in Green during 2000-2013, 2016 and 2018. Various combinations of Walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults were stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) from 2000-2017 into Green Lake. Pike River was the primary Walleye fingerling strain that was available and stocked into Green from 2000-2014. Spicer Area Walleye fingerling rearing ponds have been stocked with primarily the Spicer strain since 2015. Both Unmarked Spicer and Pike River Walleye strains were stocked into Green during 2015 (36,723 fingerlings, 2,497 pounds; 1,400 yearlings, 560 pounds). Unmarked Spicer strain fingerlings and yearlings were stocked into Green during the 2016 fall (26,365 fingerlings, 1,647 pounds; 4,641 yearlings, 828 pounds). Green Lake was stocked with Spicer strain fin clipped (right ventral) age 3+ adults (196 pounds, 192 fish) and ages 1+ fish (2,081 pounds, 3,936 fish) in the 2017 fall. Spicer strain (1,173 pounds, 16,064 fish) and Pike River strain (117 pounds, 936 fish) fingerlings were also stocked in the 2017 fall. Fin clipped (left ventral) Walleye yearlings (701 fish, 150 pounds) and adults (300 fish, 150 pounds) were stocked by private sources in 2019. In 2020 fall, Green was stocked with Spicer strain fin clipped Walleye adults (76 pounds, 39 fish) and yearlings (3,411 pounds, 7,765 fish). Green was stocked with 2,500 Spicer strain fin clipped (right ventral) Walleye (1,050 pounds) after the 2021 fall standard survey. Adults and yearlings comprised 1,844 fish (911 pounds) of the 2021 stocking. Fingerlings comprised 656 fish (139 pounds) of the 2021 stocking. In October of 2022, Walleye stocked (right ventral fin clipped) included adults (115 fish, 172 pounds), yearlings (342 fish, 145 pounds) and fingerlings (425 fish, 104 pounds). Walleye adults (109 fish, 115 pounds) and yearlings (341 fish, 149.5 pounds) were fin clipped (left ventral) and stocked during the 2023 fall.

Moderate YOY Walleye numbers (23.40 YOY/hour, 5.13 inches) due to natural reproduction were captured in 2023 fall night electrofishing survey. Yearling Walleye numbers were abundant (31.20 fish/hour, 7.51 inches) in the 2023 fall electrofishing survey. Growth was slow for the 2022 year class in 2023. YOY Walleye numbers were abundant (65.54 YOY/hour, 5.24 inches) due to natural reproduction in the 2022 fall electrofishing survey. The 2022 fall electrofishing survey had the highest historical recorded YOY Walleye catch rate for Green Lake. Young of Year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye numbers due to natural reproduction were moderate (10.50 YOY/hour, 7.39 inches) in 2021. YOY Walleye were absent in the 2020 fall electrofishing survey. Low YOY Walleye numbers (<5.00 YOY/hour) were captured in 2013-2019 fall electrofishing surveys. Although, fall electrofishing survey techniques may be less effective for sampling YOY Walleye in large multi contoured lakes with high water clarity. Moderate YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2012 (12.00 YOY/hour, 6.87 inches) and 2011 (31.00 YOY/hour, 6.46 inches average length) fall electrofishing surveys. OTC marked fry captured as fingerlings comprised 40% of the 2013 and 55% of the 2012 fall electrofishing survey catches. OTC marked YOY Walleye (fry stocked) comprised 63.3% (19.62 YOY/hour) of the 2011 fall YOY Walleye survey catch.

Walleye gillnet catch rate (10.17 fish/gillnet) was above the historical average (8.26 fish/gillnet) in the 2023 fall standard survey. The 2023 Walleye average size was moderate (1.59 pounds and 15.46 inches). The historical average length is 14.99 inches. The 2023 Walleye catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches plus) was high (5.58 fish/gillnet) and above the historical average (3.64 fish/gillnet). The 2023 Walleye fall catch rate of preferred size (20.00 inches plus) was moderate (1.83 fish/gillnet). The largest Walleye captured was 27.36 inches. Walleye growth rates were good for ages 1-4, but slow for ages 5-8. Recent Walleye year classes have been due mostly to stocking since 2001. The 2023 Walleye fall standard survey catch was comprised primarily of 2019 (37%), 2021 (27%) and 2022 (26%) year classes. Approximately 27% of 2019 Walleye year class (age 4) were stocked fin clipped fish in the 2023 Walleye fall survey catch. Zebra Mussels may negatively affect future Walleye fry stockings or natural reproduction/recruitment by reducing zooplankton food availability, thus causing poor survivability or growth. However, if benthic forage species such as Yellow Perch begin to rebound then yearling/adult Walleye recruitment and growth may also respond positively. It is encouraging that good Walleye natural reproduction success was documented in 2022 and 2023. If fingerling recruitment to adult size is poor, then continued Walleye yearling stockings may be necessary to maintain adequate Walleye numbers in Green. The new Walleye bag limit was reduced from six to three fish on Green Lake in 2021. Only 1 Walleye over 20 inches is allowed.

Other species captured during the 2023 fall standard survey included low numbers of White Sucker (0.17 fish/gillnet), Common Carp (0.40 fish/trapnet), Hybrid Sunfish (3.67 fish/trapnet) and Bigmouth Buffalo (0.07 fish/trapnet). Abundant numbers of moderate sized Yellow Bullhead (12.00 fish/gillnet, 0.79 pounds) were captured in the 2023 fall standard survey.

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking Walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the fall of 2024 for YOY Walleye abundance, and mid-September of 2024 for all fish species by standard survey nets. Tullibee will be sampled by vertical gillnetting and hydroacoustic methods in June of 2024, and November gillnetting in 2025 for both Green and Koronis.

Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (maximum depth 110 feet), lake located near Spicer,MN in Kandiyohi County. Green has excellent water quality (good clarity, low levels ofnutrients) compared to most other lakes in Kandiyohi County. The Middle Fork of the CrowRiver (MFCR) inlet via Mud Lake (34-158) and Nest Lake (34-0154) is a constant source ofmoderate nutrient loading to Green Lake. So far Green has been able to assimilate incomingnutrients without any appreciable increase in productivity. Green is heavily developed with663 homes, several resorts/motels/bed&breakfasts, several condominiums/apartment buildings,a bible camp, county park, city park, and the city of Spicer along the southwest shoreline.Structure is varied on Green with several long shallow bars (Hultgren's, Lone Tree, Grate's,Castle Flats) located in the lake. Emergent vegetation (primarily hardstem bulrush and commoncattail) are restricted to the outlet area and a small stand near the "Spicer Castle" alongthe south shore. There is a variety of submergent vegetation species, but the density islight throughout most of the lake with the exception of the outlet bay area. Green Lake hasbeen intensively stocked with a variety of species, densities, and frequencies over theyears. Smallmouth bass were introduced in the early 1940's. Cisco "tullibee" were thought tobe introduced into Green during the late 1800's. In the last ten years, stocking efforts havebeen devoted mostly to walleye. Presently, walleye are stocked (about 2000 lbs) every evenyear. Fall electrofishing surveys have been conducted since 1993 to assess the contributionsof natural reproduction and stocking to the walleye fishery in Green. Green is a popular lakefor walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegill angling. In addition, tullibeegillnetting is allowed for a two-three week period in mid to late November. In recent years,Green has been intensively surveyed to provide a better data base for developing future longterm management goals and objectives. Furthermore, experimental fishing regulations areplanned to be implemented in 1997 for developing trophy northern pike and smallmouth bassopportunities. Walleye abundance in 1994 (9.6 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range for similarlakes, but slightly above the historical average of 8.2 fish/gillnet. The 1994 average size(15.4 inches, 1.4 lbs) was above the historical average (14.5 inches, 1.3 lbs). The walleyepopulation size structure and abundance has been fairly constant over the past ten years.Significant natural reproduction was documented in 1993 (46.0 fingerlings/hour) and in 1994(52.7 YOY/hour). The 1994 stocked fingerlings accounted only 2.4% (1.3 fingerlings/hour) ofthe total fingerling production in Green during 1994 (natural and stocked= 54.0fingerlings/hour). It appears that stocking contributes minimally to the walleye populationduring years when good natural reproduction occurs. Northern pike abundance in 1994 (1.8 fish/gillnet) was below the normal range forsimilar lakes and below the historical average (2.7 fish/gillnet). The largest fish capturedin the summer survey was 31.6 inches. The average size in 1994 (21.3 inches, 2.8 lbs) wassimilar to the historical average (21.7 inches, 2.6 lbs.). Spawning runs occur in severalinlet marshes (Alvig Slough, East Woodcock Lake), and also a large run at the outlet marsharea. Spring monitoring of the northern pike spawning runs have occurred in 1994 and 1995 toprovide information for the evaluation of upcoming northern pike experimental regulationsstudy. Yellow perch abundance in 1994 (23.6 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range forsimilar lakes and comparable to the historical average (20.2 fish/gillnet). The average sizein 1994 (6.5 inches) was similar to the historical average (6.4 inches). Cisco "tullibee" abundance in 1994 summer survey (3.6 fish/gillnet) was within thenormal range for similar lakes and comparable to the historical average (4.0 fish/gillnet).Abundance was down in 1994 compared to 1993 (10.2 fish/gillnet). The average size in 1994(9.2 inches) was slightly below the historical average (9.4 inches). Smallmouth bass abundance in the 1994 spring electrofishing survey (13.7 fish/hour) wasabove the historical average (12.5 fish/hour) and above the 1993 spring survey (1.9fish/hour). Low spring electrofishing catch rates in 1993 were probably due to poor shockingconditions (high winds, precipitation, higher water levels). The average size caught in the1994 spring electrofishing survey was 12.1 inches. The largest smallmouth bass caught was18.7 inches during the summer survey.
