Largemouth bass spring electrofishing catch rate in 1994 was 1.0 fish/hour. Previouselectrofishing catch rates include 1.9 fish/hour in 1993, 8.0 fish/hour in 1991, and 57.7fish/hour in 1990. The average size was 11.3 inches in 1994. Rock bass abundance in 1994 (8.4 fish/gillnet) was above the normal range for similarlakes and above the historical average (6.8 fish/gillnet). The average size in 1994 (8.5inches, 0.5 lbs) was slightly above the historical average (8.1 inches and 0.4 lbs). Black crappie abundance in 1994 (0.1 fish/gillnet, 0.0 fish/trapnet) was below thenormal range and below the historical average (0.8 fish/gillnet, 0.6 fish/trapnet). Blackcrappie populations throughout most of Kandiyohi County have been low in recent years. Bluegill abundance in 1994 (84.6 fish/trapnet) was above the normal range for similarlakes and above the historical average (66.3 fish/trapnet). The average size in 1994 (5.4inches) was above the historical average (4.9 inches). It appears that the average size hasincreased slightly from 1993 (average size=4.7 inches). Important bluegill habitat includebulrush stands on the south shore (Spicer Castle) and the northeast outlet bay area. Green is a challenging lake to fish, but fishing deep water near structure (shallowbars, reefs) is the key for catching larger walleye during the day. Also, walleye anglershave good success trolling the shallow flats in 8-10 ft of water during June and July.Anglers generally have good success for bluegill in the outlet bay area. Smallmouth bassanglers usually have success near Grate's Bar, Hultgren's Bar, Lone Tree Bar, and thenortheast portion of Green. Northern pike anglers have good success near the Castle Flats,Peck's Bar, and the northwest portion of the lake. Green has the habitat, water quality, andforage base to potentially produce trophy northern pike and smallmouth bass. In the past,abundant crayfish populations have been important forage for producing smallmouth bass. Otherabundant forage (cisco, yellow perch) have the potential to produce trophy northern pike. In addition, there usually is a cool, oxygenated layer present when the lake stratifies inmid summer which is conducive for producing trophy northern pike. A statewide experimentalregulation study for various species will include Green Lake. Experimental regulations willbe proposed for smallmouth bass and northern pike by the beginning of 1997 fishing opener.Related experimental regulations study activities include upcoming creel surveys in 1995-1996, annual spring bass electrofishing, and annual northern pike spawning run assessment.In addition, ice out trapnetting and tagging of walleye will be conducted to get moreinformation about population size and angler exploitation in conjunction with the creelsurveys being conducted. Other priority management activities will include protecting presentwater quality, protecting and expanding existing stands of hardstem bulrush, maintainingaccess to inlet and outlet marshes for northern pike spawning, yearly evaluation of ciscopopulation through fall gillnetting, and yearly evaluation of walleye natural reproductionthrough fall electrofishing. Walleye fingerling stocking on Green should only be consideredafter successive years of poor natural reproduction as determined by fall electrofishing. Thebenefits of stocking as needed (successive years of poor natural reproduction) rather thanon a prescribed schedule (stocking every even year) is that the valuable walleye fingerlingresource can be used more efficiently and effectively (higher rates) for other lakes.Furthermore, survival and growth of walleye in a lake may decrease when stocking occurs ontop of good natural reproduction due to more competition for limited resources (forage,habitat, etc.).

Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (maximum depth 110 feet), mesotrophic lake locatednear Spicer, MN in Kandiyohi County. The littoral area comprises 38% of the total surfacearea. Green has excellent water quality compared to most other lakes in Kandiyohi County.Water clarity is excellent (historical average secchi=9 ft). Nutrient levels are low (totalphosphorous=0.015 on 6/13/94). The Middle Fork of the Crow River (MFCR) inlet via Mud Lake(34-158) and Nest Lake (34-0154) is a constant source of moderate nutrient loading to GreenLake. So far Green has been able to assimilate incoming nutrients without any appreciableincrease in trophic status. In addition to MFCR, there are seven other inlets of which allbut one connect to shallow permanent lakes/marshes. The outlet (MFCR) is located on thenortheast side of the lake and connects to Calhoun Lake (34-0062) via a marsh. The immediatewatershed types are primarily municipal (residential homes), mixed hardwoods, and marshlands.Green is heavily developed with 663 homes, several resorts/motels/bed&breakfasts, severalcondominiums/apartment buildings, bible camp, county park, city park, and the city of Spiceralong the southwest shoreline. Only a small portion of the lake near the outlet isundeveloped. Shoalwater substrates are dominated by sand and gravel throughout most of thelake with boulder and rubble common along several long shallow bars (Grate's, Hultgren's) andadjacent shoreline areas. Marl and silt are common in the outlet bay area. Emergentvegetation (primarily hardstem bulrush with some common cattail, cane, and reed canary grass)is restricted to the outlet area and a small stand near the "Spicer Castle" along the southshore. There is a variety of submergent vegetation species, but the density is lightthroughout most of the lake with the exception of the outlet bay area. Water controlstructures affecting Green Lake water levels include the MFCR/Mud Lake Reservoir Dam at NewLondon, a stoplog dam at the MFCR inlet to Green Lake, a Type C with stoplogs south ofCalhoun, and a Type C solid sill at the Calhoun outlet. Green Lake has been stocked with avariety of species and densities over the years. Smallmouth bass were introduced in the early1940's. Tullibee "cisco" were thought to be introduced into Green during the late 1800's. Inthe last ten years, stocking efforts have been devoted mostly to walleye. Historically,rescue operations have been common in adjacent connected winterkill lakes/marshes fornorthern pike. Prior to 1991, walleye were stocked almost every year. The current lakemanagement plan is to stock walleye (about 2000 lbs) only after two consecutive poor naturalyear classes documented by fall electrofishing. Fall electrofishing surveys have beenconducted since 1993 to assess the contributions of natural reproduction and stocking to thewalleye fishery in Green. Commercial removal has been limited in the last ten years to carp(16,160 lbs) and suckers (2,900 lbs). About 111 lbs of tullibee were removed by state crewsfor an initial stocking at an East Metro Fisheries Area lake. In 1989, 310 northern pike wereremoved by state crews for stocking local northern pike spawning areas (NPSA). Walleye eggs(90,000 to 28,000,000 per take) were removed by state crews for fingerling production in1971, 1978-80, 1986, and 1996 during years when eggs were not available from traditional eggtake stations. Green was stocked with 10% of the hatched walleye fry in 1996 from the GreenLake egg take. Green is a popular lake for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, andbluegill angling. In addition, tullibee gillnetting is allowed for a two-three week periodin mid to late November. In recent years, Green has been intensively sampled (consecutivelake surveys since 1989, spring electrofishing surveys for smallmouth and largemouth bass,fall electrofishing surveys for YOY/Yearling walleye, creel surveys in 1995 and 1996, springnorthern pike assessment, ice out walleye trapnetting, fall cisco gillnetting) to provide abetter data base for developing future long term management goals and objectives.Furthermore, experimental fishing regulations (24 inch maximum size for northern pike, catchand release fishing only for smallmouth and largemouth bass) will be implemented in May of1997 for developing trophy northern pike and smallmouth bass opportunities. Walleye abundance in the 1996 summer survey (12.1 fish/gillnet) was above the 1st and3rd median interquartile range (4.0 - 9.6 fish/gillnet) for Lake Class 22, and slightly abovethe historical average (8.8 fish/gillnet). The walleye population size was determined in 1995by marking 573 walleye (12 inches or greater captured during ice out trapnetting) withDennison tags. Walleye caught by anglers were inspected for marks during the 1995 summer(1,596 fish observed, 14 recaptures) and 1995-96 winter (328 fish observed, 5 recapture)creel surveys. A simple Petersen estimate of the walleye population (fish > 12 inches) was58,024 fish (37,245 - 95,865 fish, 95% confidence limits) with an annual fishing mortalityrate of 34% (19,759 fish harvested) from the combined 1995 summer (fish > 12 inches) and1995-96 winter (fish > 14 inches) creels (Coahran, D.A. 1996. Green Lake (Lake CalhounIncluded) Creel Survey, Summer of 1995 and Winter of 1995-96, Statewide ExperimentalRegulations Project, MNDNR, Section of Fisheries.). The 1996 average size (0.9 lbs fromgillnets) was below the historical average (1.3 lbs). The largest walleye captured in the1996 summer survey was 27.0 inches. The 1996 summer PSD and RSD-P was 20.5 and 4.6 (fromgillnets and trapnets) respectively. The historical average PSD and RSD-P was 49.6 and 9.0respectively. The catch rate of quality size plus (> or = 15 inches) walleye in the 1996summer survey (2.6 fish/net, gillnets and trapnets combined) was below the historical average(4.4 fish/net). Growth rates appear slightly below average for ages II-III and VIII-XIcompared to other area lakes. Fall electrofishing surveys have been conducted since 1993 todocument young of year "YOY" walleye abundance due to natural reproduction in Green Lake. The1996 YOY walleye abundance from fall night electrofishing (33.0 YOY/hour) was within the 1stand 3rd median interquartile range (10.9 - 55.6 YOY/hour) for area lakes with potentialnatural reproduction (Table 1.). The overall median YOY catch rate for Green Lake is 39.5YOY/hour. The 1996 YOY average size (5.9 inches) was slightly below the Green Lake historicalaverage (6.2 inches), and below the overall average (6.8 inches) for lakes with naturalreproduction (Table 2.). The 1996 yearling walleye catch rate from fall electrofishing (28.0fish/hour) was similar to the Green Lake historical average (24.7 fish/hour), but above theoverall average (13.8 fish/hour) for area lakes (Table 3.). The 1996 yearling average size(8.7 inches) was below the Green Lake historical average (9.2 inches), and below the overallaverage (10.6 inches) for area lakes (Table 4.). Northern pike abundance in 1996 (3.7 fish/gillnet) was within the 1st and 3rd medianinterquartile range (3.0 - 7.9 fish/gillnet) for Lake Class 22, but slightly above thehistorical average (2.8 fish/gillnet). Northern pike (600 fish, size range=11.5 - 35.8inches) were tagged with Dennison tags at several inlet spawning marsh sites in the springof 1995. Northern pike were observed for tags during the 1995 open water creel survey (123fish observed, 4 tagged fish) and the 1995-96 winter creel survey (142 fish observed, 2tagged fish). The northern pike population in Green Lake was estimated at 26,500 fish (7,557- 72,273 at 95% confidence limits) from a 1995 simple Petersen population estimate (Coahran1996). It is our opinion that this northern pike population size is an over estimate due topotential loss of fish or delay of fish returning from spawning areas. It was observed thatnorthern pike were being harvested by shore anglers at the East Woodcock spawning marsh fromthe May opener to early June of 1997. The 1996 average size (2.9 lbs from gillnets) was abovethe historical average (2.6 lbs). The largest northern pike captured in the 1996 survey was36.6 inches. The 1996 PSD and RSD-P (56.3 and 10.4 from gillnets and trapnets) were similarto the historical averages (57.1 and 11.5 respectively). Growth rates appear slightly aboveaverage compared to other local lakes. There are several significant natural spawning runsthat occur into marsh areas adjacent to Green Lake (outlet marsh area, East Woodcock inletmarsh area, and Alvig Slough area). The 1996 YOY northern pike abundance (3.0 YOY/hour) fromfall night electrofishing was above the Green Lake historical average (1.3 YOY/hour) andabove the overall average (2.0 YOY/hour) for area lakes (Table 5.). The 1996 YOY average size(10.1 inches) was below the overall average (10.9 inches) for area lakes (Table 6.). GreenLake has been noted as a trophy northern pike fishery in the past. Abundant tullibee "cisco"within Green provides an excellent forage base for producing trophy northern pike. Theexperimental regulation concerning northern pike in Green Lake will require that all northernpike 24 inches or greater in length are to be immediately released into Green Lake and thepossession limit remains unchanged at 3 northern pike. This experimental regulation isintended to increase the number of 6 - 15 lb northern pike within Green Lake. Theeffectiveness of this regulation will be evaluated eight years from implementation. Smallmouth bass abundance in the 1996 spring electrofishing survey (18.8 fish/hour) wasabove the historical average (12.2 fish/hour). The 1996 spring electrofishing average weight(1.0 lbs) was slightly below the historical average (1.2 lbs.). The 1996 spring averagelength (11.7 inches) was slightly below the historical average (12.4 inches). The largestsmallmouth bass captured during the spring survey was 19.7 inches. The 1996 spring PSD andRSD-P was 53.1 and 22.4 respectively. The historical spring PSD and RSD-P was 67.7 and 30.2respectively. The 1996 spring catch rate of preferred size (> 14 inches) smallmouth bass (4.1fish/hour) was slightly above the historical catch rate (3.4 fish/hour). Growth rates appearaverage for smallmouth bass compared to other area lakes. About 38% of the fish captured inthe spring survey belonged to the 1994 year class. An experimental regulation will go intoeffect on the bass opener on May 31, 1997 for both smallmouth and largemouth bass on GreenLake. The regulation will require the immediate release of all smallmouth and largemouth basscaught in Green Lake. No possession (on person or in the vehicle) of bass is allowed whilefishing in or on Green Lake. This regulation is intended to increase the number of 3-5 lbbass within the lake. The effectiveness of this regulation will be evaluated eight years fromimplementation. Largemouth bass abundance in the 1996 spring electrofishing survey (3.4 fish/hour) wasabove the last three surveys (< 2.0 fish/hour from 1993-1995), but below the historicalaverage (12.0 fish/hour). The 1996 spring largemouth bass average size (8.5 inches) was belowthe historical average (10.7 inches). The largest largemouth bass captured during the springsurvey was 13.0 inches. The 1996 spring PSD and RSD-P was 20.0 and 0 respectively. Growthrates appear average for largemouth bass compared to other area lakes. About 89% of the fishcaptured in the spring survey belonged to the 1994 year class. Yellow perch abundance in 1996 (17.6 fish/gillnet) was within the 1st and 3rd medianinterquartile range (7.1 - 33.9 fish/gillnet) for Lake Class 22, and similar to thehistorical average (20.2 fish/gillnet). The 1996 average size (6.8 inches from gillnets andtrapnets) was slightly above the historical average (6.4 inches). The 1996 PSD and RSD-P(from gillnets and trapnets) was 20.0 and 1.9 respectively. Growth rates appear average foryellow perch compared to other area lakes. Tullibee "cisco" abundance in the summer gillnets (0.6 fish/gillnet) was within the 1stand 3rd median interquartile range (0.5 - 5.2 fish/gillnet) for Lake Class 22, but below thehistorical average (4.0 fish/gillnet). The 1996 summer average size (0.5 lbs from gillnets)was similar to the historical average (0.4 lbs). A two-three week gillnetting season isopened each fall during mid November to allow harvest (personal use only) of tullibee fromGreen Lake. Bluegill abundance in 1996 (23.3 fish/trapnet) was within the 1st and 3rd medianinterquartile range (3.7 - 42.9 fish/trapnet) for Lake Class 22, but below the historicalaverage (59.1 fish/trapnet). The 1996 average size (6.1 inches from gillnets and trapnets)was above the historical average (5.0 inches). The largest bluegill captured in the 1996survey was 8.3 inches. The 1996 PSD and RSD-P (from gillnets and trapnets) was 57.9 and 0.6respectively. The historical PSD and RSD-P was 22.0 and 0.4 respectively. Growth rates appearaverage compared to other local lakes. There were reports of good angler success forbluegills during the 1996 open water season. Rock bass abundance in 1996 (3.4 fish/gillnet) was within the 1st and 3rd medianinterquartile range (1.0 - 6.6 fish/gillnet) for Lake Class 22, but below the historicalaverage (6.0 fish/gillnet). The 1996 average size (8.1 inches from gillnets and trapnets) wassimilar to the historical average (7.9 inches). Black crappie abundance in 1996 (1.7 fish/trapnet) was within the 1st and 3rd medianinterquartile range (0.3 - 1.7 fish/trapnet) for Lake Class 22, but above the historicalaverage (0.7 fish/trapnet). The highest documented black crappie abundance occurred in 1991(2.2 fish/trapnet). The 1996 average size (7.4 inches from gillnets and trapnets combined)was similar to the historical average (7.9 inches). Black crappie growth rates appear belowaverage for age III compared to other area lakes. Numerous black crappie were harvestedduring the open water creel survey on Green in 1982 (9,185 fish) and 1983 (2,644 fish) eventhough the 1982 summer survey catch rate was low (1.1 fish/trapnet) compared to other locallakes. The 1995 estimated open water creel harvest was only 10 black crappie. The walleye population abundance has been fairly stable during the last fifteen years,however the average size slightly decreased in 1996. Walleye management will continue to bea high priority even though additional effort has been put on trophy northern pike andsmallmouth bass management. Green has the habitat, water quality, and forage base topotentially produce trophy northern pike and smallmouth bass. In the past, abundant crayfishpopulations have been important forage for producing smallmouth bass. Other abundant forage(cisco, yellow perch) have the potential to produce trophy northern pike. In addition, thereusually is a cool, oxygenated layer present when the lake stratifies in mid summer (asevidence by the cisco population and relatively few summerkill events) which is conducive forproducing trophy northern pike. A statewide experimental regulation study for various speciesincludes Green Lake. Experimental regulations will be implemented for smallmouth bass andnorthern pike by the beginning of the 1997 fishing opener. Related experimental regulationsstudy activities include upcoming creel surveys in 2001-2002, annual spring basselectrofishing surveys, and annual northern pike spawning run assessment netting. Inaddition, ice out trapnetting and tagging of walleye will be conducted to get moreinformation about population size and angler exploitation in conjunction with the creelsurveys being conducted. Other priority management activities will include protecting presentwater quality by encouraging area landowners to practice best management practices(conservation tillage, planting buffer strips, wetland restoration, proper feedlot and manuremanagement, using low/no phosphorus lawn fertilizers, etc.), protecting and expandingexisting stands of hardstem bulrush, yearly assessment of cisco populations through fallgillnetting, and yearly evaluation of walleye natural reproduction through fallelectrofishing. Walleye fingerling stocking on Green will only be considered after twosuccessive years of poor natural reproduction as determined by fall electrofishing. Thebenefits of stocking as needed (two successive years of poor natural reproduction) ratherthan on a prescribed schedule (stocking every even year) is that the valuable walleyefingerling resource can be used more efficiently and effectively (potentially higher rates)for other lakes.

Green is a large, deep, moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Greenis a popular walleye, northern pike, bluegill, and smallmouth bass fishery. Local anglersreported good fishing success for catching walleye (1-2 lbs.) and smallmouth in 2000. Greenhas good quality walleye spawning habitat of abundant rock and gravel shoalwater areas. Fallelectrofishing surveys since 1997 have documented generally low walleye young of year "YOY"numbers due to natural reproduction, however moderate yearling walleye numbers weredocumented during ensuing fall electrofishing surveys. Experimental fishing regulations wereenacted during 1997 in order to increase the quality of size for northern pike and smallmouthbass in Green Lake. Initially, the bass experimental regulation allowed for catch and releasefishing only for both smallmouth bass and largemouth bass. The northern pike experimentalregulation prohibited the harvest of northern pike 24.0 inches or greater. In 2001, the bassregulation was changed to a maximum harvest length of 14 inches for both smallmouth andlargemouth bass. The bass regulation was modified due to booming high numbers of smallmouthpresent in Green and the perceived negative effects on the walleye population. Walleye were moderately abundant in the 2000 summer assessment (9.92 fish/gillnet) and similar to the historical average (9.70 fish/gillnet). The 2000 walleye average size wasmoderate (1.40 lbs. and 15.49 inches, gillnets). The largest walleye captured in the 2000assessment nets was 25.83 inches. Walleye growth rates were below normal for ages 1-8compared to area lakes, but were similar to previous Green Lake surveys. Walleye fry werestocked into Green during 1996 and 2000 as a 10% return of walleye eggs taken from Green forthe 1996 and 2000 statewide hatching quotas. The 2000 spring walleye fry stocking (1.7million fry marked with oxytetracycline) was unsuccessful. Walleye natural reproduction wasalso poor in 2000. The 2000 YOY walleye abundance (11.33 YOY/hour) due to fry stockingand natural reproduction in the 2000 fall electrofishing survey was below the historicalaverage (24.26 fish/hour). The 2000 YOY walleye average length (6.13 inches) from the fallelectrofishing survey was small compared to the historical average (6.63 inches). Moderateyearling (1999 year class) walleye numbers were present in the 2000 fall electrofishingsurvey (13.33 fish/hour, 10.44 inches average size). The Spicer Fisheries Office stockedapproximately 100,000 walleye fingerlings into Green during October of 2000 in response tothe low YOY walleye numbers captured in the 2000 September electrofishing survey. Smallmouth bass were abundant in the 2000 summer assessment (3.58 fish/gillnet) comparedto the historical average (1.77 fish/gillnet). Smallmouth bass abundance was greater in 1999(9.00 fish/gillnet) than 2000. The 2000 smallmouth bass average size was moderate (1.51 lbs.and 13.58 inches, gillnets). The largest smallmouth bass captured in the 2000 assessment netswas 17.32 inches. The 1996 year class comprised 44% of the total 2000 gillnet and trapnetsmallmouth bass catch. Growth rates appeared good for smallmouth bass in Green Lake. Animportant smallmouth bass forage species, crayfish, was less numerous (3.2 crayfish/gillnet)in 2000 than previous surveys in Green Lake (20.6 crayfish/gillnet, historical average). Northern pike numbers were moderate in 2000 (3.83 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (3.01 fish/gillnet). The 2000 northern pike average size was also moderate(2.84 lbs. and 22.55 inches, gillnets), but above the historical average (21.55 inches). Thelargest northern pike captured in 2000 assessment nets was 37.20 inches. Growth rates werenormal or above normal for northern pike in Green compared to area lakes. The 1998 year classcomprised 66% of the total 2000 northern pike catch. Yellow perch abundance was low in 2000 (9.17 fish/gillnet) compared to the historicalaverage (21.08 fish/gillnet). The 2000 yellow perch average size was moderate (0.15 lbs. and6.93 inches, gillnets). Bluegill numbers were moderately abundant in 2000 (49.80 fish/trapnet) and nearlyidentical to the historical average (49.81 fish/trapnet). The 2000 bluegill average size wassmall (0.10 lbs and 4.87 inches, trapnets). Other fish species captured in the 2000 summer assessment nets included low numbers oftullibee "cisco" (0.42 fish/gillnet); moderate numbers of rock bass (5.50 fish/gillnet),hybrid sunfish (2.93 fish/trapnet), pumpkinseed sunfish (5.07 fish/trapnet), and blackcrappie compared to the Green Lake historical averages. The 2000 rock bass (0.58 lbs. and8.30 inches, gillnets) and pumpkinseed sunfish (0.28 lbs., 6.18 inches, trapnets) sizes weremoderate compared to previous surveys. The Green Lake fishery appears to be in good condition for walleye, northern pike,smallmouth bass numbers. Forage species (yellow perch, tullibee, crayfish) abundance waslower than the previous year in Green. Future walleye fingerling stocking may take place inGreen if consecutive poor natural year classes occur and the summer gillnet catches fallbelow target levels. The change in the smallmouth bass regulation should allow harvest ofnumerous smaller bass in the fishery, protect and improve numbers of quality (>14 inches) andpotential trophy size smallmouth bass, and limit potential competition with walleye in GreenLake. The DNR Spicer Fisheries Office will continue to monitor Green Lake fish populationnumbers through annual summer netting surveys, spring bass electrofishing surveys and ice outnorthern pike trapping every two years, and annual YOY walleye fall electrofishing surveysin order to evaluate the effectiveness of current management practices and experimentalregulations.

A resurvey of Green Lake was conducted during late July and early August of 2013. Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), highly developed (690 homes) and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, black crappie (recent years) and bluegill. There are approximately 48 inlets that enter Green Lake. The Middle Fork Crow River is the largest inlet and enters Green along the north shore and exits along the east side eventually flowing into Calhoun Lake. Direct nutrient runoff into Green is primarily from highway runoff and residential sources, which include lake homes and the city of Spicer. There is also upstream agricultural row crop runoff into the Middle Fork Crow River. Water levels were low during the 2012 fall, normal during the 2013 spring thru late-summer, but low by fall. Nutrient levels were relatively low during June of 2013 (total phosphorus=0.015 ppm, chlorophyll-a=6.3 ppb). Water clarity was moderate (11.0 feet) for Green Lake on August 1, 2013.

Climate change effects have been noticeable for both habitat and species density changes in Green Lake during recent decades. Periphyton (algae, diatoms) and dead plant material now cover the boulder/rubble substrates generally all year long with exception of some narrow (<1 foot deep) windswept near shore areas. This has favored warm water species (black crappie, bass, bluegill, rock bass) which are nest spawners, unlike broadcast spawners such walleye and tullibee. In addition, increased densities of submergent vegetation such as invasive Eurasian watermilfoil have provided added habitat/cover for warm water fish species. The 2013 most frequently observed submergent and algal vegetation species or groups included chara, stonewort, Eurasian watermilfoil, river pondweed, water moss, clasping-leaf pondweed, sago pondweed and curly-leaf pondweed. Emergent vegetation such as hardstem bulrush is abundant in the outlet bay. A moderate stand of bulrush is also present along the southeast shore. Shoalwater substrates are mostly sand, rubble, gravel and boulder. The ice out of May 9th was the latest recorded date since 1897 for Green Lake. The 2013 spring/early summer weather was cold/cool with above normal precipitation, whereas, the late summer and early fall was noticeably warmer with minimal precipitation. Ice on was relatively early (November 27) during 2013 for Green.

A broad band (3-36 feet) of ideal temperatures (<74 F) and dissolved oxygen levels (>3 ppm) for tullibee were present in Green during late July and early August of 2013. Although conditions were present for a major tullibee summerkill in 2012, none was observed probably due to low numbers of adults present in the population. A few local residents reported a minor summerkill of dead tullibee near shore areas of Green during 2011. We observed only a few dead tullibee during the 2011 population assessment. A major summerkill of tullibee occurred during the same time period on nearby Lake Koronis in 2011. Green had been the only lake in the Spicer Area open to the public for fall gillnetting of tullibee during late November or early December each year since the late 1980's. Green Lake was not opened for tullibee gillnetting in 2012 or 2013 due to the low numbers sampled in recent years. Tullibee are an important forage fish for trophy northern pike in Green.

The threats of present (Eurasian watermilfoil, curly-leaf pondweed) and potential exotic invasive species introductions (i.e. zebra mussels, quagga mussels, spiny water flea, faucet snail, etc.) are of a major concern to local residents in Kandiyohi County. Eurasian watermilfoil "EWM" was first documented in Green Lake at several isolated sites during 2000. Both DNR and private attempts to chemically eradicate EWM permanently have been unsuccessful. Private applicators are currently using agricultural based global positioning techniques to better target a specific granular herbicide to known EWM stands. Unfortunately, Eurasian watermilfoil has spread throughout the lake in scattered stands especially near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, storm water inlet areas and off shore "break" (10-15 feet deep) areas since 2000. The frequency of occurrence of EWM in near shore transects has increased from 4 sites in 2003, 16 sites in 2007, 20 sites in 2008 and 28 sites in 2013. EWM mean abundance at transect sites has also increased in a similar trend from 2003 (1.3%) to 2013 (12.0%).

EWM and curly-leaf pondweed tend to thrive in disturbed areas (i.e. previous chemically or mechanically treated areas, storm water inlets) or during years of minimal snowfall and maximum light penetration when competition from native species is minimal. Many large stands of EWM on Green Lake have been located near storm water inlets. Watershed projects that may reduce sediment and nutrient inputs from storm water inlets will also be important for controlling EWM in these patchy areas. Widespread-extensive matting of EWM on the surface is unlikely to occur throughout Green Lake unlike some milfoil infested lakes with protected bay areas (i.e. Minnetonka) due to frequent windswept conditions, the presence of relatively low nitrogen (ammonium) nutrient levels, and unsuitable dominant substrates (boulder, rubble, gravel) present in the majority of shoal water areas of Green Lake. DNR Aquatic invasive species interns will continue to randomly monitor boats entering and leaving the many access sites in an attempt to educate and prevent the spread of exotics into Kandiyohi County Lakes.

Bluegill numbers were moderate in 2013 (33.00/trapnet) compared to the normal range of similar lakes, but below Green Lake historical average (46.76 fish/trapnet). The 2013 bluegill average size was moderate (0.17 pounds and 5.90 inches) from trapnets. The bluegill historical average weight is 0.13 pounds from trapnets. The 2013 catch rate of moderate sized (>6.0 inches) bluegill was high (15.86 fish/trapnet). The 2013 catch rate of large (>8.0 inches) bluegill was low (0.64 fish/trapnet). Bluegill growth rates were near or below the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-6, but above the normal ranges for ages 7-8. The 2010 and 2008 year classes comprised 54% and 25% respectively of the 2013 bluegill catch.

Black crappie numbers were moderately abundant in 2013 (4.33 fish/gillnet) and above the Green Lake historical average (1.20 fish/gillnet). The 2013 black crappie average size was moderate from gillnets (0.44 pounds and 8.08 inches). Black crappie growth rates were below the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-3, but within or above the normal ranges for ages 4-7. The 2012 and 2008 year classes comprised 33% and 22% respectively of the 2013 black crappie catch.

Northern pike numbers were moderately abundant in 2013 (3.08 fish/gillnet) compared to the Green Lake historical average (2.75 fish/gillnet). The 2013 northern pike average size was moderate (3.23 pounds and 24.06 inches) from gillnets. The 2013 catch rate of large (>28 inches) northern pike (0.42 fish/gillnet) was similar to the historical average (0.43 fish/gillnet). Northern pike captured in 2003-2005, 2007, 2009 and 2012-2013 assessments were notably lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. Low numbers of forage fish (yellow perch and tullibee) were documented in Green Lake assessments from 2003-2013. Northern pike growth rates were generally near or below the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 2-8. However, growth rates were within the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-8. The 2010 and 2008 year classes comprised 27% and 25% respectively of the 2013 northern pike gillnet and trapnet catch.

Smallmouth bass numbers were moderately abundant in 2013 (1.25 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range of similar lakes, but below the Green Lake historical average (1.92 fish/gillnet). The 2013 smallmouth bass average size was moderately large (1.57 pounds and 12.70 inches) and similar to the historical average (1.55 pounds and 13.36 inches) from gillnets for Green Lake. The 2013 catch rate of large (>14 inches) smallmouth bass (0.75 fish/gillnet) was moderate, but slightly below the historical average (1.17 fish/gillnet). Smallmouth bass condition factors have been poor since 2000 except for 2004 and 2011. Smallmouth bass growth rates were within both the Green Lake and Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-8. The 2012 and 2008 smallmouth bass year classes comprised 29% and 21% respectively of the 2013 smallmouth bass gillnet catch.

Crayfish, an important smallmouth bass forage species, were not captured in 2007-2009 and 2012-2013. Low numbers of crayfish were captured in 2011 (1.1 crayfish/gillnet), 2010 (0.3 crayfish/gillnet), 2006 (0.1 crayfish/gillnet) and 2005 (0.2 crayfish/gillnet). No crayfish were caught in the 2002-2004 gillnets. The crayfish historical average catch rate is 6.7 crayfish/gillnet for Green.

Tullibee "cisco" numbers were low in the 2013 summer (0.17 fish/gillnet) compared to the Green Lake historical average summer catch rate (2.24 fish/gillnet). The 2013 summer tullibee average size was large (1.13 pounds and 14.57 inches) from gillnets. The tullibee historical summer average weight is 0.62 pounds from gillnets.

There were low numbers of tullibee (16.50 fish/gillnet) captured in the 2013 fall using specialized gillnets (200 feet length, 6 feet deep, 1.75 inch bar mesh) that target adult spawning tullibee. The 2013 fall tullibee average size was large (1.42 pounds and 14.61 inches) for Green. Tullibee growth rates were within the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1 and 6, but below the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 2-5. The 2008 year class comprised 88% of 2013 fall tullibee catch. Low numbers of tullibee (8.33 fish/gillnet, 13.61 inches average length) were also captured in the 2012 fall survey of Green Lake using standard graduated mesh lake survey nets. The 2008 year class comprised 76% of the 2012 fall tullibee catch in Green Lake. Low numbers of tullibee were captured in nearby Lake Koronis (5.33 fish/gillnet, 14.91 inches average length) in the 2012 fall standard lake survey gillnets.

The lack of adult tullibee on the spawning grounds from early November to early December of 2010-2013 as sampled by DNR or private netters during the open season is not a good indication for the long term sustainability of the tullibee population in Green Lake. Hopefully, cool summers will occur during the next several years, which may result in good hatches and survival of tullibee in Green Lake if adequate brood stock numbers are still present.

Yellow perch numbers were low in 2013 (1.08 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range of similar lakes and the Green Lake historical average (13.90 fish/gillnet). The trend of low yellow perch numbers have been reported in other statewide lakes during recent years. The 2013 yellow perch average size was small (0.08 pounds and 6.25 inches) from gillnets. The yellow perch historical average weight is 0.12 pounds from gillnets. Yellow perch growth rates were near the upper ends of the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-2. All yellow perch captured in the 2013 gillnets were from the 2011 year class.

Walleye abundance in 2013 (8.58 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range for similar lakes, but slightly below the Green Lake historical average (9.17 fish/gillnet). The 2013 walleye average size was moderate (1.49 pounds and 15.36 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average weight and length are 1.27 pounds and 14.67 inches from gillnets. The 2013 catch rate of moderate sized (>15 inches) walleye was moderate (4.42 fish/gillnet) and slightly above the historical average (3.89 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. The 2013 catch rate of large (>20 inches) walleye (0.92 fish/gillnet) was similar to the historical average (0.77 fish/gillnet). Walleye condition factors were fair to poor in 2013. Walleye growth rates were generally below the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-7. Growth rates were generally above the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 3-8. Recent walleye year classes have been due mostly to stocking since 2001. The 2011 and 2009 year classes each comprised about 18% of the 2013 walleye gillnet and trapnet catch. Other moderate walleye year classes present included 2006-2008, 2010 and 2012. Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked walleye (fry stocked) accounted for 33% of the 2013 walleye gillnet catch of 9-14 inch size range (2012-2010 year classes).

Green Lake has been stocked annually with walleye fry (1-4 million) from 2000-2013 except for 2002. OTC marked walleye fry (1-2 million) were stocked in Green each year during 2000-2001 and 2007-2013. Approximately 2.0 million OTC marked walleye fry were stocked in Green during 2013. The walleye fry were stocked in part as a 10% return of walleye eggs taken for the statewide propagation program. Marked OTC walleye fingerlings (30,787 fish) accounted for 60% of the fingerlings stocked (51,641 fish) in Green during the 2008 fall. Walleye unmarked fingerlings (91,716 fish, 3,208 pounds) and OTC marked fry (1,999,770 fish) were stocked into Green during 2013. Various combinations of walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) since 2000 into Green Lake. During the 1990's, walleye fry were stocked in 1996 and larger walleye (fingerlings and adults) were stocked in 1994, 1992 and 1990.

A fall electrofishing assessment of Green Lake was conducted on October 7, 2013 to evaluate walleye natural reproduction and a 2013 walleye fry stocking in Green Lake. Low numbers of young of year "YOY" walleye were captured in the 2013 fall electrofishing survey (5.00 YOY/hour, 6.40 inches average length). OTC marked fish comprised 40% (2013 fry stocked year class) of the 2013 fall YOY walleye catch. OTC marked fish (2012 fry stocked year class) comprised 55% (6.60 YOY/hour) of the 2012 YOY fall walleye catch (12.00 YOY/hour). Moderate numbers of YOY walleye were captured in a previous 2011 fall electrofishing survey (31.00 YOY/hour, 6.46 inches average length). OTC marked YOY walleye (fry stocked) comprised 63.3% (19.62 YOY/hour) of the 2011 fall YOY walleye survey catch. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average YOY walleye catch rate and length are 13.89 YOY/hour and 6.73 inches. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY walleye for Green occurred in 1994 (54.00 YOY/hour, 6.15 inches average size). Yearling walleye numbers were low (1.00 fish/hour, 8.58 inches) in the 2013 fall survey.

Rock bass numbers were abundant in 2013 (10.92 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and Green Lake historical average (8.04 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. The 2013 rock bass average size was small (0.35 pounds and 7.18 inches) from gillnets. The rock bass historical average weight is 0.41 pounds from gillnets.

Largemouth bass numbers were moderately abundant in 2013 (1.00 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range of similar lakes and the Green Lake historical average (0.74 fish/gillnet). The 2013 largemouth bass average size was moderate (1.07 pounds and 11.38 inches) from gillnets. The largemouth bass historical average weight is 0.70 pounds from gillnets. Growth rates were generally below or near both the Green Lake and Spicer Area 25th quartiles for ages 2-5. The 2011 and 2008 largemouth year classes comprised 42% and 25% respectively of the 2012 largemouth bass gillnet and trapnet catch.

Other species captured included low numbers of white sucker (1.00 fish/gillnet), carp (0.14 fish/trapnet), pumpkinseed sunfish (0.79 fish/trapnet), hybrid sunfish (1.36 fish/trapnet) and black bullhead (0.14 fish/trapnet). Moderate numbers of large yellow bullhead were captured in 2013 (3.33 fish/gillnet, 1.01 pounds average weight).

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the 2014 fall for walleye natural reproduction, and 2014 summer for all fish species by assessment nets.

A standard survey of Green Lake was conducted during late July to early August of 2018. A targeted fall electrofishing survey was conducted on October 18, 2018 to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye abundance in Green Lake. A targeted fall gillnetting survey was conducted for Walleye during late September of 2018. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets, and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass). A creel survey was last conducted on Green Lake during 2015.

Green is a large (5,561 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), highly developed (690 homes) and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is currently infested with invasive species such as Curly-leaf Pondweed, Eurasian Watermilfoil and Zebra Mussels. Green is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Smallmouth Bass, Black Crappie (recent years) and Bluegill. There are approximately 48 inlets that enter Green Lake. The Middle Fork Crow River is the largest inlet and enters Green along the north shore and exits along the east side eventually flowing into Calhoun Lake. Water clarity was excellent (14.5 feet) for Green Lake on August 2, 2018. Submergent vegetation frequencies appeared higher for several species (various pondweeds, milfoil species and coontail) in Green during the 2018 summer compared to previous surveys. Emergent vegetation such as Hardstem Bulrush is abundant in the outlet bay. A moderate stand of bulrush is present along the southeast shore. Shoalwater substrates are mostly sand, gravel, rubble and boulder.

The threats of present (Zebra Mussels, Eurasian Watermilfoil and Curly-leaf Pondweed) and potential exotic invasive species introductions (i.e. Starry Stonewort, Quagga Mussels, Spiny Water Flea, Faucet Snail, etc.) are of a major concern to local residents in Kandiyohi County. Climate change and invasive species effects have been noticeable for both habitat and species density changes in Green Lake during recent decades. Periphyton (algae, diatoms) and dead plant material now cover the boulder/rubble substrates generally all year long with the exception of some narrow (<1 foot deep) windswept near shore areas due to warmer waters and increased near shore nutrient deposition. This has favored warm water species (Black Crappie, Largemouth Bass, Bluegill, Rock Bass) which are nest spawners, unlike broadcast spawners such Walleye and Tullibee "Cisco". Furthermore, increased densities of submergent vegetation species such as invasive Eurasian Watermilfoil since 2000 have provided added habitat/cover for many warm water fish species. Eurasian Watermilfoil has spread throughout the lake in scattered stands especially near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, storm water inlet areas and off shore "break" (10-15 feet deep) areas since 2000. It was more prevalent in water depths greater than 10 feet and less frequent in shallower water during 2018. Zebra Mussels have decreased green algal abundance resulting in lower densities of zooplankton, shifted energy and nutrient transfers from pelagic to benthic habitats, altered predator-prey relationships, decreased fish condition factors and also increased water clarity since 2014.

Black Crappie numbers were moderately abundant in 2018 gillnets and trapnets for Green compared to the historical averages and similar lakes. The Black Crappie population is made up of mostly smaller sized fish (< 8.0 inches) and younger year classes (2016 and 2015). Although, larger sized (>10.0 inch) fish are present.

Bluegill numbers were low in the 2018 trapnets compared to the historical average and similar lakes. The Bluegill average size was excellent (0.24 pounds and 6.4 inches), but 42% of the catch were 6 years and older fish. Growth rates were below average for younger fish, but better for older fish. Anglers generally have good success catching larger Bluegill near Eurasian Watermilfoil patches or break off areas in 10-15 feet of water during the summer on Green.

Largemouth Bass numbers continue to be abundant in Green due to increased habitat (i.e. Eurasian Watermilfoil). The average size is small (0.55 pounds and 9.3 inches) from gillnets.

Northern Pike numbers (3.42 fish/gillnet) were moderate compared to similar lakes, but above average for Green in 2018. The 2018 Northern Pike average size was moderate (2.78 pounds and 22.3 inches) from gillnets, but below the historical average (3.18 pounds and 23.5 inches). Northern Pike have been generally lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. Low numbers of forage fish (Yellow Perch and Tullibee) have been documented in Green Lake surveys from 2003-2018. Green Lake is one of the few local lakes that still have trophy size Northern Pike (>40.0 inches) present. The largest Northern Pike captured in the 2018 gillnets was 37.6 inches. Northern Pike possession limit regulations for Green Lake in the North-central Zone are as follows: 10 (Not more than 2 over 26". All from 22-26" must be immediately released.) by angling; 10 (only 1 Northern Pike between 22-26" and 1 over 26"; or 2 over 26") by dark house spearing.

Rock Bass numbers were abundant and above both the Green Lake historical average and normal range for similar lakes. The 2018 Rock Bass average weight and length were 0.47 pounds and 8.1 inches from gillnets.

Smallmouth Bass numbers (0.67 fish/gillnet) were lower in 2018 compared to the historical average (1.79 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. The 2018 Smallmouth Bass average size (1.60 pounds and 13.5 inches) was large, but similar to the historical average. The largest Smallmouth Bass captured was 17.2 inches in the 2018 survey. Large sized Crayfish, an important Smallmouth Bass forage species, have been present in low numbers since 1999, but were more abundant in our 2018 gillnets compared to previous surveys. We did observe numerous small sized crayfish in the stomachs of Smallmouth Bass and Rock Bass. Crayfish numbers may increase in the future due to a new forage species "Zebra Mussel" present in Green. In response, this may also provide a greater forage base "crayfish" for Smallmouth Bass.

Tullibee were not present in the 2018 or 2017 summer gillnet catches. The Tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 1.93 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. A November targeted gillnet survey was not conducted for Tullibee in 2018, but will be scheduled for 2019. Tullibee numbers were low (0.50 fish/gillnet, 11.3 inches) in the most recent 2017 November targeted survey. Green Lake has not been opened for Tullibee public gillnetting since 2011 due to the low Tullibee numbers sampled in recent years. Tullibee are an important forage fish, especially for larger Northern Pike and Walleye in Green. Tullibee can also provide a secondary fishing opportunity during the winter months.

Yellow Perch abundance was low in 2018 (1.50 fish/gillnet). Yellow Perch abundance has been less than 10.00 fish/gillnet every survey since 2002. Yellow Perch growth rates were slow. The average size was small (0.09 pounds and 6.4 inches) during 2018. Local anglers have reported in past years seeing numerous small Yellow Perch amongst the Chara "Muskgrass" beds with cameras during the summer or while spearing in the winter. Our standard gillnets may not effectively sample these small (<5.0 inches) Yellow Perch. Predation pressures from various species (i.e. Rock Bass, Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Walleye, etc.) may have also selected for smaller sized and earlier reproducing Yellow Perch restricted to near bottom habitat containing dense Chara beds in Green. A statewide study will examining Yellow Perch catchability, growth and maturity using small mesh gillnets in Green and other lakes in 2019.

Green Lake was stocked annually with Walleye fry (1-4 million) from 2000-2013 except for 2002. Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked Walleye fry (1-2 million) were stocked in Green each year during 2000-2001, 2007-2013, 2016-2018. No Walleye fry were stocked in 2014 or 2015 due to the cessation of egg take operations on Green Lake. Unmarked Spicer and Pike River Walleye strains were stocked into Green during 2015 (36,723 fingerlings, 2,497 pounds; 1,400 yearlings, 560 pounds). Unmarked Spicer strain fingerlings and yearlings were stocked into Green during the 2016 fall (26,365 fingerlings, 1,647 pounds; 4,641 yearlings, 828 pounds). Green Lake was stocked with Spicer strain fin clipped adults (196 pounds, 192 fish) and yearling plus fish (2,081 pounds, 3,936 fish) in the 2017 fall. Spicer strain (1,173 pounds, 16,064 fish) and Pike River strain (117 pounds, 936 fish) fingerlings were also stocked in the 2017 fall. Various combinations of Walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) from 2000-2017 into Green Lake.

Walleye natural reproduction and fry stocking success has been minimal at best since 2012. Low Young of Year "YOY" or fingerling sized Walleye numbers were captured in the 2018 (1.00 YOY/hour, 7.13 inches), 2014 (4.00 YOY/hour, 7.62 inches), 2013 (5.00 YOY/hour, 6.40 inches), and 2012 (12.00 YOY/hour, 6.87 inches) fall electrofishing surveys. No YOY Walleye were captured during the 2017, 2016 or 2015 fall electrofishing surveys. Moderate numbers of YOY Walleye were captured in a previous 2011 fall electrofishing survey (31.00 YOY/hour, 6.46 inches). OTC marked YOY Walleye (fry stocked) comprised 63.3% (19.62 YOY/hour) of the 2011 fall YOY Walleye survey catch. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY Walleye for Green occurred in 1994 (54.00 YOY/hour, 6.15 inches).

Walleye abundance in 2018 summer gillnets (3.25 fish/gillnet) was below historical average catch rate of 8.51 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2018 Walleye average size was moderate (1.94 pounds and 17.18 inches) but above the historical average from gillnets. Recent Walleye year classes have been due to some limited natural reproduction, but mostly to fingerling and fry stockings from 2001-2014. Fingerling and yearling stockings have primarily contributed to the recent year classes since 2015. The 2018 walleye survey catch was comprised of 2011 (10%), 2012 (21%), 2013 (3%), 2014 (8%), 2015 (19%), 2016 (24%) and 2017 (2%) year classes. The 2011 Walleye year class was successful in many area lakes. OTC marked Walleye (fry stocked) accounted for 60%, 36%, 8% and 0% respectively of the 2011, 2012, 2013, 2016 and 2017 year classes caught in the 2018 Walleye combined summer and fall survey catches. YOY Walleye catch rates from 5-30 fish per hour due to fry stockings or natural reproduction may be adequate for providing a moderate year class in larger or clearer lakes. However, future Walleye fry stockings and natural reproduction may be less successful in Green due to poor survival from potential negative effects on zooplankton populations by Zebra Mussels. Continued Walleye fingerling or yearling stockings may be necessary to maintain adequate Walleye numbers in Green.

Other species captured included low numbers of White Sucker, Common Carp, Pumpkinseed, Hybrid Sunfish and Black Bullhead during 2018. Moderate numbers of large Yellow Bullhead were also captured in 2018 (3.25 fish/gillnet, 0.94 pounds average weight).

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking Walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the fall of 2019 for YOY Walleye abundance, 2019 fall for Tullibee and the summer of 2019 for all fish species by standard survey nets.

A targeted fall night electrofishing survey was conducted for young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye on Green Lake during September 17, 2020. Previous fall electrofishing surveys were conducted at six stations for a total of 60 minutes. The 2020 survey was conducted as part of a larger statewide research study to evaluate fall electrofishing catch effectiveness for different total shocking times. Nine stations were sampled for a total of 120 minutes in 2020. The water temperature was 64 F. Water levels were low during 2020. Shocking was difficult due to numerous docks and lifts still in the water during the survey. We observed abundant numbers of Brook Silverside, Bluegill, Rock Bass and small Yellow Perch in the 2020 fall electrofishing survey. A standard summer survey was done in early August of 2020. A targeted fall gillnetting survey for Walleye was done in late September of 2020.

Green is a large (5,561 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), highly developed (690 homes) and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is currently infested with invasive species such as Curly-leaf Pondweed, Eurasian Watermilfoil and Zebra Mussels. Green is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Smallmouth Bass, Black Crappie (recent years) and Bluegill.

Green Lake was stocked annually with Walleye fry (1-4 million) from 2000-2013 except for 2002. Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked Walleye fry (1-2 million) were stocked in Green each year during 2000-2001, 2007-2013, 2016 and 2018. OTC is an antibiotic. Fry are immersed in an OTC bath for several hours prior to stocking. It leaves a noticeable ring on the ear bone "otolith" which distinguishes it from natural or non-marked fish. A sample of Walleye are sacrificed from surveys for inspection of marks in order to estimate a ratio of stocked versus natural Walleye in a lake. This determines if fry stocking is necessary for a lake. No Walleye fry were stocked in 2020, 2019, 2017, 2015 or 2014 due in part to the cessation of egg take operations on Green Lake. Walleye fry stocked during previous years were mostly part of a 10% return of Walleye eggs taken for the statewide propagation program. Unmarked Spicer and Pike River Walleye strains were stocked into Green during 2015 (36,723 fingerlings, 2,497 pounds; 1,400 yearlings, 560 pounds). Unmarked Spicer strain fingerlings and yearlings were stocked into Green during the 2016 fall (26,365 fingerlings, 1,647 pounds; 4,641 yearlings, 828 pounds). Green Lake was stocked with Spicer strain fin clipped age 3+ adults (196 pounds, 192 fish) and ages 1+ fish (2,081 pounds, 3,936 fish) in the 2017 fall. Spicer strain (1,173 pounds, 16,064 fish) and Pike River strain (117 pounds, 936 fish) fingerlings were also stocked in the 2017 fall. In 2020 fall, Green was stocked with Spicer Strain Walleye adults (76 pounds, 39 fish) and yearlings (3,411 pounds, 7,765 fish). Various combinations of Walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) from 2000-2017 into Green Lake. Walleye yearlings (701 fish, 150 pounds) and adult (300 fish, 150 pounds) were stocked by private sources in 2019.

YOY Walleye were absent in the 2020 fall electrofishing survey. Low yearling/adult Walleye numbers were caught in the 2020 fall electrofishing survey. Low YOY Walleye numbers were captured in the 2019 (4.00 YOY/hour, 7.24 inches), 2018 (1.00 YOY/hour, 7.13 inches), 2014 (4.00 YOY/hour, 7.62 inches), 2013 (5.00 YOY/hour, 6.40 inches) and 2012 (12.00 YOY/hour, 6.87 inches) fall electrofishing surveys. No YOY Walleye were captured during the 2017, 2016 or 2015 fall electrofishing surveys. OTC marked fry captured as fingerlings comprised 40% of the 2013 and 55% (6.60 YOY/hour) of the 2012 fall electrofishing surveys. Moderate numbers of YOY Walleye were captured in a previous 2011 fall electrofishing survey (31.00 YOY/hour, 6.46 inches average length). OTC marked YOY Walleye (fry stocked) comprised 63.3% (19.62 YOY/hour) of the 2011 fall YOY Walleye survey catch. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average YOY Walleye catch rate and length are 10.74 YOY/hour and 6.81 inches. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY Walleye for Green occurred in 1994 (54.00 YOY/hour, 6.15 inches). Yearling Walleye numbers were moderate to low in the 2014 (6.00 fish/hour), 2016 (3.00 fish/hour) and 2018 (2.00 fish/hour) fall electrofishing surveys. No yearling Walleye were captured in the 2017 and 2015 fall electrofishing surveys.

Walleye abundance in the 2020 fall survey (8.25 fish/gillnet) was higher than the summer survey (4.00 fish/gillnet). The 2020 Walleye average sizes were similar for the fall (1.91 pounds and 17.25 inches) and summer surveys (2.01 pounds and 17.42 inches). The 2020 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches and larger) Walleye was higher for fall (6.00 fish/gillnet) compared to summer (2.83 fish/gillnet). The 2020 fall catch rate of preferred size (20.00 inches and larger) Walleye (1.75 fish/gillnet) was higher than the summer catch rate (0.83 fish/gillnet) Recent Walleye year classes have been due mostly to stocking since 2001.

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking Walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the fall of 2021 for YOY Walleye abundance, 2022 fall for Tullibee and the summer of 2021 for all fish species by standard survey nets.

Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (maximum depth 110 feet), low-moderate productive lake located near Spicer, MN in Kandiyohi County. Green has excellent water quality compared to most other lakes in Kandiyohi County. Water clarity is excellent (secchi disk reading 12.0 feet on 6-16-92). Nutrient levels are low. However, the Middle Fork of the Crow River via Mud Lake (34-0158) and Nest Lake (34-0154) is a constant source of moderate nutrient loading to Green Lake. So far Green has been able to assimilate these incoming nutrients without an appreciable change in productive status. In addition to the Middle Fork of the Crow River, there are seven other inlets which all but one connect to shallow permanent lakes/marshes. The outlet (Middle Fork of the Crow River) is located on the northeast side of the lake and connects to Lake Calhoun (34-0062) via a marsh. The immediate watershed types are primarily municipal (residential homes), mixed hardwoods, and marshlands. Green is heavily developed. The lake substrate is composed of about 37% sand, 29% gravel, 25% rubble, 7% boulder, 1% clay, and 1% marl. There are several long shallow bars (Hultgren's, Lone Tree, Grate's, Castle Flats) located in the lake. Emergent vegetation (primarily hardstem bulrush with some common cattail, cane, and reed canary grass) are restricted to the outlet area and a small stand near the "Spicer Castle" along the south shore. There is a variety of submergent vegetation species, but density is light throughout most of the lake with the exception of the northeast shore (outlet). Green has been intensively stocked with a variety of species (primarily walleye, northern pike), densities, and frequencies over the years. Smallmouth bass were introduced in the early 1940's. Tullibee (cisco) were thought to be introduced into Green during the late 1800's. Historically, rescue operations have been common in adjacent connected winterkill lakes/marshes for northern pike and walleye. In the last ten years, stocking efforts have been devoted to walleye and winter rescue northern pike. In the fall of 1993, fall electrofishing was begun to assess the contributions of natural reproduction and stocking to the walleye fishery in Green. Commercial removal has been limited in the last ten years to some carp (16,160 lbs) and suckers (2,900 lbs). Green is a popular lake for walleye, northern pike, and smallmouth bass angling. In addition, tullibee "cisco" gillnetting is allowed for a two week period usually during mid to late November. Walleye abundance in 1993 (9.3 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range (3.7 - 10.0 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes, but slightly above the historical average (8.0 fish/gillnet). The 1993 average size was the same as the historical average (1.3 lbs). Growth rates appear average compared to other local lakes. Significant natural reproduction was documented in 1993. Fall electrofishing catch rates in 1993 were 46.0 young of year walleye/hour and 30.3 yearling walleye/hour. Natural reproduction in 1992 probably contributed to most of the yearling catch in 1993, however stocking in the fall 1992 (2,056 lbs, 90,670 fish) may also have contributed. Northern pike abundance in 1993 (3.1 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range (3.0 - 8.2 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes and similar to the historical average (2.9 fish/gillnet). The largest northern pike caught in the gillnets was 32.0 inches. The 1993 average weight (2.5 lbs) was similar to the historical average (2.6 lbs). Growth rates appear good compared to local lakes, however no fish over five years old were caught in the survey gear. There are several inlets marshes (Alvig Slough, East Woodcock Lake) and the outlet marsh area which northern pike spawning occurs. Yellow perch abundance in 1993 (32.7 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range (8.1 - 50.5 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes and above the historical abundance (19.8 fish/gillnet). Gillnet catch rates have ranged from a low of 4.7 fish/gillnet in 1979 to a high of 32.7 fish/gillnet in 1993. The 1993 average size was 6.5 inches. Growth rates appear slightly below average compared to other local lakes. Tullibee "cisco" abundance in 1993 summer survey (10.2 fish/gillnet) was the highest recorded value and also above the normal range (0.7 - 6.5 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes. The historical average is 4.0 fish/gillnet. The 1993 average size (0.4 lbs) was slightly above the historical average (0.3 lbs). Growth rates appear similar to previous surveys. About 66% of the fish caught were from the 1992 year class. Cool summers and good dissolved oxygen levels throughout the water column the past two years probably contributed to the increased survival and recruitment of tullibee. A partial summerkill of tullibee occurred in 1988 and 1983 probably due to higher water temperatures/lower dissolved oxygen levels during the late summer in those years. Smallmouth bass abundance (1.2 fish/gillnet) in 1993 was the highest recorded value and was above the normal range (0.2 - 0.7 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes. The historical average gillnet catch was 0.5 fish/gillnet. The largest fish captured in the summer survey was 18.3 inches. Growth rates appear average. Although the 1993 summer catch was the highest recorded value, the 1993 spring electrofishing abundance rating (1.9 fish/hour) was below previous spring estimates (1991= 26.5 fish/hour, 1990= 8.0 fish/hour). The 1993 spring electrofishing estimates may have been negatively influenced by poor shocking conditions (high winds, frequent precipitation, higher water levels) that occurred in May and June of 1993. Smallmouth anglers tend to have the greatest success along the long shallow bars and the northeast side of the lake. Largemouth bass 1993 spring electrofishing catch rate (1.9 fish/hour) was poor compared to previous surveys (1991= 8.0 fish/hour, 1990= 57.7 fish/hour). Poor shocking conditions may have also influenced the low largemouth bass catch rate in 1993. The 1993 average weight (0.6 lbs) was similar to the historical average (0.7 lbs). Rock bass abundance in 1993 (10.1 fish/gillnet) was the highest recorded value and was above the normal range (0.6 - 4.5 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes. The historical average was 6.6 fish/gillnet. The 1993 average weight (0.5 lbs) was slightly above the historical average (0.4 lbs). The 1993 average size was 8.6 inches. Black crappie abundance (0.3 fish/trapnet) was slightly within the normal range (0.2 - 1.5 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes, but below the historical average (0.7 fish/trapnet). The 1993 average weight was the same as the historical average (0.3 lbs). Black crappie were most abundant in the 1982 survey (1.1 fish/trapnet). Growth rates appear below average compared to other local lakes. Bluegill catch rates (96.8 fish/trapnet) in 1993 were above the normal range (3.1 - 47.1 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes and above the historical average (64.1 fish/trapnet). The average size was 4.7 inches. The optimal density and population size structure occurred in 1986 (31.5 fish/trapnet, 35% of fish were greater than 6 inches). Anglers generally have the greatest success for catching bluegill along the bulrush fringes of the northeast shore area. Black bullhead abundance (1.3 fish/trapnet) in 1993 was within the normal range (0.3 - 2.9 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes and slightly below the historical average (1.9 fish/trapnet). The 1993 average black bullhead weight was the same as the historical average (0.4 lbs). Yellow bullhead abundance in 1993 (0.7 fish/trapnet) was below the normal range (1.1 - 4.8 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes, but slightly above the historical average (0.5 fish/trapnet). The 1993 yellow bullhead weight (0.9 lbs) was slightly above the historical average (0.7 lbs). The 1993 bowfin "dogfish" catch rate (2.0 fish/trapnet) was above the normal range (0.3 - 1.1 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes and slightly above the historical average (1.7 fish/trapnet). The 1993 average weight (4.3 lbs) was similar to the historical average (4.6 lbs). Green has a variety of fishing opportunities (walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, largemouth bass, bluegill, and black crappie), especially for those anglers who prefer the challenge of fishing a large lake with lots of structure. Green is a popular lake among local and non local anglers. Night fishing (trolling, casting) for walleye along the shallow bars is quite popular, but deep jigging is also a successful technique during the daytime. Unlike other area lakes where walleye fishing may slow down during mid summer, anglers often continue having success on Green. The abundant forage base of tullibee and yellow perch has the potential of producing trophy walleye and northern pike. Priority management activities should include maintaining present water quality conditions, protecting and expanding hardstem bulrush stands, maintaining inlet access for northern pike to make natural spawning runs (Alvig Slough, East Woodcock, Outlet marsh), winter rescue of northern pike when necessary, evaluating the contributions of walleye stockings and the necessity of further stockings through fall electrofishing and lake surveys, determine the extent of angler exploitation on smallmouth bass populations, biannual sampling of bass populations through spring electrofishing, enacting experimental regulations if necessary for smallmouth bass and northern pike to create more trophy fish available. Another option would be to introduce muskellunge to Green. The size, structure, habitat, and available forage (tullibee) has the possibility of producing a viable population of trophy muskellunge for anglers.

A fish population assessment of Green Lake was conducted in mid July of 2002. Green is a large, deep, low-moderate productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegill. Green Lake receives high recreational use during the summer months. Aquatic vegetation is generally limited in the lake. Low densities of Eurasian water milfoil have been documented in Green Lake primarily near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, fishing pier, and several isolated areas since 2000. Efforts to chemically eradicate Eurasian water milfoil have been unsuccessful. Widespread and extensive matting of Eurasian water milfoil is unlikely to occur through out Green Lake. The dominant substrates (rock, rubble, gravel) present in the shoal water areas are not suitable for aquatic vegetation establishment. Experimental regulations for both northern pike and smallmouth bass were enacted in 1997 in order to increase the average size and produce trophy fisheries of smallmouth bass and northern pike in Green Lake. The northern pike experimental regulation (24 inch maximum size limit) prohibits the harvest of fish 24 inches and greater. The smallmouth and largemouth bass regulation was originally catch and release only. However, the bass regulation was modified to a 14 inch maximum harvest size limit in 2001. The bass regulation was changed because of increasing numbers of smallmouth bass and the perceived negative effects on the walleye population in Green Lake. A summer creel survey was conducted on Green Lake during the 2001 summer (May 10 - September 30) as an on going evaluation of the two experimental regulations.Bluegill numbers were abundant in 2002 (63.9 fish/trapnet) and above the historical average catch rate (51.1 fish/trapnet) for Green. The 2002 bluegill average size was small (0.09 lbs. and 4.7 inches) from the trapnets. The bluegill historical average length is 5.1 inches from trapnets. The largest bluegill captured was 9.3 inches from the 2002 summer assessment. The 2002 catch rate of quality size (6.0 inches) and larger bluegill was moderate (8.3 fish/trapnet) in the 2002 summer assessment. Northern pike numbers were low to moderate in 2002 (2.8 fish/gillnet) and similar to the historical average catch rate (3.0 fish/gillnet) for Green. The northern pike average size was moderate to large (4.45 lbs. and 24.8 inches) from gillnets. The northern pike historical average length is 21.7 inches from gillnets. The largest northern pike captured was 38.3 inches in the 2002 summer assessment. Northern pike growth rates in Green were above the normal ranges for ages 1-7 compared to area lakes. The Green Lake northern pike population is also evaluated every other spring through ice out trapping. The northern pike average size has increased both in the summer and spring ice out assessments since the experimental regulation was enacted in 1997. Smallmouth bass numbers were abundant in 2002 (3.2 fish/gillnet) and above the historical average catch rate (1.92 fish/gillnet) for Green. The 2002 smallmouth bass average size was moderate to large (1.87 lbs. and 14.5 inches) from gillnets. The smallmouth bass historical average length is 13.2 inches from gillnets for Green. The largest smallmouth bass captured was 19.1 inches from the 2002 summer assessment. The 2002 catch rate of preferred size (14.0 inches) and larger smallmouth bass was high (2.25 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (1.19 fish/gillnet). About 31% of the smallmouth bass captured in the 2002 summer assessment were from a 1997 year class. Smallmouth bass growth rates calculated in the Green 2002 summer assessment were generally below the normal ranges compared to Green Lake historical growth data. Crayfish, an important smallmouth bass forage species, were not caught in the 2002 gillnets. The crayfish historical average catch rate is 15.7 crayfish/gillnet. Local anglers have reported excellent success catching large smallmouth bass in recent years. However, local anglers have expressed concern over the relatively high smallmouth population effect via competition on the presently low walleye population in Green Lake.Tullibee "cisco" numbers were low in 2002 (0.3 fish/gillnet) and below the historical average catch rate (2.9 fish/gillnet) for Green. The 2002 tullibee average size was moderate (0.56 lbs. and 11.00 inches) from gillnets. The tullibee historical average length is 10.1 inches from gillnets. Tullibee are an important forage species for both large northern pike and large walleye.Yellow perch numbers were moderate in 2002 (21.1 fish/gillnet) and similar to the historical average catch rate (20.7 fish/gillnet) for Green. The 2002 yellow perch average size was small (0.12 lbs. and 6.4 inches) from gillnets. The yellow perch historical average length is 6.6 inches from gillnets. The largest yellow perch captured was 9.7 inches in the 2002 summer assessment. Walleye numbers were low in 2002 (6.3 fish/gillnet) and below the historical average catch rate (9.4 fish/gillnet) for Green. The 2002 walleye average size was moderate (1.27 lbs. and 14.3 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average length is 14.6 inches from gillnets for Green. The largest walleye captured was 24.3 inches in the 2002 summer assessment. The catch rate of quality size (15.0 inches) and larger walleye in 2002 (2.8 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (4.1 fish/gillnet) for Green. Walleye growth rates calculated in the Green 2002 summer assessment were below the normal ranges for ages 1-8 compared to area lakes, but similar to the Green Lake historical growth rate data. Local anglers reported below average walleye angling success for numbers, although smaller sized walleye were reported being caught with greater frequency than the previous year.Walleye natural reproduction in Green was generally both frequent and adequate to sustain walleye numbers from 1993-1996 based on previous fall and summer surveys. However, walleye natural reproduction has been fair to poor from 1997-2002. Walleye fingerlings or yearlings have been stocked into Green every year from 2000-2002 because of poor walleye natural reproduction. No young of year "YOY" walleye were captured in the 2002 fall night electrofishing survey. The YOY walleye historical average catch rate is 18.7 fish/hour for non stocked fish in Green Lake. All small walleye sampled in the 2002 fall night electrofishing survey (16.0 yearlings/hour) were marked fish from the 2001 stocking of walleye fry (1.04 million fish). The 2001 walleye fry stocking was from a 10% return of walleye eggs taken for statewide hatching operations. Unmarked walleye fingerlings and yearlings were stocked during the 2001 fall (144,386 fingerlings, 4,162 lbs.; 104 yearlings, 26 lbs.) and the 2002 fall (5,976 fingerlings, 432 lbs.; 12,617 yearlings, 3,127 lbs.) because of low documented YOY walleye numbers due to poor natural reproduction.Rock bass numbers were abundant in 2002 (13.7 fish/gillnet) and above the historical average catch rate (6.4 fish/gillnet) for Green. The 2002 rock bass average size was small to moderate (0.37 lbs. and 7.3 inches) from gillnets. The rock bass historical average length is 8.1 inches from gillnets. The largest rock bass captured was 11.3 inches from the 2002 summer assessment.Current fish management activities on Green include protecting the important aquatic vegetation such as bulrush through the permit process, monitoring and preventing the spread of Eurasian water milfoil if possible within and out of Green Lake, participating in the Middle Fork of the Crow River Watershed Project, monitoring both smallmouth bass and northern pike populations for the experimental regulations study, and stocking walleye fingerlings after two consecutive years of poor natural reproduction as documented by fall night electrofishing surveys. The Green Lake fishery will be surveyed in the 2003 spring for smallmouth bass and the 2003 summer for all species. Ice out trapping assessment for northern pike will occur in 2003. A fall electrofishing for young of year walleye will occur in 2003.

A fish resurvey of Green Lake was conducted in early August of 2003. Green is a large, deep, low-moderate productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegill. Green Lake receives high recreational use during the summer months. Low densities of Eurasian water milfoil have been documented in Green Lake primarily near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, fishing pier, and several isolated areas since 2000. Efforts to chemically eradicate Eurasian water milfoil have been unsuccessful. Widespread and extensive matting of Eurasian water milfoil is unlikely to occur through out Green Lake. Water levels were normal during the spring and early summer, but low by fall due to drought conditions in 2003. Thirty-two inlets/tiles/culverts were identified draining into Green Lake during the 2003 resurvey. The largest inlet is the Middle Fork of the Crow River, which enters Green along the north shore via the Old Mill Inn Dam. The Middle Fork of the Crow River outlets near the northeast corner of Green and connects to Calhoun Lake. A Highway 23 four-lane construction project began adjacent to Green Lake during 2003. Significant runoff (sediment) from the Highway 23 construction project drained into Green during several large rainfall events in late June and early July of 2003.
