One of the few positive aspects of the Highway 23 project was the construction of retention ponds along the Highway 23 corridor to reduce or slow future runoff into Green Lake. Water quality (total phosphorus=0.016) and clarity (13.00 ft on 6/9/2003) readings taken during early June of 2003 indicated good results, but water clarity (secchi=4.83 ft on 8/4/2003) was significantly reduced by August of 2003. The most frequently occurring shoalwater substrates noted in the 2003 resurvey were sand, gravel, rubble, and boulder. The most frequently occurring submergent vegetations species present in 2003 included muskgrass (chara), filamentous algae, stonewort, water moss, sago pondweed, and variable pondweed. Hardstem bulrush stands were present in the outlet bay area and south shore near an area called the Spicer Castle.Experimental regulations for both northern pike and smallmouth bass were enacted in 1997 in order to increase the average size and produce trophy fisheries of smallmouth bass and northern pike in Green Lake. The northern pike experimental regulation (24 inch maximum size limit) prohibits the harvest of fish 24 inches and greater. The smallmouth and largemouth bass regulation was originally catch and release only. However, the bass regulation was modified to a 14 inch maximum harvest size limit in 2001. The bass regulation was modified again in the 2003 fall to a 14 inch maximum harvest size limit with one bass over 21 inches allowed. The bass regulation was changed because of increasing numbers of smallmouth bass and the perceived negative effects on the walleye population in Green Lake. A summer creel survey will be conducted on Green Lake during 2004-2005 as an on going evaluation of the two experimental regulations. A public input meeting will occur during the 2005 fall to determine the fate of current experimental regulations for northern pike and bass on Green for 2006 and beyond.Bluegill numbers were moderate to high in 2003 (60.6 fish/trapnet) compared to the normal ranges (25th=26.6, 50th=55.2, 75th=74.3 fish/trapnet) for Green and similar lakes. The Green Lake bluegill historical average catch rate is 51.7 fish/trapnet. The 2003 bluegill average size was small (0.11 pounds and 4.8 inches) from the trapnets. The bluegill historical average length is 5.1 inches from trapnets. The 2003 catch rate of quality size (6.0 inches) and larger bluegill was moderate (17.1 fish/trapnet). Bluegill growth rates were generally below the normal ranges compared to area lakes. Northern pike numbers were moderate in 2003 (2.9 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range (25th=2.6, 50th=3.0, 75th=3.6 fish/gillnet) for Green, but below the normal range for similar lakes. The Green Lake northern pike historical average catch rate is 3.0 fish/gillnet. The 2003 northern pike average size were moderate (3.66 pounds and 24.9 inches) from gillnets. However, the northern pike captured in 2003 were notably lean in appearance and poor condition compared to fish captured in the previous 2002 assessment. The northern pike historical average length is 22.0 inches from gillnets. Northern pike growth rates in Green were within or above the normal ranges for ages 1-5 compared to area lakes. The 2001 Northern pike year class comprised 48% of the 2003 total northern pike survey catch. The northern pike average size has increased both in the summer and spring ice out surveys since the experimental regulation was enacted in 1997. The largest northern pike captured in the 2003 summer survey was 39.5 inches.Smallmouth bass numbers were moderate to high in 2003 (2.4 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges (25th=0.4, 50th=1.0, 75th=2.7 fish/gillnet) for Green and for similar lakes. The smallmouth bass historical average catch rate is 1.9 fish/gillnet from Green. No spring electrofishing surveys for bass were conducted in 2003. The 2003 smallmouth bass average size was moderate (1.32 pounds and 12.0 inches) from gillnets. The smallmouth bass historical average length is 13.1 inches from gillnets for Green. The 2003 catch rate of preferred size (14.0 inches) and larger smallmouth bass was moderate (1.1 fish/gillnet) compared to the Green historical average (1.2 fish/gillnet). The 2002 smallmouth bass year class comprised 47% of the total 2003 smallmouth bass survey catch. Smallmouth bass growth rates calculated in 2003 from Green were generally below or near the low end of the normal ranges for ages 1-3, but above the normal ranges for ages 4-5 compared to Green Lake historical growth data. Crayfish, an important smallmouth bass forage species, were not caught in the 2003 or 2002 gillnets. The crayfish historical average catch rate is 15.7 crayfish/gillnet.Tullibee "cisco" numbers were low in 2003 (0.3 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges (25th=0.4, 50th=1.7, 75th=3.4 fish/gillnet) for Green and similar lakes. The tullibee historical average catch rate is 2.8 fish/gillnet for Green. The 2003 tullibee average size was small (0.27 pounds. and 9.4 inches) from gillnets. The tullibee historical average length is 10.0 inches from gillnets. Tullibee are an important forage species for both large northern pike and large walleye.Yellow perch numbers were low in 2003 (5.3 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges (25th=14.1, 50th=19.1, 75th=26.2 fish/gillnet) for Green and similar lakes. The yellow perch historical average catch rate is 19.7 fish/gillnet for Green. The 2003 yellow perch average size was moderate to small (0.12 pounds. and 6.6 inches) from gillnets. Yellow perch growth rates were variable compared to area lakes. The 2000 yellow perch year class comprised 82% of the 2003 total yellow perch survey catch.Walleye numbers were moderate in 2003 (9.4 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range (25th=7.9, 50th=9.5, 75th=10.0 fish/gillnet) for Green, but high compared to similar lakes. The walleye historical average catch rate is 9.4 fish/gillnet for Green. The 2003 walleye average size was moderate (1.38 pounds. and 15.1 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average length is 14.6 inches from gillnets. The 2003 catch rate of quality size (15.0 inches) and larger walleye in 2003 (4.7 fish/gillnet) was similar to the historical average (4.2 fish/gillnet) for Green. The 2001 year class (stocked and natural reproduction) comprised 42% of the total 2003 walleye survey catch. Walleye growth rates calculated from the 2003 Green survey were below the normal ranges for area lakes, but similar to historical growth rates for Green. Walleye natural reproduction in Green was generally both frequent and adequate to sustain walleye numbers based on previous fall and summer surveys from 1993-1996. However, walleye natural reproduction has been fair to poor from 1997-2003. Walleye fingerlings or yearlings have been stocked in Green every year from 2000-2003 because of poor walleye natural reproduction. Walleye fry (1,768,781 fry) were stocked during the 2003 spring. Low young of year "YOY" walleye numbers (4.0 YOY walleye/hour, 8.5 inches average size) were captured in the 2003 fall night electrofishing survey. The YOY walleye historical average catch rate is 18.6 YOY walleye/hour for Green Lake. Approximately 3,550 pounds of walleye adults/yearlings (18,597 fish) and 654 pounds of walleye fingerlings (18,650 fish) were stocked during 2003 spring and fall. Rock bass numbers were high in 2003 (12.6 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges (25th=3.5, 50th=6.4, 75th=8.7 fish/gillnet) for Green and similar lakes. The rock bass historical average catch rate is 6.8 fish/gillnet for Green. The 2003 rock bass average size was moderate to small (0.27 pounds. and 6.7 inches) from gillnets. The rock bass historical average length is 8.0 inches from gillnets.Current fish management activities on Green include protecting the important aquatic vegetation such as bulrush through the permit process, monitoring and preventing the spread of Eurasian water milfoil if possible within and out of Green Lake, participating in the Middle Fork of the Crow River Watershed Project, monitoring both smallmouth bass and northern pike populations for the experimental regulations study, and stocking walleye fingerlings after two consecutive years of poor natural reproduction as documented by fall night electrofishing surveys. The Green Lake fishery will be surveyed in the 2004 spring for smallmouth bass and the 2004 summer for all species. Ice out trapping assessment for northern pike will occur in the 2004 spring. A fall electrofishing survey for young of year walleye will occur in 2004. A creel survey will be conducted during 2004 and 2005 to evaluate the bass and northern pike experimental regulations.

A resurvey of Green Lake was conducted during early August of 2014. Green is a large (5,561 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), highly developed (690 homes) and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, black crappie (recent years) and bluegill. There are approximately 48 inlets that enter Green Lake. The Middle Fork Crow River is the largest inlet and enters Green along the north shore and exits along the east side eventually flowing into Calhoun Lake. Direct nutrient runoff into Green is primarily from highway runoff and residential sources, which include lake homes and the city of Spicer. There is also upstream agricultural row crop runoff into the Middle Fork Crow River. Water levels were high during June and July of 2014 from inlets due to rain events, but low by fall. A slow no-wake zone was put in place for lakes in Kandiyohi and Stearns Counties during June thru early July of 2014. High water levels caused some shoreline erosion in addition to many docks and boat lifts floating away from their moorings. Nutrient levels were relatively low during June of 2013 (total phosphorus=0.015 ppm, chlorophyll-a=6.3 ppb). Water clarity was poor (5.5 feet) for Green Lake on August 6, 2014. Water clarity ranged from 5.5-13.3 feet during bi-monthly sampling from June-August of 2014.

The threats of present (zebra mussels, Eurasian watermilfoil, and curly-leaf pondweed) and potential exotic invasive species introductions (i.e. quagga mussels, spiny water flea, faucet snail, etc.) are of a major concern to local residents in Kandiyohi County. Eurasian watermilfoil "EWM" was first documented in Green Lake at several isolated sites during 2000. Both DNR and private attempts to chemically eradicate EWM have been unsuccessful. Eurasian watermilfoil has spread throughout the lake in scattered stands especially near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, storm water inlet areas and off shore "break" (10-15 feet deep) areas since 2000. EWM and curly-leaf pondweed tend to thrive in disturbed areas (i.e. previous chemically or mechanically treated areas, storm water inlets) or during years of minimal snowfall and maximum light penetration when competition from native species is minimal.

One adult zebra mussel was found on a dock along the southeast shore of Green during the early summer of 2014. No additional zebra mussels were found until the fall of 2014. Numerous small young zebra mussels were found attached on docks and boat lifts scattered throughout Green Lake. Zebra mussel eradication techniques (e.g. potassium chloride "potash", zequanox, copper sulfate, etc.) have been recently tried in metro area lakes where populations have not spread throughout the lake. Zequanox is a combination of specific dead bacteria cells which are toxic to zebra mussels. Eradication of zebra mussels is improbable once mussels spread throughout a lake due to their ability to reproduce large numbers of young zebra mussel "veligers" by a small number of adults. Green Lake will continue to be monitored to document the impacts zebra mussels may have on the lake ecology (i.e. water clarity, substrate effects, aquatic vegetation, plankton abundance, native species responses, etc.).

Bluegill numbers were low in 2014 (29.60/trapnet) compared to the historical average of 46.16 fish/trapnet. The 2014 bluegill average size was moderate (0.18 pounds and 6.18 inches), but above the historical average weight of 0.13 pounds from trapnets. Abundant numbers of moderate sized (6.00 plus inches) bluegill (16.87 fish/trapnet) were captured in the 2014 trapnets. However, only low numbers of larger (8.00 plus inches) bluegill (0.80 fish/trapnet) were captured in 2014.

Black crappie numbers were abundant in 2014 (2.67 fish/gillnet, 2.13 fish/trapnet) compared to the historical averages of 1.25 fish/gillnet and 0.76 fish/trapnet. The 2014 black crappie average sizes were moderate from gillnets (0.35 pounds and 7.68 inches), but slightly larger from trapnets (0.43 pounds and 8.70 inches). The black crappie historical average lengths are 7.85 inches for both gillnets and trapnets. Black crappie growth rates are excellent for ages 2+ fish in Green. The 2012 and 2011 year classes combined comprised 70% of the black crappie captured in 2014 survey nets.

Northern pike numbers were moderately abundant in 2014 (3.17 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average of 2.77 fish/gillnet. The 2014 northern pike average size was moderate (3.36 pounds and 24.10 inches) from gillnets. The northern pike historical average weight and length are 3.15 pounds and 23.37 inches from gillnets. The 2014 catch rate of larger (28.00 plus inches) northern pike (0.58 fish/gillnet) was moderate and similar to the historical average (0.43 fish/gillnet). The largest northern pike captured was 35.1 inches from a gillnet in 2014. Northern pike growth rates were low to moderate especially for ages 1-5, but better for ages 6+ fish. Northern pike captured have been notably lean in appearance during most recent surveys compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. Low numbers of forage fish (yellow perch and tullibee) have been documented in Green Lake assessments from 2003-2014. The 2011 year class comprised 30% of the 2014 northern pike catch.

Smallmouth bass numbers were low in 2014 (0.67 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average of 1.88 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2014 smallmouth bass average size was moderate (0.92 pounds and 11.38 inches), but smaller than the historical average size of 1.53 pounds and 13.28 inches from gillnets. Low numbers of larger (14.00 inch plus) smallmouth bass (0.33 fish/gillnet) were captured in 2014 gillnets. Smallmouth bass growth rates were poor.

Crayfish, an important smallmouth bass forage species, have been present in low numbers since 2002. Low numbers of crayfish were captured in 2014 (0.08 crayfish/gillnet. The crayfish historical average catch rate is 6.4 crayfish/gillnet for Green. Research has identified crayfish and pumpkinseed sunfish as predators of smaller zebra mussels. Crayfish numbers may increase in Green due a new species present "zebra mussel" which crayfish may readily prey upon. In response, this may also provide a greater forage base "crayfish" for smallmouth bass.

Tullibee "cisco" numbers were low in the 2014 summer (0.08 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green and similar lakes. The tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 2.16 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2014 summer tullibee average size was small (0.26 pounds and 8.62 inches) from gillnets. The tullibee historical summer average weight is 0.60 pounds from gillnets.

Vertical gillnets were set for tullibee at three deepwater (60-105 feet deep) sites which included the north side adjacent to Hultgren's Bar (deepest part), southwest side and southeast side during late August of 2014. There were 153 tullibee captured in 15 vertical gillnets. Tullibee captured with this gear averaged 9.8 inches and ranged from 3.2 to 16.5 inches. Approximately 39% of the tullibee captured were likely young of year fish and 44% were probably ages 6+ to 8+ (2006-2009 year classes) based on historical growth data. The tullibee average depth at capture was 27.9 feet during late August. The thermocline in Green was set up at 49 feet over the deepest area of the lake (105 feet) and the temperature when dissolved oxygen dropped to 3.0 ppm was 72.5 F. Tullibee were sampled in waters from 3.3 to 32.8 feet deep. These waters ranged in temperatures from 60 to 75 F and dissolved oxygen concentrations of 0.07 to 7.95 ppm.

No fall tullibee sampling was conducted in 2014 due to early onset of ice conditions during the peak spawning time period. There were low numbers of tullibee (16.50 fish/gillnet) captured in the 2013 fall using specialized gillnets (200 feet length, 6 feet deep, 1.75 inch bar mesh) that target adult spawning tullibee. The 2013 fall tullibee average size was large (1.42 pounds and 14.61 inches) for Green. The 2008 year class comprised 88% of 2013 fall tullibee catch. Low numbers of tullibee (8.33 fish/gillnet, 13.61 inches average length) were also captured in the 2012 fall survey of Green Lake using standard graduated mesh lake survey nets. Low numbers of tullibee were also captured in nearby Lake Koronis in the 2014 summer (0.20 fish/gillnet, 8.74 inches average length) and fall (6.00 fish/gillnet, 15.95 inches average length) using standard lake survey gillnets.

Green Lake was not opened for public tullibee gillnetting in the 2013 or 2014 fall due to low numbers in recent surveys. The lack of adult tullibee on the spawning grounds from early November to early December of 2010-2013 as sampled by DNR or private netters during the open season is not a good indication for the long term sustainability of the tullibee population in Green Lake. Hopefully, cool summers will occur during the next several years, which may result in good hatches and survival of tullibee in Green Lake if adequate brood stock numbers are still present.

Yellow perch numbers were low in 2014 (2.92 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average of 13.53 fish/gillnet. The 2014 yellow perch average size was small (0.10 pounds and 6.26 inches), but similar to the historical average size (0.12 pounds) from gillnets. Yellow perch growth rates were poor. Local anglers have reported seeing numerous small yellow perch (<6 inches) with cameras amongst the chara beds along the bottom during winter and summer. Intense predation by walleye, bass and northern pike on larger yellow perch may explain the low catches of moderate to larger perch in summer gillnets.

Walleye numbers were low in 2014 (6.17 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average of 9.07 fish/gillnet, but near the median catch rate for similar lakes. The 2014 walleye average size was moderate (1.36 pounds and 15.21 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average weight and length are 1.27 pounds and 14.69 inches from gillnets. Low numbers of moderate sized (15.00 plus inches) walleye (2.83 fish/gillnet) were captured from gillnets in 2014. Walleye growth rates were poor for ages 1-8 compared to other Spicer Area lakes, but moderate for ages 3-6 compared to Green Lake historical growth data. The 2011 and 2012 year classes comprised about 35% and 14% respectively of the 2014 walleye gillnet and trapnet catch. Recent walleye year classes have been due mostly to stocking since 2001.

Green Lake had been stocked annually with walleye fry (1-4 million) from 2000-2013 except for 2002. No walleye fry were stocked in 2014 due to the cessation of egg take operations on Green Lake. Walleye fry stocked during previous years were part of a 10% return of walleye eggs taken for the statewide propagation program. Walleye fingerlings (41,344 fish, 3,652 pounds) were stocked into Green during 2014. Various combinations of walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) since 2000 into Green Lake.

A fall electrofishing assessment of Green Lake was conducted on October 7, 2014 to evaluate walleye natural reproduction in Green Lake. Low numbers of young of year "YOY" walleye were captured in the 2014 fall electrofishing survey (4.00 YOY/hour, 7.62 inches average length). Low numbers of YOY walleye (< 15 YOY/hour) were captured in previous surveys since 1996 with the exception of 2011. Moderate numbers of YOY walleye were captured in the 2011 fall electrofishing survey (31.00 YOY/hour, 6.46 inches average length). OTC marked YOY walleye (fry stocked) comprised 63.3% (19.62 YOY/hour) of the 2011 fall YOY walleye survey catch. The 2011 walleye year class was successful in many area lakes.

Rock bass numbers were abundant in 2014 (13.58 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average of 8.23 fish/gillnet. The 2014 rock bass average size was moderate (0.37 pounds and 7.37 inches) and similar to the historical average size of 0.41 pounds from gillnets.

Largemouth bass numbers were abundant in 2014 (1.42 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average of 0.76 fish/gillnet. The 2014 largemouth bass average size was small (0.55 pounds and 9.14 inches) from gillnets. The largemouth bass historical average weight is 0.69 pounds from gillnets. Largemouth bass growth rates were fair.

Other species captured included low numbers of white sucker (1.08 fish/gillnet), carp (0.00 fish/trapnet), pumpkinseed sunfish (0.53 fish/trapnet), hybrid sunfish (1.27 fish/trapnet) and black bullhead (0.17 fish/gillnet). Moderate numbers of large yellow bullhead were captured in 2014 (2.42 fish/gillnet, 0.98 pounds average weight).

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the fall of 2015 for walleye natural reproduction, and summer of 2015 for all fish species by assessment nets.

The prsnt Wae pop. is made up of all yr classes. Grwth rates are abv avg. with abundance avg. N Pk are above avg. in numbers with avg. grwth rates (strong year classes of II and III year olds). BG are about 2 times avg. in numbers with avg. grwth. Blk Crappies, Perch and Rock Bass are present.

Green is a large, deep, moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Greenis a popular walleye, northern pike, bluegill, and smallmouth bass fishery. Local anglersreported good fishing success for catching both smallmouth and walleye in 1999. Local anglersreported that walleye average sizes improved in 1999. Green had good walleye naturalreproduction during past years in the abundant rock and gravel shoal water areas. However,walleye natural reproduction has been poor since 1997 in Green. Green Lake was last stockedwith walleye fingerlings (43,827 right pelvic fin clipped fish, 2,027 lbs.) in 1994. GreenLake was stocked with 2,699,904 walleye fry in the 1996 spring which was a 10% return of thewalleye eggs taken from Green Lake for the 1996 state wide walleye hatching quotas.Experimental fishing regulations were enacted during 1997 in order to increase the qualityof size for northern pike and smallmouth bass in Green Lake. The smallmouth bass experimentalregulation allows for catch and release fishing only. The northern pike experimentalregulation prohibits the harvest of northern pike 24.0 inches or greater. The northern pikeexperimental regulation will be evaluated in 2008 at which time it will be maintained,modified, or removed depending on the effectiveness of the regulation and public support. Thesmallmouth bass regulation may be modified by 2001 pending comments from a public reviewmeeting in August of 2000 and the analysis of data collected from the 2000 summer fishsampling survey of Green Lake. Walleye were abundant (15.58 fish/gillnet) and the average size (15.15 inches, gillnets)increased in 1999 compared to previous surveys (9.71 fish/gillnet and 14.51 inches historicalaverages). Four walleye year classes (18% for 1994, 18% for 1995, 36% for 1996, 21% for 1997)comprised most of the 1999 walleye catch. Walleye natural reproduction was good to fair in1993 (46.00 YOY/hour), 1994 (52.70 YOY/hour), 1995 (22.00 YOY/hour) and 1996 (33.00YOY/hour). Poor walleye natural reproduction was documented by fall electrofishing in 1997(13.00 YOY/hour), 1998 (4.50 YOY/hour) and 1999 (11.54 YOY/hour). Although YOY walleyenumbers were low in 1997, these fish were moderately abundant as yearlings in the 1998 fallelectrofishing survey (22.50 yearlings/hour). Fingerling stocking in 1994 contributed to lessthan 3% of the total 1994 year class catch in previous Green Lake surveys and no stocked fishwere observed in the 1999 survey. Northern pike were moderately abundant (4.00 fish/gillnet), but small (19.88 inches,2.10 lbs from the gillnets) in 1999 due the presence of large numbers of young fish (1998year class comprised 44% of total northern pike catch). The largest northern pike capturedin the 1999 survey was 34.25 inches. Smallmouth bass were abundant in both the 1999 gillnets (9.00 fish/gillnet) and 1999spring electrofishing survey (35.00 fish/hour) compared to the historical averages (1.61fish/gillnet, 16.56 fish/hour). The 1999 smallmouth bass average weight was 1.36 lbs. fromthe gillnets. The 1999 smallmouth bass average length (12.47 inches, gillnets) was slightlybelow the Green historical average (13.06 inches). The largest smallmouth bass captured inthe 1999 survey was 17.91 inches. The 1996 year class comprised 36.1% of the 1999 smallmouthbass gillnet catch. Crayfish is an important forage species for smallmouth bass in Green.Crayfish numbers were abundant (61.0 crayfish/gillnet) in the 1999 gillnets. Sunfish were moderately abundant (27.50 bluegill/trapnet, 16.21 hybrid sunfish/trapnet)within Green during 1999. The 1999 bluegill average length was small (4.46 inches and 0.08lbs from trapnets). The 1999 hybrid sunfish average size (0.21 lbs., 5.88 inches) in Greenwas greater than the bluegill average size. Rock bass were also moderately abundant in Greenduring 1999 (5.83 fish/gillnet, 0.57 lbs average weight). Forage fish species such as yellow perch (33.42 fish/gillnet) and tullibee (2.50fish/gillnet) were moderately abundant within Green during 1999. The 1999 yellow perchaverage length (6.65 inches) from gillnets was similar to the historical average (6.58inches). The 1999 tullibee average weight from gillnets was 1.02 lbs. Tullibee provide animportant forage base for large northern pike in Green Lake. The Green Lake fishery appears to be in good condition for walleye, northern pike,smallmouth bass numbers. In addition, there are abundant forage species (yellow perch,tullibee, crayfish) present in Green. Bluegill numbers rebounded in 1999 compared to 1998,but the average size was small. If walleye natural reproduction is poor again in 2000, thenwalleye fingerling stocking will take place in the fall of 2000. Local anglers have recentlyvoiced concern over the increasingly abundant smallmouth bass numbers in Green and thepossible affect on the walleye population. The DNR Spicer Fisheries Office will continue tomonitor Green Lake fish population numbers through annual summer netting surveys, spring basselectrofishing surveys and ice out northern pike trapping every two years, and annual YOYwalleye fall electrofishing surveys in order to evaluate the effectiveness of currentmanagement practices and experimental regulations.

A population assessment of Green Lake was conducted in late July of 2006. Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, black crappie, and bluegill. Green Lake receives high recreational use during the summer months. Low densities of Eurasian water milfoil have been documented in Green Lake primarily near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, and several isolated areas since 2000. Efforts to chemically eradicate Eurasian water milfoil have been unsuccessful. Widespread and extensive matting of Eurasian water milfoil is unlikely to occur through out Green Lake. The dominant substrates (boulder, rubble, gravel) present in the shoalwater areas are not suitable for aquatic vegetation establishment. Green Lake is managed primarily for walleye and secondarily for northern pike, tullibee, bluegill, and smallmouth bass.

Experimental regulations for northern pike, smallmouth bass, and largemouth bass were enacted in Green Lake during 1997 as part of a statewide research study. In December of 2005, the DNR decided to end all experimental regulations on Green Lake (largemouth bass, smallmouth bass and northern pike) and return to statewide regulations as of the May 13, 2006 opener for northern pike and May 27, 2006 opener for bass. This decision was based both on public input and the analyzed data collected from netting and creel surveys.

Bluegill numbers were high in 2006 (44.47/trapnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, but similar to the Green historical average catch rate (49.25 fish/trapnet). The 2006 bluegill average size was moderate (0.16 pounds and 5.87 inches from the trapnets). The bluegill historical average length is 5.19 inches from trapnets. There were abundant numbers of quality size (6.00 inches) and larger bluegill (21.97 fish/trapnet) in the 2006 assessment.

Black crappie numbers were high in 2006 (3.83 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and the highest recorded value for Green Lake (historical average catch rate=0.73 fish/gillnet). The 2006 black crappie average size was small (0.26 pounds and 7.14 inches from gillnets). The black crappie historical average length is 7.65 inches from gillnets in Green.

Northern pike numbers were low in 2006 (1.83 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and below the Green historical average catch rate (2.86 fish/gillnet). The 2006 northern pike average size was large (5.05 pounds and 27.29 inches from gillnets). The northern pike historical average length is 22.71 inches from gillnets. The northern pike captured in 2003-2006 surveys were notably lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. Low numbers of forage fish (yellow perch and tullibee) were documented in Green Lake surveys from 2003-2006. The 2004 and 2002 northern pike year classes comprised 30% and 26% respectively of the 2006 total northern pike assessment catch.

Smallmouth bass numbers were high in 2006 (2.25 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, but similar to the Green historical average catch rate (2.01 fish/gillnet). The 2006 smallmouth bass average size was moderate (1.61 pounds and 12.28 inches from gillnets). The smallmouth bass historical average length is 13.29 inches from gillnets for Green Lake. The 2005 and 2000 smallmouth bass year classes comprised the majority of the total 2006 smallmouth bass assessment catch. Crayfish, an important smallmouth bass forage species, were caught in low numbers in 2006 (0.1 crayfish/gillnet) and 2005 (0.2 crayfish/gillnet). The crayfish historical average catch rate is 10.5 crayfish/gillnet for Green.

Tullibee "cisco" numbers were low in the 2006 (0.58 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and below the Green historical average summer catch rate (2.48 fish/gillnet). The 2006 summer tullibee average size was moderate (0.73 pounds and 11.31 inches from gillnets). The tullibee historical average weight is 0.42 pounds from gillnets.

Yellow perch numbers were low in 2006 (3.67 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and below the Green historical average catch rate (17.71 fish/gillnet). The 2006 yellow perch average size was small (0.11 pounds and 6.28 inches from gillnets). The yellow perch historical average weight is 0.13 pounds from gillnets. The 2003 and 2002 yellow perch year classes comprised the majority of the 2006 total yellow perch assessment catch.

Walleye numbers were moderate to high in 2006 (9.58 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, but similar to the Green historical average catch rate (9.03 fish/gillnet). The 2006 walleye average size was moderate (1.24 pounds and 13.89 inches from gillnets). The walleye historical average length is 14.67 inches from gillnets. There were moderate numbers of quality size (15.00 inches) and larger walleye in 2006 (3.00 fish/gillnet). The 2004 and 2000 year classes (stocked and natural reproduction) comprised the majority of the total 2006 walleye assessment catch.

A fall electrofishing survey of Green Lake was conducted during early October of 2006. The 2006 fall electrofishing survey was conducted to evaluate walleye natural reproduction and a 2006 walleye fry stocking (2.06 million) in Green Lake. There were low young of year "YOY" walleye numbers (9.00 YOY/hour, 7.46 inches average length) captured in 2006. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average catch rate and length are 15.40 YOY/hour and 6.84 inches respectively. The Spicer Area YOY walleye historical average catch rate is 70.35 YOY/hour from lakes fry stocked and lakes with natural reproduction.

Rock bass numbers were high in 2006 (7.00 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, but similar to the Green historical average catch rate (7.24 fish/gillnet). The 2006 rock bass average size was moderate (0.40 pounds and 7.72 inches from gillnets). The rock bass historical average weight is 0.43 pounds from gillnets.

Largemouth bass numbers were high in 2006 (4.58 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and above the Green historical average catch rate (0.42 fish/gillnet). The 2006 largemouth bass average size was small (0.48 pounds and 8.50 inches from gillnets). The largemouth bass historical average weight is 0.64 pounds from gillnets.

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on a periodic basis, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives, and stocking various fish species as warranted. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the 2007 spring ice out for northern pike, 2007 fall for walleye natural reproduction, and 2007 summer for all fish species by survey nets. A creel survey was conducted for the 2006-07 winter and scheduled for the 2007 summer.

A population assessment of Green Lake was conducted in late July of 2009. Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Water levels were below normal during the summer, but normal by the late fall of 2009. Water clarity was good (12.0 feet) for Green Lake on July 23, 2009. Dissolved oxygen levels were above 4.0 ppm in depths down to 46 feet during late July of 2009. The shoreline is fully developed with the exception of the outlet area on the east side of the lake. The immediate watershed is varied with the City of Spicer, residential homes, wetlands, hardwood lots, and agricultural row crops. There are approximately 48 inlets (mostly small tiles) that drain into Green Lake. The Middle Fork of the Crow River (Nest Lake outlet) is the largest inlet that flows into Green Lake along the north shore at the Ye Olde Mill Inn Dam and exits along the east shore of Green Lake. Nutrient runoff is low to moderate primarily from nearby residential and city sources, and upstream sources from the Middle Fork of the Crow River via Nest Lake. Numerous storm water retention ponds were built during the 2003 State Highway 23 Four-Lane Project along the west side of Green Lake. There are six public access sites and one shore fishing site (outlet) on the lake. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegill. Green Lake receives high recreational use during the summer months. Green Lake is managed primarily for walleye and secondarily for northern pike, yellow perch, tullibee, bluegill, and smallmouth bass.

Low densities of Eurasian water milfoil had been documented in Green Lake primarily near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, and several isolated areas since 2000. Efforts to chemically eradicate various Eurasian water milfoil stands were overall unsuccessful in 2000, 2001, 2007, and 2008. Small widely scattered Eurasian milfoil stands were observed in off shore "break" areas at a mean depth of 8.6 feet during 2007. Most large stands of Eurasian milfoil on Green Lake have been located near storm water inlets. Watershed projects that may reduce sediment and nutrient inputs from storm water inlets will also be important for controlling Eurasian milfoil in these patchy areas. Widespread-extensive matting of Eurasian water milfoil is unlikely to occur through out Green Lake due to frequent windswept conditions, the presence of relatively low nitrogen (ammonium) nutrient levels and unsuitable dominant substrates (boulder, rubble, gravel) present in the majority of shoalwater areas.

Bluegill numbers were low in 2009 (27.87/trapnet) compared to historical catches, but moderate compared to similar lakes. The Green Lake bluegill historical average catch rate is 48.39 fish/trapnet. The 2009 bluegill average size was moderate to small (0.17 pounds and 5.81 inches) from the trapnets. The bluegill historical average weight is 0.12 pounds from trapnets. The 2009 catch rate of quality size (6.00 inches and larger) bluegill (10.33 fish/trapnet) was moderate and similar to the historical average (11.58 fish/trapnet).

Black crappie numbers were high in 2009 (1.67 fish/gillnet) compared to historical catches and similar lakes. The Green Lake black crappie historical average catch rate is 0.85 fish/gillnet. The 2009 black crappie average size was moderate to large (0.55 pounds and 9.09 inches) from gillnets. The black crappie historical average length is 7.97 inches from gillnets in Green. The 2009 catch rate of quality size (8.00 inches and larger) black crappie (1.08 fish/gillnet) was high and above the historical average (0.30 fish/gillnet). Black crappie growth rates were within the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-6. The 2005 black crappie year class comprised 37% of the 2009 black crappie assessment catch.

Northern pike numbers were low in 2009 (1.42 fish/gillnet) compared to historical catches and similar lakes. The Green Lake northern pike historical average catch rate is 2.72 fish/gillnet. The 2009 northern pike average size was moderate (3.50 pounds and 24.62 inches) from gillnets. The northern pike historical average weight and length are 3.10 pounds and 23.21 inches from gillnets. Northern pike captured in 2003-2005, 2007 and 2009 assessments were notably lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. The 2009 northern pike condition factor (0.577) was below the Green Lake normal range (0.605 -0.630). Low numbers of forage fish (yellow perch and tullibee) were documented in Green Lake assessments from 2003-2009. The 2009 catch rate of preferred size (28.00 inches and larger) northern pike (0.42 fish/gillnet) was near the historical average (0.43 fish/gillnet). Spearing pressure and harvest of large northern pike was high during the 2006-07 winter following the return to statewide regulations. Northern pike growth rates were within the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-4, but below the normal ranges for ages 5-8. Growth rates were also below the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 7-8. The 2008 year class comprised 22% of the 2009 northern pike gillnet and trapnet catch.

Smallmouth bass numbers were moderate in 2009 (1.00 fish/gillnet) compared to historical catches, but abundant compared to similar lakes. The smallmouth bass historical average catch rate is 1.93 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2009 smallmouth bass average size was large (1.99 pounds and 15.11 inches) from gillnets. The smallmouth bass historical average weight and length are 1.57 pounds and 13.53 inches from gillnets for Green Lake. The 2009 catch rate of preferred size (14.00 inches and larger) smallmouth bass (0.58 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (1.23 fish/gillnet). The 2005 year class comprised 36% of the 2009 smallmouth bass gillnet catch. Smallmouth bass growth rates were generally below the both Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-5, but within the normal ranges for ages 6-8. The 2009 smallmouth bass condition factor (1.418) was poor. YOY smallmouth bass numbers was low in 2009 shoreline seine hauls (0.90 fish/seine haul, 1.93 inches average length).

Crayfish, an important smallmouth bass forage species, were not captured from 2007-2009. Low numbers of crayfish were captured in 2006 (0.1 crayfish/gillnet) and 2005 (0.2 crayfish/gillnet). No crayfish were caught in the 2002-2004 gillnets. The crayfish historical average catch rate is 8.4 crayfish/gillnet for Green.

Tullibee "cisco" numbers were low in the 2009 summer (0.17 fish/gillnet) compared to historical catches and similar lakes. The tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 2.33 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. All of the tullibee were captured in one gillnet station located along the east portion of the lake at 30-40 feet deep. The 2009 summer tullibee average size was large (1.74 pounds and 15.00 inches) from gillnets. The tullibee historical average weight is 0.56 pounds from gillnets.

Yellow perch numbers were low in 2009 (2.58 fish/gillnet) compared to historical catches and similar lakes. The yellow perch historical average catch rate is 15.96 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2009 yellow perch average size was small (0.10 pounds and 6.23 inches) from gillnets. The yellow perch historical average weight is 0.13 pounds from gillnets. The 2009 yellow perch condition factor (Fulton K-Factor) was 1.102. Yellow perch condition factors have been near or below the Green normal range since 2003. Yellow perch growth rates were generally below the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-5. The 2006 (56%) and 2005 (31%) yellow perch year classes comprised the majority of the 2009 yellow perch gillnet catch.

Walleye numbers were low in 2009 (2.83 fish/gillnet) compared to historical catches and similar lakes. The walleye historical average catch rate is 8.86 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2009 walleye average size was moderate (1.38 pounds and 15.03 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average weight and length are 1.26 pounds and 14.68 inches from gillnets. The 2009 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches and larger) walleye (1.50 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (3.75 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. The walleye year classes of 2008 (12%), 2007 (21%), 2006 (35%), 2005 (9%), and 2004 (6%) comprised the majority of the 2009 gillnet catch. The recent walleye year classes since 2001 are due mostly to stocking. Walleye growth rates were within the lower end of the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-7. The condition factor for walleye greater than 12 inches (0.901) was at the lower end of the Green Lake normal range (0.901 - 0.938).

A fall electrofishing assessment of Green Lake was conducted during early October of 2009. The 2009 fall electrofishing assessment was conducted to evaluate walleye natural reproduction and a 2009 walleye fry stocking in Green Lake. Approximately one million OTC marked walleye fry were stocked each year during 2007 and 2008. Marked OTC walleye fingerlings (30,787 fish) accounted for 60% of the fingerlings stocked (51,641 fish) in Green during the 2008 fall. Two million OTC marked walleye fry were stocked in Green during 2009. The walleye fry were stocked in part as a 10% return of walleye eggs taken for the statewide propagation program. There were low young of year "YOY" walleye numbers (5.00 YOY/hour, 6.46 inches average length) captured in 2009. Walleye yearling numbers were also low (3.00 fish/hour, 9.44 inches average length) in the 2009 fall electrofishing survey. Marked fish from 2008 and 2009 stockings accounted for 50% of YOY walleye catch and 0% of the yearling walleye catch in the 2009 fall electrofishing. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average YOY walleye catch rate and length are 13.69 YOY/hour and 6.46 inches. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY walleye for Green occurred in 1994 (54.00 YOY/hour, 6.15 inches average size). Walleye fingerlings (74,082 fish, 3,081 pounds), yearlings (12 fish, 6 pounds), and fry (2,110,771 fish) were stocked into Green during early April-November of 2009. Green Lake has been stocked annually with walleye fry from 2000-2009 except for 2002. Various combinations of walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked yearly (2,000 - 4,000 pounds/year) since 2000 into Green Lake. During the 1990's, walleye fry were stocked in 1996 and fingerlings/yearlings/adults were stocked in 1994, 1992, 1990.

Rock bass numbers were moderate to abundant in 2009 (8.92 fish/gillnet) compared to historical catches and similar lakes. The rock bass historical average catch rate is 7.64 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2009 rock bass average size was small (0.30 pounds and 6.93 inches) from gillnets. The rock bass historical average weight is 0.42 pounds from gillnets.

Largemouth bass numbers were abundant in 2009 (1.17 fish/gillnet) compared to historical catches and similar lakes. The largemouth bass historical average catch rate is 0.56 fish/gillnet for Green. The 2009 largemouth bass average size was moderate (0.97 pounds and 11.10 inches) from gillnets. The largemouth bass historical average weight is 0.67 pounds from gillnets. Largemouth bass growth rates were within the low end of the Spicer Area normal ranges for age 1-7. The 2003 and 2006 largemouth bass year classes each comprised 20% of the 2009 largemouth bass assessment gillnet and trapnet catch.

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the 2010 fall for walleye natural reproduction, and 2010 summer for all fish species by assessment nets.

A population assessment of Green Lake was conducted during late July and early August of 2012. Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegill. Water levels were high to normal during the 2012 spring but 1-2 feet below normal by late summer due to drought conditions. Water clarity was moderate (10.5 feet) for Green Lake on July 30, 2012. Climate change effects have been noticeable for both habitat and species density changes in Green Lake during recent decades. Periphyton (algae, diatoms) and dead plant material now cover the boulder/rubble substrates generally all year long with exception of some narrow (<1 foot deep) windswept near shore areas. This has favored warm water species (black crappie, bass, bluegill, rock bass) which are nest spawners that guard and fan the eggs, unlike broadcast spawners such walleye and tullibee. In addition, increased densities of submergent vegetation such as invasive Eurasian watermilfoil have provided added habitat/cover for warm water fish species. The 2012 summer weather was dry and hot with many days of high temperatures above 90 F during several weeks of July. Narrow bands (1-3 feet) of marginal temperatures (<23.5 C) and dissolved oxygen levels (1-3 ppm) for tullibee were present at depths of 25-30 feet in Green during late July and early August of 2012. Dissolved oxygen levels and temperatures in Green were at potential summerkill levels of 2 ppm and 23.5 C for tullibee on both July 30th and August 9th of 2012. No summerkill events were reported or observed in Green or nearby Lake Koronis in 2012.

A few local residents reported a minor summerkill of dead tullibee near shore areas of Green during 2011. We observed only a few dead tullibee during the 2011 population assessment. A major summerkill of tullibee occurred during the same time period on nearby Lake Koronis in 2011 with pelicans feeding greatly on the dead fish. Green has been the only lake in the Spicer Area open to the public for fall gillnetting of tullibee during late November or early December each year since the late 1980's. Green Lake was not opened for tullibee gillnetting in 2012 due to the low numbers sampled in 2012 and recent years. Tullibee are an important forage fish for trophy northern pike in Green.

The threats of present (Eurasian watermilfoil, curly-leaf pondweed) and potential exotic invasive species introductions (i.e. zebra mussels, quagga mussels, spiny water flea, faucet snail, etc.) are of a major concern to local residents in Kandiyohi County. Eurasian watermilfoil "EWM" was first documented in Green Lake at several isolated sites during 2000. Both DNR and private attempts to chemically eradicate EWM permanently have been unsuccessful. Eurasian watermilfoil has spread throughout the lake in scattered stands especially near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, storm water inlet areas and off shore "break" (10-15 feet deep) areas since 2000.

EWM and curly-leaf pondweed tend to thrive in disturbed areas (i.e. previously chemically or mechanically treated areas, storm water inlets) or during years of minimal snowfall and maximum light penetration when competition from native species is minimal. Many large stands of EWM on Green Lake have been located near storm water inlets. Watershed projects that may reduce sediment and nutrient inputs from storm water inlets will also be important for controlling EWM in these patchy areas. Widespread-extensive matting of EWM on the surface is unlikely to occur throughout Green Lake unlike some milfoil infested lakes with protected bay areas (i.e. Minnetonka) due to frequent windswept conditions, the presence of relatively low nitrogen (ammonium) nutrient levels and unsuitable dominant substrates (boulder, rubble, gravel) present in the majority of shoal water areas of Green Lake. DNR Aquatic invasive species interns will continue to randomly monitor boats entering and leaving the many access sites in an attempt to educate and prevent the spread of exotics into Kandiyohi County Lakes.

Bluegill numbers were moderate in 2012 (34.00/trapnet) and within the normal ranges for similar lakes and Green. The Green Lake bluegill historical average catch rate is 47.26 fish/trapnet. The 2012 bluegill average size was large (0.27 pounds and 6.82 inches) from trapnets. The bluegill historical average weight is 0.13 pounds from trapnets. The 2012 catch rate of quality size (6.00 inches) and larger bluegill (27.93 fish/trapnet) was above the historical average (13.29 fish/trapnet). The 2012 catch rate of preferred size (8.00 inches) and larger bluegill (4.57 fish/trapnet) was also high compared to the historical average (0.54 fish/trapnet).

Black crappie numbers were abundant in 2012 gillnets (3.58 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green Lake and similar lakes. Black crappie abundance in the 2012 trapnets (0.86 fish/trapnet) was near the upper normal range for Green Lake. The Green Lake black crappie historical average catch rates are 1.08 fish/gillnet and 0.70 fish/trapnet. The 2012 black crappie average sizes were moderate from gillnets (0.42 pounds and 8.22 inches, but larger from trapnets (0.55 pounds and 9.75 inches). The black crappie historical average lengths are 7.85 inches for gillnets and 7.76 inches for trapnets in Green. The 2012 catch rate of quality size (8.00 inches) and larger black crappie (0.71 fish/trapnet) was above the historical average (0.35 fish/trapnet).

Northern pike numbers were abundant in 2012 (3.33 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for Green Lake, but near the low end of the normal range for similar lakes. The Green Lake northern pike historical average catch rate is 2.74 fish/gillnet. The 2012 northern pike average size was moderate (3.33 pounds and 24.13 inches) from gillnets. The northern pike historical average weight and length are 3.14 pounds and 23.31 inches from gillnets. The 2012 catch rate of preferred size (28.00 inches) and larger northern pike (0.58 fish/gillnet) was slightly above the historical average (0.43 fish/gillnet). Northern pike captured in 2003-2005, 2007, 2009 and 2012 assessments were notably lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. The 2012 northern pike condition factor (0.602) was below the Green Lake normal range (0.604-0.634). Low numbers of forage fish (yellow perch and tullibee) were documented in Green Lake assessments from 2003-2012. Northern pike growth rates were generally below the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-7. However, growth rates were within the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-7. The 2009 year class comprised 52% of the 2012 northern pike gillnet and trapnet catch.

Smallmouth bass numbers were moderate in 2012 (2.08 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for Green, but above the normal range for similar lakes. The smallmouth bass historical average catch rate is 1.94 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2012 smallmouth bass average size was small (0.89 pounds and 11.09 inches) from gillnets. The smallmouth bass historical average weight and length are 1.55 pounds and 13.39 inches from gillnets for Green Lake. The 2012 catch rate of preferred size (14.00 inches) and larger smallmouth bass (0.50 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (1.19 fish/gillnet). The 2012 smallmouth bass condition factor (1.309 Fulton K-Factor) was below normal range (1.401-1.536) for Green. Smallmouth bass condition factors have been near or below the Green normal ranges since 2000 except for 2004 and 2011. Smallmouth bass growth rates were generally below both the Green Lake and Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-4, within the normal ranges for ages 5-6 and above the normal ranges for age 7. Three smallmouth bass year classes (2011, 2009 and 2008) each comprised approximately 30% of the 2012 smallmouth bass gillnet catch.

Crayfish, an important smallmouth bass forage species, were not captured in 2007-2009 and 2012. Low numbers of crayfish were captured in 2011 (1.1 crayfish/gillnet), 2010 (0.3 crayfish/gillnet), 2006 (0.1 crayfish/gillnet) and 2005 (0.2 crayfish/gillnet). No crayfish were caught in the 2002-2004 gillnets. The crayfish historical average catch rate is 7.1 crayfish/gillnet for Green.

Tullibee "cisco" abundance in the 2012 summer (0.25 fish/gillnet) was below the normal ranges for Green Lake and similar lakes. The tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 2.31 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. A majority of the tullibee were captured in summer gillnet stations located along the east and south portions of the lake at depths between 25-30 feet. The 2012 summer tullibee average size was moderate to large (0.94 pounds and 12.83 inches) from gillnets. The tullibee historical summer average weight is 0.60 pounds from gillnets. All tullibee captured in the 2012 summer gillnets were from the 2009 year class.

There were low numbers of tullibee (8.33 fish/gillnet) captured in the 2012 fall special assessment. The 2012 fall tullibee average size was moderate to large (1.06 pounds and 13.61 inches) for Green. Tullibee growth rates were within or above the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1 7. The 2008 year class comprised 76% of the 2012 fall tullibee catch in Green Lake. There were no tullibee from 2009-2011 year classes present in the 2012 fall catch. Low numbers of tullibee were captured in nearby Lake Koronis (5.33 fish/gillnet, 14.91 inches average length) in the 2012 fall. The fall tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 76.5 fish/gillnet and 12.52 inches for Green Lake.

The lack of adult tullibee on the spawning grounds from early November to early December of 2010-2012 as sampled by both DNR and private netters during the open season is not a good indication for the long term sustainability of the tullibee population in Green Lake. Hopefully, cool summers will occur during the next several years, which may result in good hatches and survival of tullibee in Green Lake if adequate brood stock numbers are still present.

Yellow perch numbers were low in 2012 (0.58 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green Lake and similar lakes. The yellow perch historical average catch rate is 14.38 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2012 yellow perch average size was small (0.08 pounds and 6.25 inches) from gillnets. The yellow perch historical average weight is 0.12 pounds from gillnets. The 2012 catch rate of quality size (8.00 inches) and larger yellow perch was 0.00 fish/gillnet. The 2012 yellow perch condition factor (0.858 Fulton K-Factor) was below the normal range (1.081-1.246) for Green. Yellow perch condition factors have been near or below the Green normal ranges since 2003 except for 2004 and 2011.

Walleye numbers were moderately abundant in 2012 (10.08 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green Lake and similar lakes. The walleye historical average catch rate is 9.19 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2012 walleye average size was moderate (1.19 pounds and 14.18 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average weight and length are 1.26 pounds and 14.64 inches from gillnets. The 2012 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches) and larger walleye (3.42 fish/gillnet) was near the historical average (3.86 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. The 2012 catch rate of preferred size (20.00 inches) and larger walleye (1.17 fish/gillnet) was slightly above the historical average (0.76 fish/gillnet). The 2012 walleye condition factor (0.857 Fulton K-Factor) was below the normal range (0.873-0.907) for Green. Walleye growth rates were generally below both the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-5, but within the normal ranges for ages 6-8. Recent walleye year classes have been due mostly to stocking since 2001. The 2010 and 2009 walleye year classes comprised about 29% and 20% respectively of the 2012 walleye gillnet and trapnet catch. The 2011 and 2008 year classes each comprised 16% of the 2012 walleye gillnet and trapnet catch. OTC marked walleye (fry stocked) accounted for 86% of the 2011, 9% of the 2010, and 33% of the 2009 year classes captured in the 2012 gillnets.

Green Lake has been stocked annually with walleye fry (1-4 million) from 2000-2012 except for 2002. OTC marked walleye fry (1-2 million) were stocked in Green each year during 2000-2001 and 2007-2012. The walleye fry were stocked in part as a 10% return of walleye eggs taken for the statewide propagation program. Marked OTC walleye fingerlings (30,787 fish) accounted for 60% of the fingerlings stocked (51,641 fish) in Green during the 2008 fall. Walleye unmarked fingerlings (59,672 fish, 3,081 pounds) and OTC marked fry (1,827,749 fish) were last stocked into Green during 2012. Various combinations of walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) since 2000 into Green Lake. During the 1990's, walleye fry were stocked in 1996 and larger walleye (fingerlings and adults) were stocked in 1994, 1992 and 1990.

A fall electrofishing assessment of Green Lake was conducted on October 3, 2012. The 2012 fall electrofishing assessment was conducted to evaluate walleye natural reproduction and a 2012 walleye fry stocking in Green Lake. Low numbers of young of year "YOY" walleye were captured in 2012 fall electrofishing survey (12.00 YOY/hour, 6.87 inches average length). OTC marked fish (2012 fry stocked year class) comprised 55% of the 2012 YOY walleye catch in the 2012 walleye fall electrofishing survey. Moderate numbers of YOY walleye were captured in the previous 2011 fall electrofishing survey (31.00 YOY/hour, 6.46 inches average length). OTC marked YOY walleye (fry stocked) comprised 63.3% (19.62 YOY/hour) of the 2011 fall survey catch. The Spicer Area YOY walleye historical average catch rate is 81.31 YOY/hour. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average YOY walleye catch rate and length are 14.33 YOY/hour and 6.75 inches. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY walleye for Green occurred in 1994 (54.00 YOY/hour, 6.15 inches average size). Yearling walleye numbers (10.91 fish/hour, 9.79 inches) in the 2012 fall survey were comparable to the Green historical average (11.83 fish/hour, 9.64 inches average size). OTC Marked fish (2011 fry stocked year class) comprised approximately 80% of the yearling walleye captured in the 2012 fall electrofishing survey.

Rock bass numbers were abundant in 2012 (10.58 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green and similar lakes. The rock bass historical average catch rate is 7.93 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2012 rock bass average size was small (0.32 pounds and 6.97 inches) from gillnets. The rock bass historical average weight is 0.41 pounds from gillnets.

Largemouth bass numbers were abundant in 2012 (3.00 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green and similar lakes. The largemouth bass historical average catch rate is 0.73 fish/gillnet for Green. The 2012 largemouth bass average size was small (0.60 pounds and 9.15 inches) from gillnets. The largemouth bass historical average weight is 0.68 pounds from gillnets. Growth rates were generally below both the Green Lake and Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 2-5. The 2011 and 2008 largemouth year classes comprised 42% and 25% respectively of the 2012 largemouth bass gillnet and trapnet catch.

An Index of Biotic Integrity "IBI" survey was conducted from July 20-23, 2012 on Green Lake to compare small fish species presence versus lake characteristics (i.e. water quality, size, depth, productivity, etc.). Seine hauls were conducted with a bag seine of 50 foot width and 1/8 inch bar mesh in depths of 3.5 feet or less. Near shore electrofishing was conducted with a back-pack unit in water depths less than 2 feet deep. There are 20 stations that were spaced equally apart around the entire shoreline of the lake in a variety of near shore habitats and each station was approximately 100 feet long, but only 19 stations were sampled with both seining and electrofishing gears due to water levels, emergent vegetation, or unsuitable substrates for walking. Approximately 22 different fish species (19 species from electrofishing, 19 species from seining) were captured from electrofishing and seining combined. Fish species captured included gamefish (i.e. smallmouth bass and largemouth bass), panfish (bluegill, yellow perch, rock bass, pumpkinseed sunfish, green sunfish, and hybrid sunfish), large non-gamefish (yellow bullhead) and small non-gamefish (Iowa darter, johnny darter, banded killifish, longnose dace, tadpole madtom, pugnose shiner, golden shiner, spottail shiner, blackchin shiner, bluntnose minnow, brook silverside, brook stickleback and logperch). Young of year species captured included largemouth and smallmouth bass in seine hauls. Green Lake has greater numbers of fish species present than most other Spicer Area lakes.

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the 2013 fall for walleye natural reproduction, and 2013 summer for all fish species by assessment nets.

A targeted survey of Tullibee (Cisco) in Green Lake was conducted during mid-late November of 2015 using lake survey gillnets. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets, and possibly spring electrofishing for bass).

Green is a large (5,561 acres), and deep (110 feet maximum) lake located in Kandiyohi County. Tullibee were believed to be initially introduced into Green during the 1880's. Koronis is the only other Spicer Area lake with a self-sustaining Tullibee population. Tullibee spawn in 3-6 feet of water over bottom substrates consisting of large rock during late November to early December when the water temperature reaches 41 degrees Fahrenheit "F" or less. Spawning substrates in both Green and Koronis during recent years have been covered by periphyton/algae except in shallow (<1 foot) windswept shoal areas. Climate changes may be negatively affecting Tullibee natural reproduction/recruitment success in these lakes due to degrading spawning habitat and increasing numbers of warm water fish species (i.e. Rock Bass, Pumpkinseed, Smallmouth Bass, Largemouth Bass, etc.) which prey upon Tullibee eggs, fry or fingerlings.

Adult Tullibee are susceptible to summerkill in Green Lake if oxygen levels drop (<2 ppm) in the cooler deeper areas (<74 F) of the lake for an extended time (1-3 weeks) during late July to early August. Young Tullibee can tolerate warmer temperatures than adult Tullibee. The last reported summerkill on Green prior to 2011 was a minor event during 1995. Low dissolved oxygen (<2 ppm) levels were present at depths where preferred adult Tullibee temperatures (<74 F) occurred for a short time period in the 2010 late summer. Although no summerkill of Tullibee was reported for Green, a minor summerkill of adult Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2010. A major summerkill of Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2011, but only a minor kill occurred in Green during the 2011 summer. Drought conditions and extremely high air temperatures were the norm for the Spicer Area during July and early August of 2012. There were no apparent summerkills in Green or Koronis during 2012, but adult numbers were so low that summerkill events may not have been recognizable, especially due to the large numbers of pelicans living on Lake Koronis islands. A narrow band (1-3 feet) of marginal temperatures (<74 F) and dissolved oxygen levels (1-3 ppm) was present in depths of 25-30 feet in Green during late July and early August of 2012. Dissolved oxygen levels and temperatures in Green were at potential summerkill levels of 2 ppm and 74 F on both July 30th and August 9th of 2012. Summer temperature and oxygen conditions were more conducive for Tullibee survival during 2013-2015. Green has been the only lake in the Spicer Area open to the public for fall gillnetting of Tullibee during late November or early December each year since the late 1980's. Green Lake has been closed for Tullibee gillnetting since 2012 due to the low numbers sampled in recent years. Tullibee are an important forage fish for trophy northern pike in Green.

Tullibee numbers were moderate in a 2014 special assessment (mid-August) using vertical gillnets (51.0 fish/gang, 153 Tullibee total). There were five gillnets set per gang at three different deep water sites from the surface to bottom. Fish ranged in size from 3.2 to 16.5 inches from the seven different mesh sized panels of vertical gillnets. Young of year Tullibee (2014 year class) and age 6+ year classes comprised the majority of the 2014 vertical gillnet catch. Unlike vertical gillnets, standard summer lake survey gillnets are comprised of five different mesh sizes per net, 250 feet long and set in water depths with adequate oxygen levels (usually 10-40 feet deep) encompassing 6 feet of depth up from the bottom. Fall gillnet assessments utilize standard summer gillnets, but are set along shallow (< 6 feet) boulder bars during mid/late November when water temperatures are below 41 F.

Tullibee abundance in the 2015 summer standard gillnets (0.9 fish/gillnet) was near the 50th quartile for Green Lake (25th=0.3, 50th=0.8, 75th=2.6 fish/gillnet) and above the 25th quartile (0.5 fish/gillnet) for Lake Class 22 lakes. The Tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 2.1 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2015 Tullibee average size was small (0.79 pounds and 10.7 inches). The Tullibee historical average weight is 0.61 pounds from summer gillnets. Approximately 73% of Tullibee captured were from the 2012 year class in the summer gillnets.

Tullibee numbers were low (10.3 fish/gillnet, 13.7 inches) in the 2015 fall assessment. Tullibee abundance was similar (8.3 fish/gillnet, 13.61 inches) in the 2012 fall special assessment. Moderate numbers of Tullibee were captured in nearby Lake Koronis (19.7 fish fish/gillnet, 14.2 inches) in the 2015 fall. The fall Tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 76.5 fish/gillnet and 12.5 inches for Green Lake. The 2015 fall Tullibee condition factor (1.136) was at the 75th quartile for Green Lake. Tullibee growth rates were near the Green Lake 25th quartiles for ages 1-3, near the 50th quartile for age 4, and above the 75th quartiles for ages 4 and 5-7. The 2008 and 2009 year classes comprised 55% combined of the 2015 fall Tullibee catch in Green Lake. The 2012 and 2013 year classes comprised 26% and 13% respectively of the 2015 fall Tullibee catch. The inconsistency of Tullibee natural reproduction and adequate adult Tullibee numbers on the spawning grounds as sampled by the DNR is not a good indication for the long term sustainability of the Tullibee population in Green Lake. Hopefully, consecutive cool summers will continue to occur periodically, which may result in a good hatch, recruitment and survival of Tullibee to maintain a long term population in Green.

Improving and maintaining good water quality in Green is the key for Tullibee numbers to survive and flourish. Public fall gillnetting season will probably be postponed until the adult population rebounds to adequate levels. Current fish management activities on Green include monitoring the fish population on a periodic basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives, and stocking various fish species as warranted. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the 2016 summer for all fish species.

A standard survey of Green Lake was conducted during early August of 2017. A targeted fall electrofishing survey was conducted on September 27, 2017 to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye abundance in Green Lake. Targeted fall gillnetting surveys were conducted for Walleye during late September of 2017 and Tullibee during mid to late November of 2017. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets, and spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass). A creel survey was last conducted on Green Lake during 2015.

Green is a large (5,561 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), highly developed (690 homes) and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is currently infested with invasive species such as Curly-leaf Pondweed, Eurasian Watermilfoil and Zebra Mussels. Green is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Smallmouth Bass, Black Crappie (recent years) and Bluegill. There are approximately 48 inlets that enter Green Lake. The Middle Fork Crow River is the largest inlet and enters Green along the north shore and exits along the east side eventually flowing into Calhoun Lake. Direct nutrient runoff into Green is primarily from highway runoff and residential sources, which include lake homes and the city of Spicer. There is also upstream agricultural row crop runoff that enters into the Middle Fork Crow River. Water clarity was excellent (18.0 feet) for Green Lake on July 31, 2017. There were adequate dissolved oxygen (>3 ppm) and temperature conditions (<74 F) for Tullibee survival at depths of 27-36 feet during the 2017 survey and 40-60 feet during the 2016 survey. Submergent vegetation densities appeared lower in Green and other Spicer Area lakes during the 2017 summer. Emergent vegetation such as Hardstem Bulrush is abundant in the outlet bay. A moderate stand of bulrush is present along the southeast shore. Shoalwater substrates are mostly sand, gravel, rubble and boulder. The 2017 summer weather was moderate to cooler compared to previous summers. Recent ice on dates were December 12, 2017, December 10, 2016 and December 27, 2015. Snow and mild temperatures resulted in poor conditions (<6 inches of ice), thus limiting access on Green and many other local lakes during December of 2016. Similar poor ice conditions occurred during early to mid-December of 2017. Several vehicles went through the ice adjacent to ice heaves near the Spicer public access during January of 2018. Recent ice off dates were March 21, 2017 and March 22, 2016 which were the second and third earliest occurrences for Green Lake.

Climate change and invasive species effects have been noticeable for both habitat and species density changes in Green Lake during recent decades. Periphyton (algae, diatoms) and dead plant material now cover the boulder/rubble substrates generally all year long with the exception of some narrow (<1 foot deep) windswept near shore areas. This has favored warm water species (Black Crappie, Largemouth Bass, Bluegill, Rock Bass) which are nest spawners, unlike broadcast spawners such Walleye and Tullibee "Cisco". Increased densities of submergent vegetation such as invasive Eurasian Watermilfoil have provided added habitat/cover for many fish species. The most frequently observed submergent and algal vegetation species or groups for Green have included Chara, Stonewort, Eurasian Watermilfoil, River Pondweed, Water Moss, Clasping-leaf Pondweed, Sago Pondweed and Curly-leaf Pondweed.

Eurasian Watermilfoil was first documented in Green Lake at several isolated sites during 2000. Both DNR and private attempts to chemically eradicate it have been unsuccessful. Private applicators are currently using agricultural based global positioning techniques to better target a specific granular herbicide to known Eurasian Watermilfoil stands. Unfortunately, Eurasian Watermilfoil has spread throughout the lake in scattered stands especially near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, storm water inlet areas and off shore "break" (10-15 feet deep) areas since 2000. Eurasian Watermilfoil and Curly-leaf Pondweed tend to thrive in disturbed areas (i.e. previous chemically or mechanically treated areas, storm water inlets) or during years of minimal snowfall and maximum light penetration when competition from native species is minimal. Watershed projects that may reduce sediment and nutrient inputs from storm water inlets will also be important for controlling it in these patchy areas. Widespread-extensive matting of Eurasian Watermilfoil on the surface is unlikely to occur throughout Green Lake unlike some Eurasian Watermilfoil infested lakes with protected shallow bay areas (i.e. Minnetonka) due to frequent windswept conditions, the presence of relatively low nitrogen (ammonium) nutrient levels, and unsuitable dominant substrates (boulder, rubble, gravel) present in the majority of shoal water areas of Green Lake. The frequency of occurrence of Eurasian Watermilfoil in transects had increased from 4 sites in 2003, 16 sites in 2007, 20 sites in 2008 and 28 sites in 2013. Mean abundance at transect sites has increased in a similar trend from 2003 (1.3%) to 2013 (12.0%).

The threats of present (Zebra Mussels, Eurasian Watermilfoil and Curly-leaf Pondweed) and potential exotic invasive species introductions (i.e. Starry Stonewort, Quagga Mussels, Spiny Water Flea, Faucet Snail, etc.) are of a major concern to local residents in Kandiyohi County. One adult Zebra Mussel was found on a dock along the southeast shore of Green during the early summer of 2014. No additional Zebra Mussels were found until the fall of 2014. Numerous small young Zebra Mussels were found attached on docks and boat lifts scattered throughout Green Lake in 2015. Zebra Mussels were abundant within Green Lake during 2017, especially small mussels attached to aquatic vegetation (chara). Water clarity greatly increased during 2017 in response to the high densities of Zebra Mussel. The secchi reading was 18 feet on July 31, 2017. Eradication techniques (e.g. potassium chloride "potash", zequanox, copper sulfate, etc.) have been recently tried in metro area lakes where Zebra Mussel populations have not spread throughout the lake. Zequanox is a combination of specific dead bacteria cells which are toxic to Zebra Mussels. Eradication of Zebra Mussels is improbable once mussels spread throughout a lake due to their ability to reproduce large numbers of young Zebra Mussel "veligers" by a small number of adults. Green Lake will continue to be monitored to document the impacts Zebra Mussels may have on the lake ecology (i.e. water clarity, substrate effects, aquatic vegetation, plankton abundance, native species responses, etc.).

Black Crappie numbers were low in 2017 trapnets (0.87 fish/trapnet), but the average size was moderate (0.44 pounds, 9.04 inches). There were moderately abundant numbers of small sized (0.23 pounds and 6.66 inches) Black Crappie caught in the 2017 gillnets (2.50 fish/gillnet). Most of these small fish in gillnets were from the 2016 year class. The Black Crappie historical average catch rates are 1.30 fish/gillnet and 0.77 fish/trapnet. Growth rates were within or above the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-5. The 2016 year class comprised 38% of the 2017 Black Crappie summer gillnet and trapnet survey catch.

Bluegill numbers were moderately abundant in 2017 (21.53 fish/trapnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes. The Green Lake Bluegill historical average catch rate is 44.65 fish/trapnet. The 2017 Bluegill average size was large (0.26 pounds and 6.72 inches) from trapnets. The Bluegill historical average weight is 0.14 pounds from trapnets. There were abundant numbers of 8.00 inches and larger Bluegill (3.19 fish/trapnet) in the 2017 trapnets. The 2017 catch rate of quality size (6.00 inches and larger) Bluegill growth rates were within or above the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 5-8. The 2011 year class comprised 30% of the 2017 Bluegill summer gillnet and trapnet catch.

Largemouth Bass abundance in 2017 (2.50 fish/gillnet) was above the 75th quartiles for Green (25th=0.06, 50th=0.41, 75th=1.10 fish/gillnet) and Lake Class 22 lakes (75th=1.20 fish/gillnet).
