The Largemouth Bass historical average catch rate is 0.84 fish/gillnet. The 2017 Largemouth Bass average weight and length were 0.95 pounds and 11.34 inches from gillnets. The Largemouth Bass historical average weight is 0.70 pounds from gillnets. Largemouth Bass growth rates were near the Green Lake 75th quartiles for ages 1-7, but near or below the Spicer Area 50th quartiles. The 2013 and 2014 year classes each comprised 24% of the 2017 Largemouth Bass summer survey catch.

Northern Pike numbers were abundant in 2017 (4.08 fish/gillnet) compared to the Green Lake historical average catch rate (2.75 fish/gillnet). The 2017 Northern Pike average size was moderate (3.94 pounds and 24.96 inches) from gillnets. The Northern Pike historical average weight and length are 3.19 pounds and 23.49 inches from gillnets. The 2017 catch rate of 28.00 inches and larger Northern Pike (1.33 fish/gillnet) was above the historical average (0.46 fish/gillnet). Northern Pike have been generally lean in appearance or poor condition compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. Smaller sized Northern Pike (<24.00 inches) were in poor condition, but not larger fish (>24.00 inches) in 2017. Low numbers of forage fish (Yellow Perch and Tullibee) have been documented in Green Lake surveys from 2003-2016. Growth rates were below the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-7. The 2014 year class comprised 30% of the 2017 Northern Pike summer catch.

Rock Bass abundance in 2017 (13.08 fish/gillnet) was above the 75th quartiles (25th=5.75, 50th=8.65, 75th=11.90 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake and Lake Class 22 lakes (75th=6.63 fish/gillnet). The Rock Bass historical average catch rate is 8.73 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2017 Rock Bass average weight and length were 0.48 pounds and 8.20 inches from gillnets. The Rock Bass historical average weight is 0.41 pounds from gillnets.

Smallmouth Bass were moderately abundant in 2017 (1.83 fish/gillnet). The Smallmouth Bass historical average catch rate is 1.83 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2017 Smallmouth Bass average size was large (1.70 pounds and 13.66 inches) from gillnets. Growth rates were generally within the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-6. The 2010 and 2011 year classes each comprised 23% and 18% respectively of the 2017 Smallmouth Bass summer gillnet catch.

Crayfish, an important Smallmouth Bass forage species, have been present in low numbers since 1999. Low numbers of crayfish were captured in 2017 (0.17 crayfish/gillnet), 2015 (0.08 crayfish/gillnet), 2014 (0.08 crayfish/gillnet), 2011 (1.1 crayfish/gillnet), 2010 (0.3 crayfish/gillnet), 2006 (0.1 crayfish/gillnet) and 2005 (0.2 crayfish/gillnet). No crayfish were caught in the 2002-2004, 2007-2009, 2012-13 and 2016 gillnets. The crayfish historical average catch rate is 5.5 crayfish/gillnet for Green. Research has identified crayfish and Pumpkinseed as predators on smaller Zebra Mussels. We did observe numerous small crayfish in the stomachs of Smallmouth Bass. Crayfish numbers may increase in the future due to a new forage species "Zebra Mussel" present in Green. In response, this may also provide a greater forage base "crayfish" for Smallmouth Bass.

Tullibee were not present in the 2017 summer gillnet catch. The Tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 2.06 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. A targeted September gillnetting survey was conducted primarily to assess the Walleye population. There were 12 gillnets set at standard summer stations during September of 2017. In addition, 2 special gillnets were also set in deeper water (40-50 feet deep), adjacent to standard sets near Hultgren's and Gratz's Bars. Tullibee (5.50 fish/special gillnet, 11.43 inches) were only captured at these two sites during the September targeted gillnetting survey.

Tullibee numbers were low (0.50 fish/gillnet, 11.25 inches) in the 2017 November survey. Tullibee abundance was higher in the 2012 (8.33 fish/gillnet, 13.61 inches) and 2015 (10.33 fish/gillnet, 13.66 inches) fall surveys. Moderate numbers of Tullibee were captured in nearby Lake Koronis (19.67 fish fish/gillnet, 14.17 inches) in the 2015 fall, but low numbers in 2017 (10.33 fish/gillnet, 14.41 inches). The fall Tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 70.30 fish/gillnet and 12.48 inches for Green Lake. Tullibee growth rates were below the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1 5. The 2012 year class comprised 45% and 100% respectively of the 2017 September and November Tullibee survey catches. There were adequate dissolved oxygen (>3 ppm) and temperature conditions (<74 F) for Tullibee survival at depths of 27-36 feet during the 2017 survey and 40-60 feet during the 2016 survey. Green Lake has not been opened for Tullibee public gillnetting since 2011 due to the low Tullibee numbers sampled in recent years. Tullibee are an important forage fish, especially for larger Northern Pike and Walleye in Green. Tullibee can also provide a secondary fishing opportunity during the winter months.

Yellow Perch numbers were low in 2017 (0.42 fish/gillnet). The Yellow Perch historical average catch rate is 12.34 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. Yellow Perch catch rates have been <10.00 fish/gillnet since 2003. Local anglers have reported in past years seeing numerous small Yellow Perch amongst the chara beds with cameras during the summer or while spearing in the winter. Our standard gillnets may not effectively sample these small (<5.0 inches) Yellow Perch. Predation pressures from various species (i.e. Rock Bass, Largemouth Bass, Walleye, etc.) may have also selected for smaller sized and earlier reproducing Yellow Perch restricted to near bottom habitat containing dense chara beds in Green. The 2017 Yellow Perch average size was small (0.09 pounds and 6.23 inches) from gillnets. The 2014 year class comprised 80% of the 2017 Yellow Perch summer survey catch.

Green Lake was stocked annually with Walleye fry (1-4 million) from 2000-2013 except for 2002. Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked Walleye fry (1-2 million) were stocked in Green each year during 2000-2001, 2007-2013 and 2016. No Walleye fry were stocked in 2014 or 2015 due to the cessation of egg take operations on Green Lake. Walleye fry stocked during previous years were mostly part of a 10% return of Walleye eggs taken for the statewide propagation program. Walleye unmarked Spicer strain fingerlings and yearlings (18,413 fish, 1,784 pounds) were stocked into Green during the 2016 fall. Green Lake was stocked with Spicer strain fin clipped adults (196 pounds, 192 fish) and yearlings (2,081 pounds, 3,936 fish) in 2017 fall. Spicer strain (1,173 pounds, 16,064 fish) and Pike River strain (117 pounds, 936 fish) fingerlings were also stocked in the 2017 fall. Various combinations of Walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) since 2000 into Green Lake.

No YOY Walleye were captured during the 2017, 2016 or 2015 fall electrofishing surveys. Low YOY Walleye numbers were captured in the 2014 (4.00 YOY/hour, 7.62 inches average length) and 2013 (5.00 YOY/hour, 6.40 inches average length) fall electrofishing surveys. "OTC marked fry captured as fingerlings comprised 40% of the 2013 and 55% (6.60 YOY/hour) of the 2012 fall electrofishing surveys. Moderate numbers of YOY Walleye were captured in a previous 2011 fall electrofishing survey (31.00 YOY/hour, 6.46 inches average length). OTC marked YOY Walleye (fry stocked) comprised 63.3% (19.62 YOY/hour) of the 2011 fall YOY Walleye survey catch. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average YOY Walleye catch rate and length are 11.83 YOY/hour and 6.77 inches. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY Walleye for Green occurred in 1994 (54.00 YOY/hour, 6.15 inches average size). Yearling Walleye numbers were moderate to low in the 2014 (6.00 fish/hour) and 2016 (3.00 fish/hour) fall surveys. No yearling Walleye were captured in the 2017 and 2015 fall electrofishing surveys.

Walleye numbers were low in 2017 summer gillnets (4.25 fish/gillnet) compared to the Green historical average catch rate (8.68 fish/gillnet). The 2017 Walleye average size was moderate (1.40 pounds and 15.65 inches) from gillnets. The Walleye historical average weight and length are 1.27 pounds and 14.70 inches from gillnets. The 2017 catch rate of 15.00 inches and larger Walleye (2.33 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (3.68 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. Walleye growth rates were generally below the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 3-8. Recent Walleye year classes have been due mostly to stocking since 2001. The 2017 walleye survey catch was comprised primarily of 2011 (15%), 2012 (11%), 2013 (15%), 2014 (20%), 2015 (25%) and 2016 (8%) year classes. The 2011 Walleye year class was successful in many area lakes. OTC marked Walleye (fry stocked) accounted for 43%, 22%, 17% and 100% respectively of the 2011, 2012, 2013 and 2016 year classes caught in the 2017 Walleye combined summer and fall survey catches. YOY Walleye catch rates from 5-30 fish per hour due to fry stockings or natural reproduction may be adequate for providing a moderate year class in larger or clearer lakes. However, future Walleye fry stockings and natural reproduction may be less successful in Green due to poor survival from potential negative effects on zooplankton populations by Zebra Mussels. Continued Walleye fingerling or yearling stockings may be necessary to maintain adequate Walleye numbers in Green.

Other species captured included low numbers of White Sucker (0.25 fish/gillnet), Common Carp (0.80 fish/trapnet), Pumpkinseed (0.33 fish/trapnet), Hybrid Sunfish (2.27 fish/trapnet) and Black Bullhead (0.08 fish/gillnet) during 2017. Moderate numbers of large Yellow Bullhead were also captured in 2017 (2.67 fish/gillnet, 0.96 pounds average weight).

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking Walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the fall of 2018 for YOY Walleye abundance, and the summer of 2018 for all fish species by standard survey nets.

A standard survey of Green Lake was conducted during late July to early August of 2019. A targeted fall electrofishing survey was conducted on October 7, 2019 to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye abundance in Green Lake. Targeted fall gillnetting surveys were conducted for Yellow Perch (mid-September) and Walleye (late September) in 2019. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets, and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass). A creel survey was conducted on Green Lake during 2019 summer and scheduled for 2019-2020 winter.

Green is a large (5,561 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), highly developed (690 homes) and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is currently infested with invasive species such as Curly-leaf Pondweed, Eurasian Watermilfoil and Zebra Mussels. Green is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Smallmouth Bass, Black Crappie (recent years) and Bluegill. There are approximately 48 inlets that enter Green Lake. The Middle Fork Crow River is the largest inlet and enters Green along the north shore and exits along the east side eventually flowing into Calhoun Lake. The 2019 summer was cooler with more rainfall than normal. The secchi reading was 9.7 feet on July 30, 2019. Water levels were above normal during 2019. Direct nutrient runoff into Green is primarily from highway runoff and residential sources, which include lake homes and the city of Spicer. There is also upstream agricultural row crop runoff that enters into the Middle Fork Crow River. There were adequate dissolved oxygen (>3 ppm) and temperature conditions (<74 F) for Tullibee survival at depths of 20-30 feet during 2019, 20-35 feet during the 2018 survey, 27-36 feet during the 2017 survey, and 40-60 feet during the 2016 survey. Submergent vegetation appeared less dense in 2019 than previous survey years. Emergent vegetation such as Hardstem Bulrush is abundant in the outlet bay. A moderate stand of bulrush is present along the southeast shore. Shoalwater substrates are mostly sand, gravel, rubble and boulder. Recent ice on dates were December 2, 2019; November 27, 2018; December 12, 2017; December 10, 2016; and December 27, 2015. Recent ice off dates were April 23, 2019; May 7, 2018; March 21, 2017; and March 22, 2016 for Green Lake.

The threats of present (Zebra Mussels, Eurasian Watermilfoil and Curly-leaf Pondweed) and potential exotic invasive species introductions (i.e. Starry Stonewort, Quagga Mussels, Spiny Water Flea, Faucet Snail, etc.) are of a major concern to local residents in Kandiyohi County. Climate change and invasive species effects have been noticeable for both habitat and species density changes in Green Lake during recent decades. Periphyton (filamentous algae, diatoms) and dead plant material now cover the boulder/rubble substrates generally all year long with the exception of some narrow (<1 foot deep) windswept near shore areas due to warmer waters and increased near shore nutrient deposition. This has favored warm water species (Black Crappie, Largemouth Bass, Bluegill, Rock Bass) which are nest spawners, unlike broadcast spawners such Walleye and Tullibee "Cisco". Furthermore, increased densities of submergent vegetation species such as invasive Eurasian watermilfoil since 2000 have provided added habitat/cover for many warm water fish species. Eurasian watermilfoil has spread throughout the lake in scattered stands especially near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, storm water inlet areas and off shore "break" (10-15 feet deep) areas since 2000. It was more prevalent in water depths greater than 10 feet and less frequent in shallower water during 2018 and 2019. Zebra Mussels have decreased free open water green algal abundance resulting in lower densities of zooplankton, shifted energy and nutrient transfers from open water to bottom habitats, altered predator-prey relationships, decreased fish condition factors and also increased water clarity since 2014. Several other area lakes (Andrew, Diamond, Eagle, Elkhorn, George, Nest, Norway and Games) were recently reported as infested with Zebra Mussels in 2017-2018.

Black Crappie numbers were moderate in 2019 gillnets (2.08 fish/gillnet and 1.73 fish/trapnet). The Black Crappie historical average catch rates are 1.32 fish/gillnet and 0.80 fish/trapnet. The 2019 Black Crappie average sizes were large from gillnets (0.56 pounds and 9.75 inches), but moderate from trapnets (0.41 pounds and 8.99 inches). In recent years, Black Crappie have been targeted more frequently by both summer and winter anglers based on anecdotal and creel survey reports.

Bluegill numbers were moderate in 2019 (30.20 fish/trapnet). The Green Lake Bluegill historical average catch rate is 43.09 fish/trapnet. The 2019 Bluegill average size was small (0.12 pounds and 5.17 inches) from trapnets. The largest Bluegill captured was 9.37 inches in the 2019 summer survey. Bluegill growth rates were below the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-5. The 2015 year class comprised 29% of the 2019 Bluegill summer gillnet and trapnet catch. Bluegill ages 6 and older comprised 16% of the 2019 Bluegill summer catch. Anglers often target Eurasian watermilfoil stands when fishing for Bluegill in Green Lake.

Largemouth Bass numbers were abundant in 2019 (1.58 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average catch rate (0.88 fish/gillnet). The 2019 Largemouth Bass average size was moderate (0.92 pounds and 11.51 inches) from gillnets. Largemouth Bass growth rates were slow for ages 1-7. The 2016 year class comprised 32% of the 2019 Largemouth Bass summer survey catch.

Northern Pike numbers were abundant in 2019 (5.00 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average catch rate is 2.84 fish/gillnet. The 2019 Northern Pike average size was small (2.44 pounds and 21.33 inches) from gillnets. The Northern Pike historical average weight and length are 3.16 pounds and 23.37 inches from gillnets. The largest Northern Pike captured was 40.55 inches from the 2019 summer survey. Northern Pike have been generally lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. Low numbers of forage fish (Yellow Perch and Tullibee) have been documented in Green Lake surveys from 2003-2019. Northern Pike growth rates were slow for ages 1-5. The 2016 year class comprised 26% of the 2019 Northern Pike summer catch. Northern Pike possession limit regulations for Green in the North-central Zone are as follows: anglers can keep 10 Northern Pike, but not more than two pike longer than 26 inches; and all from 22 to 26 inches must be released. Northern Pike taken by spearing follow the same rules except one pike may be between 22 and 26 inches or two larger than 26 inches.

Rock Bass numbers were abundant in 2019 (19.25 fish/gillnet) and the highest recorded catch for Green. The Rock Bass historical average catch rate is 9.15 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. Rock Bass catch rates were rarely greater than 10.00 fish/gillnet prior to 2001. The 2019 Rock Bass average size was large (0.57 pounds and 8.69 inches) from gillnets. The Rock Bass historical average weight is 0.42 pounds from gillnets.

Smallmouth Bass numbers were low in 2019 (1.08 fish/gillnet). The Smallmouth Bass historical average catch rate is 1.77 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2019 Smallmouth Bass average size was large (1.45 pounds and 12.20 inches) from gillnets. Smallmouth Bass growth rates were within the Green Lake normal ranges. There were no dominant Smallmouth Bass year classes in the summer gillnet catch.

Large sized Crayfish, an important Smallmouth Bass forage species, have been present in low numbers since 1999. Moderate numbers of crayfish were captured in both 2019 summer and fall gillnet surveys (2.17 crayfish/gillnet). Low numbers (<1.00 crayfish/gillnet) or no crayfish were captured from 2002-2018 gillnets. The crayfish historical average catch rate is 5.20 crayfish/gillnet for Green. Research has identified crayfish and Pumpkinseed Sunfish as predators on smaller Zebra Mussels. We did observe numerous small sized crayfish in the stomachs of Smallmouth Bass and Rock Bass. Crayfish numbers may increase in the future due to a new forage species "Zebra Mussel" present in Green. In response, this may also provide a greater forage base "crayfish" for Smallmouth Bass.

Tullibee were not present in the 2017-2019 summer gillnet catches. The Tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 1.88 fish/gillnet for Green Lake.

A November targeted gillnet survey was conducted for Tullibee in 2019. Tullibee numbers were low in 2019 November survey (1.75 fish/gillnet, 13.92 inches). Tullibee numbers were low (0.50 fish/gillnet, 11.25 inches) in the previous 2017 November targeted survey. Tullibee abundance was higher in the 2012 (8.33 fish/gillnet, 13.61 inches) and 2015 (10.33 fish/gillnet, 13.66 inches) fall surveys. The fall Tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 67.43 fish/gillnet and 12.56 inches for Green Lake. Tullibee growth rates were slow for ages 1 5. The 2014 year class comprised 57% of the 2019 November Tullibee survey catch. Green Lake has not been opened for Tullibee public gillnetting since 2011 due to the low Tullibee numbers sampled in recent years. Tullibee are an important forage fish, especially for larger Northern Pike and Walleye in Green. Tullibee can also provide a secondary fishing opportunity during the winter months.

Yellow Perch numbers were low in 2019 (2.25 fish/gillnet). The Yellow Perch historical average catch rate is 11.73 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2019 Yellow Perch average size was small (0.13 pounds and 6.48 inches) from gillnets. Yellow Perch growth rates were slow for ages 1-4. The 2015 year class comprised 64% of the 2019 Yellow Perch summer survey catch.

Local anglers have reported in past years seeing numerous small Yellow Perch amongst the Chara "Muskgrass" beds with cameras during the summer or while spearing in the winter. Our standard gillnets may not effectively sample these small (<5.0 inches) Yellow Perch. Predation pressures from various species (i.e. Rock Bass, Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Walleye, etc.) may have also selected for smaller sized and earlier reproducing Yellow Perch restricted to near bottom habitat containing dense Chara beds in Green. A statewide study will examining Yellow Perch catchability, growth and maturity using small mesh gillnets in Green and other lakes in 2019.

Green Lake was stocked annually with Walleye fry (1-4 million) from 2000-2013 except for 2002. Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked Walleye fry (1-2 million) were stocked in Green each year during 2000-2001, 2007-2013 and 2016-2018. Fry were marked with OTC to document the contribution to the Walleye population versus natural reproduction or fingerling stockings in later surveys. No Walleye fry were stocked in 2019, 2014 or 2015 due in part to the cessation of egg take operations on Green Lake. Walleye fry stocked during previous years were mostly part of a 10% return of Walleye eggs taken for the statewide propagation program. Various combinations of Walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) from 2000-2017 into Green Lake. Walleye yearlings (701 fish, 150 pounds) and adult (300 fish, 150 pounds) were stocked by private sources in 2019.

Low YOY Walleye numbers were captured in the 2019 (4.00 YOY/hour, 7.24 inches), 2018 (1.00 YOY/hour, 7.13 inches), 2014 (4.00 YOY/hour, 7.62 inches), 2013 (5.00 YOY/hour, 6.40 inches) and 2012 (12.00 YOY/hour, 6.87 inches) fall electrofishing surveys. No YOY Walleye were captured during the 2017, 2016 or 2015 fall electrofishing surveys. OTC marked fry captured as fingerlings comprised 40% of the 2013 and 55% (6.60 YOY/hour) of the 2012 fall electrofishing surveys. Moderate numbers of YOY Walleye were captured in a previous 2011 fall electrofishing survey (31.00 YOY/hour, 6.46 inches average length). OTC marked YOY Walleye (fry stocked) comprised 63.3% (19.62 YOY/hour) of the 2011 fall YOY Walleye survey catch. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average YOY Walleye catch rate and length are 11.14 YOY/hour and 6.81 inches. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY Walleye for Green occurred in 1994 (54.00 YOY/hour, 6.15 inches).

Walleye numbers were low in 2019 summer gillnets (5.17 fish/gillnet), but higher than the 2017 (4.25 fish/gillnet) and 2018 (3.25 fish/gillnet) summer survey numbers. The Walleye historical average catch rate is 8.42 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2019 Walleye average size was moderate (1.56 pounds and 15.57 inches) from gillnets. The Walleye historical average weight and length are 1.29 pounds and 14.82 inches from gillnets. Walleye growth rates were slow compared to Spicer Area Lakes, but above the normal ranges for Green Lake. Recent Walleye year classes have been due mostly to stocking since 2001. The 2019 walleye summer survey catch was comprised of a variety of year classes with 68% of the fish coming from 2015-2018 year classes. OTC marked Walleye (fry stocked) accounted for 78% respectively of the 2018 year class caught in the 2019 Walleye summer and fall survey catches. OTC marked fish (fry stocked) made up 36% of the total Walleye catch from marked year classes in the 2019 fall and summer gillnets combined. Population estimates were made from the 2017 fall stocking of 3,936 yearling fin clipped Walleye and the 2018 and 2019 summer and fall survey combined catches. We estimated a 2018 fall Walleye population of 15,390 age 2 fish. A 2019 fall Walleye population was estimated at 8,311 age 3 fish. YOY Walleye catch rates from 5-30 fish per hour due to fry stockings or natural reproduction may be adequate for providing a moderate year class in larger or clearer lakes. However, Zebra Mussels may negatively affect future Walleye fry stockings and natural reproduction by reducing zooplankton food availability, thus causing poor Walleye first year survival. Continued Walleye fingerling or yearling stockings may be necessary to maintain adequate Walleye numbers in Green.

Other species captured included low numbers of White Sucker (0.33 fish/gillnet), Common Carp (0.40 fish/trapnet), Pumpkinseed (0.40 fish/trapnet), Hybrid Sunfish (2.53 fish/trapnet) and Black Bullhead (0.25 fish/gillnet) during 2019. Abundant numbers of large Yellow Bullhead were also captured in 2019 (6.42 fish/gillnet, 0.70 pounds average weight).

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking Walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the fall of 2020 for YOY Walleye abundance, 2022 fall for Tullibee and the summer of 2020 for all fish species by standard survey nets.

A targeted survey of Tullibee (Cisco) in Green Lake was conducted during mid-late November of 2019 using lake survey gillnets. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass).

Green is a large (5,561 acres), and deep (110 feet maximum) lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is currently infested with invasive species such as Curly-leaf Pondweed, Eurasian Watermilfoil and Zebra Mussels. A standard survey (summer gillnets and trapnets) of Green Lake was also conducted during late July through early August of 2019. A targeted fall gillnetting and boom electrofishing survey were conducted for small sized Yellow Perch in mid-September of 2019. A targeted gillnetting survey was conducted for Walleye during late September of 2019. A fall electrofishing survey was conducted on October 7, 2019 to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye abundance in Green Lake.

Tullibee were believed to be initially introduced into Green during the 1880's. Koronis is the only other Spicer Area lake with a self-sustaining Tullibee population. Tullibee spawn in 3-6 feet of water over bottom substrates consisting of large rock during late November to early December when the water temperature reaches 41 degrees Fahrenheit "F" or less. Spawning substrates in both Green and Koronis during recent years have been covered by periphyton/filamentous algae except in shallow (<1 foot) windswept shoal areas. Increased phosphorus inputs or availability often result in greater blue-green and filamentous algae blooms. Climate changes (e.g. warmer temperatures, additional growing days, increased storm/runoff activity, etc.) coupled with continued nutrient inputs and Zebra Mussel impacts may be negatively affecting Tullibee natural reproduction and recruitment success in these lakes due to degrading spawning habitat and increasing numbers of warm water fish species (e.g. Rock Bass, Pumpkinseed, Smallmouth Bass, Largemouth Bass, etc.) which prey upon Tullibee eggs, fry or fingerlings.

Adult Tullibee are susceptible to summerkill in Green Lake if oxygen levels drop (<2 ppm) in the cooler deeper areas (<74 F) of the lake for an extended time (1-3 weeks) during late July to early August. Young Tullibee can tolerate warmer temperatures than adult Tullibee. The last reported summerkill on Green prior to 2011 was a minor event during 1995. Low dissolved oxygen (<2 ppm) levels were present at depths where preferred adult Tullibee temperatures (<74 F) occurred for a short time period in the 2010 late summer. Although no summerkill of Tullibee was reported for Green, a minor summerkill of adult Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2010. A major summerkill of Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2011, but only a minor kill occurred in Green during the 2011 summer. Drought conditions and extremely high air temperatures were the norm for the Spicer Area during July and early August of 2012. There were no apparent summerkills in Green or Koronis during 2012, but adult numbers were so low that summerkill events may not have been recognizable, especially due to the large numbers of pelicans living on Lake Koronis' islands. A narrow band (1-3 feet) of marginal temperatures (<74 F) and dissolved oxygen levels (1-3 ppm) was present in depths of 25-30 feet in Green during late July and early August of 2012. Dissolved oxygen levels and temperatures in Green were at potential summerkill levels of 2 ppm and 74 F on both July 30th and August 9th of 2012. Summer temperature and oxygen conditions were more conducive for Tullibee survival during 2013-2019.

Zebra Mussels were first observed in Green Lake in 2014. Presently, Zebra Mussels are abundant within the lake. It is unknown the extent Zebra Mussels will affect Tullibee and the corresponding forage base. Green was the only lake in the Spicer Area open to the public for fall gillnetting of Tullibee during late November or early December each year from the late 1980's to 2011. Green Lake has been closed for Tullibee gillnetting since 2012 due to the low numbers sampled in recent years. Tullibee are an important forage fish for trophy Northern Pike in Green.

Tullibee were not present in the 2017-2019 summer standard survey catches. The Tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 1.88 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. A targeted September gillnetting survey was conducted primarily to assess the Walleye population. There were 12 gillnets set at standard summer stations during September of 2017-2019. In addition, 2 special gillnets were also set in deeper water (40-50 feet deep), adjacent to standard sets near Hultgren's and Gratz's Bars during 2017. Tullibee (5.50 fish/special gillnet, 11.43 inches) were only captured at these two sites during the 2017 September gillnetting survey.

Tullibee numbers were low in 2019 (1.75 fish/gillnet, 13.94 inches) and 2017 (0.50 fish/gillnet, 11.25 inches) November surveys. Tullibee abundance was higher in the 2012 (8.33 fish/gillnet, 13.61 inches) and 2015 (10.33 fish/gillnet, 13.66 inches) November surveys. Moderate numbers of Tullibee were captured in nearby Lake Koronis in 2019 (27.50 fish/gillnet, 15.75 inches) and 2015 (19.67 fish fish/gillnet, 14.17 inches), but low numbers in 2017 (10.33 fish/gillnet, 14.41 inches). The fall Tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 67.43 fish/gillnet and 12.56 inches for Green Lake. Tullibee growth rates were slow in the November survey gillnet catches. The 2014 year class comprised 57% of the 2019 November Tullibee survey catch. The inconsistency of Tullibee natural reproduction and inadequate adult Tullibee numbers on the spawning grounds as sampled by the DNR is not a good indication for the long term sustainability of the Tullibee populations in Green and Koronis. Hopefully, consecutive cool summers will continue to occur periodically, which may result in a good hatch, recruitment and survival of Tullibee to maintain a long term population in Green.

Improving and maintaining good water quality in Green is the key for Tullibee numbers to survive and flourish. Public fall gillnetting season will probably be postponed until the adult population rebounds to adequate levels. Current fish management activities on Green include monitoring the fish population on a periodic basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives, and stocking various fish species as warranted. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the 2020 summer for all fish species. Tullibee will be sampled by November gillnetting in 2022 for both Green and Koronis.

A standard survey in Green Lake was conducted during early September of 2021 using lake survey gillnets and trapnets. Standard surveys were done during the last week of July or first week of August prior to 2021. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass). Targeted surveys were conducted to determine if September gillnetting would more effectively sample the Walleye population than the standard July-August surveys in Green Lake during 2017-2020. Current and past September gillnetting surveys occurred during or after the fall turnover. We set 12 gillnets at standard summer stations during early September of 2021. Green Lake was partially mixed from surface to 55 feet deep with water temperatures near 70 F; dissolved oxygen was 8.3 ppm near the surface, 4.8 ppm at 55 feet deep and 0.4 ppm near the bottom. The secchi reading was 13.0 feet during the early September survey. Fine meshed gillnetting (4 sets) was conducted during late September for estimating sex/maturity of Yellow Perch as part of a University of Minnesota study. A fall electrofishing survey was conducted on October 18, 2021 to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye abundance in Green Lake. A creel survey was conducted on Green Lake during the 2019 summer and 2019-2020 winter.

Green is a large (5,561 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), highly developed (690 homes) and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is currently infested with invasive species such as Curly-leaf Pondweed, Eurasian Watermilfoil (2000) and Zebra Mussels (2014). Green is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Smallmouth Bass, Black Crappie (recent years) and Bluegill. There are approximately 48 inlets that enter Green Lake. The Middle Fork Crow River is the largest inlet and enters Green along the north shore and exits along the east side eventually flowing into Calhoun Lake. Water levels were low during 2020 and 2021. Direct nutrient runoff into Green is primarily from highway runoff and residential sources, which include lake homes and the city of Spicer. There is also upstream agricultural row crop runoff that enters the Middle Fork Crow River. Submergent vegetation appeared less dense in 2021 than previous survey years. Emergent vegetation such as Hardstem Bulrush is abundant in the outlet bay. A moderate stand of bulrush is present along the southeast shore. Zebra mussels were abundant on shoalwater substrates such rubble and boulder throughout the littoral areas. Zebra Mussels have decreased free open water green algal abundance which as caused lower densities of zooplankton, shifted energy and nutrient transfers from open water to bottom habitats, altered predator-prey relationships, decreased some fish species condition factors, and increased water clarity since 2014. Several other area lakes (Andrew, Diamond, Eagle, Elkhorn, George, Nest, Norway, and Games) were recently reported as infested with Zebra Mussels in 2017-2018.

Black Crappie gillnet catch rate (0.33 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (1.28 fish/gillnet) in the 2021 fall standard survey. Black Crappie trapnet catch rate was 1.20 fish/trapnet in the 2021 fall survey. The 2021 Black Crappie average sizes were moderate for fall gillnets (0.50 pounds and 8.61 inches), but large for fall trapnets (0.88 pounds and 11.43 inches). The 2021 Black Crappie catch rate of preferred size (10.00 plus inches) was moderate (1.13 fish/trapnet). Black Crappie growth rates near the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-8. The 2016 year class comprised 68% of the 2021 Black Crappie survey catch.

Bluegill trapnet catch rate (38.67 fish/trapnet) was near the historical average (42.67 fish/trapnet) in the 2021 fall standard survey. Bluegill trapnet average size was small (0.09 pounds and 4.80 inches). The largest Bluegill captured was 9.76 inches. The 2021 Bluegill catch rate of preferred size (8.00 plus inches) was low (0.53 fish/trapnet). Bluegill growth rates were less or near the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-4, near the 50th quartiles for age 5 and near the 75th quartiles for ages 6-8. The 2018 year class comprised 88% of the 2021 Bluegill survey catch.

Largemouth Bass gillnet catch rate (1.93 fish/gillnet) was above the historical average (0.44 fish/gillnet) in the 2021 fall standard survey. The 2021 Largemouth Bass gillnet average size was large (1.44 pounds and 13.09 inches). The 2015 year class comprised 43% of the 2021 Largemouth Bass gillnet catch. Abundant numbers of small sized Largemouth Bass (1.93 fish/trapnet, 7.13 inches average) were captured in the 2021 fall trapnets. Two-year-old fish or younger comprised 89% of the Largemouth Bass trapnet catch. Largemouth Bass growth rates were within the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-6, but below the normal ranges for ages 7-8. Growth rates were generally above the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-6 and within the normal ranges for ages 7-8.

Northern Pike gillnet catch rate (2.75 fish/gillnet) was similar to the historical average (2.87 fish/gillnet) in the 2021 fall standard survey. The 2021 Northern Pike average size was small (1.92 pounds and 20.56 inches). The 2021 Northern Pike catch rate of preferred size (28.00 plus inches) was naught (0.00 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (0.44 fish/gillnet). Northern Pike growth rates were below the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-6, but within the normal ranges for ages 7-8. The 2017 year class comprised 36% of the Northern Pike gillnet catch. Northern Pike possession limit regulations for Green in the North-central Zone are as follows: anglers can keep 10 Northern Pike, but not more than two pike longer than 26 inches; and all from 22 to 26 inches must be released. Northern Pike taken by spearing follow the same rules except one pike may be between 22 and 26 inches or two larger than 26 inches.

Rock Bass gillnet catch rate (7.83 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (9.18 fish/gillnet) in the 2021 fall standard survey. The 2021 Rock Bass gillnet average size was large (0.55 pounds and 8.53 inches).

Smallmouth Bass gillnet catch rate (1.25 fish/gillnet) was lower than the historical average (1.75 fish/gillnet) in the 2021 fall standard survey. The 2021 Smallmouth Bass gillnet average size (0.67 pounds and 10.14 inches) was small. The 2021 Smallmouth Bass fall catch rate of preferred size (14.00 plus inches) was low (0.09 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (1.03 fish/gillnet). A minor summerkill of adult Smallmouth Bass was noted in Green due to a viral outbreak during July/August of 2021. Smallmouth Bass growth rates were less or near than the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-5, within the normal ranges for ages 6-7 and above the normal range for age 8.

Northern Crayfish (important prey species for Smallmouth Bass) numbers were high during the 2021 fall survey (16.58 crayfish/gillnet) compared to previous surveys from 2002-2020 (<3.00 crayfish/gillnet). Zebra Mussels are an important forage prey for Northern Crayfish. Zebra Mussels may cause a shift to greater numbers of benthic species such as Northern Crayfish and Yellow Perch which would be beneficial to Smallmouth Bass.

Tullibee gillnet catch rate was low (0.17 fish/gillnet) in the 2021 fall standard survey. Tullibee were absent in the 2020 September or summer gillnet catches. The Tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 1.78 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2021 Tullibee average size was small (0.11 pounds and 7.13 inches). Tullibee growth rates were below the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-3.

Yellow Perch gillnet catch rate was low (3.00 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (11.19 fish/gillnet) in the 2021 fall standard survey. The 2020 Yellow Perch average size was small (0.14 pounds and 6.64 inches) in the early September survey. The 2021 fall catch rate of quality size (8.00 inches and larger) Yellow Perch was also low (0.25 fish/gillnet). Yellow Perch growth rates were generally less than the Spicer Area normal ranges. Growth rates were generally below the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-5. The 2018 year class comprised 73% of the total fall standard survey catch. Female mature Yellow Perch comprised 100% of the total fall standard survey catch.

Abundant Yellow Perch numbers (121.00/gillnet, 4.82 inches average length) were captured in the late September fine meshed gillnet survey. Approximately 86% of the Yellow Perch captured were less than 4.50 inches in this late September survey. Fall electrofishing also sampled moderate numbers of small Yellow Perch. Female mature fish comprised 71.6% of the Yellow Perch total catch (fine mesh gillnets and fall electrofishing) with an average length of 4.69 inches.

Various combinations of Walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults were stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) from 2000-2017 into Green Lake. Pike River was the primary Walleye fingerling strain that was available and stocked into Green from 2000-2014. Spicer Area Walleye fingerling rearing ponds have been stocked with primarily the Spicer strain since 2015. Both Unmarked Spicer and Pike River Walleye strains were stocked into Green during 2015 (36,723 fingerlings, 2,497 pounds; 1,400 yearlings, 560 pounds). Unmarked Spicer strain fingerlings and yearlings were stocked into Green during the 2016 fall (26,365 fingerlings, 1,647 pounds; 4,641 yearlings, 828 pounds). Green Lake was stocked with Spicer strain fin clipped (right ventral) age 3+ adults (196 pounds, 192 fish) and ages 1+ fish (2,081 pounds, 3,936 fish) in the 2017 fall. Spicer strain (1,173 pounds, 16,064 fish) and Pike River strain (117 pounds, 936 fish) fingerlings were also stocked in the 2017 fall. Fin clipped (left ventral) Walleye yearlings (701 fish, 150 pounds) and adults (300 fish, 150 pounds) were stocked by private sources in 2019. In 2020 fall, Green was stocked with Spicer strain fin clipped Walleye adults (76 pounds, 39 fish) and yearlings (3,411 pounds, 7,765 fish). Green was stocked with 2,500 Spicer strain fin clipped (right ventral) Walleye (1,050 pounds) after the 2021 fall standard survey. Adults and yearlings comprised 1,844 fish (911 pounds) of the 2021 stocking. Fingerlings comprised 656 fish (139 pounds) of the 2021 stocking.

Young of Year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye numbers due to natural reproduction were moderate (10.50 YOY/hour, 7.39 inches) in 2021. YOY Walleye were absent in the 2020 fall electrofishing survey. Low YOY Walleye numbers (<5.00 YOY/hour) were captured in 2013-2019 fall electrofishing surveys. Although, fall electrofishing survey techniques may be less effective for sampling YOY Walleye in large multi contoured lakes with high water clarity. Moderate YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2012 (12.00 YOY/hour, 6.87 inches) and 2011 (31.00 YOY/hour, 6.46 inches average length) fall electrofishing surveys. OTC marked fry captured as fingerlings comprised 40% of the 2013 and 55% of the 2012 fall electrofishing survey catches. OTC marked YOY Walleye (fry stocked) comprised 63.3% (19.62 YOY/hour) of the 2011 fall YOY Walleye survey catch.

Walleye gillnet catch rate (6.67 fish/gillnet) was slightly below the historical average (8.25 fish/gillnet) in the 2021 fall standard survey. The 2021 Walleye average size was moderate (1.56 pounds and 16.15 inches). The 2021 catch rate of quality size (15.00 plus inches) Walleye (3.25 fish/gillnet) was similar to the historical average (3.54 fish/gillnet). The 2021 fall catch rate of preferred size (20.00 plus inches) Walleye was low (0.42 fish/gillnet). Walleye growth rates were above the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-4, but within the normal ranges for ages 5-8. Walleye growth rates were within the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-2, but below the normal ranges for ages 3-8. Recent Walleye year classes have been due mostly to stocking since 2001. The 2021 Walleye fall standard survey catch was comprised of 2007 (1%), 2011 (3%), 2012 (1%), 2013 (5%), 2014 (2%), 2015 (8%), 2016 (12%) and 2017 (7%), 2018 (17%) and 2019 (38%) year classes. Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked Walleye (fry stocked) accounted for 100%, 0%, 50%, 28.6% and 38.5% respectively of the 2011, 2012, 2013, 2016 and 2018 year classes caught in the 2021 Walleye fall standard survey catches. OTC marked fish (fry stocked) made up 15.5% of the total Walleye catch from marked year classes in the 2021 fall standard survey gillnets. Walleye yearlings and adults were marked by a fin clip (right ventral) when stocked into Green during 2017 and 2020. Approximately 29.7% of combined Walleye Ages 2-5 were fin clipped fish in the 2021 Walleye fall standard survey catch. Fin clipped fish comprised 42% and 25% respectively of the 2019 and 2016 year classes in the 2021 Walleye fall standard survey catch. Zebra Mussels may negatively affect future Walleye fry stockings and natural reproduction by reducing zooplankton food availability, thus causing poor Walleye first year survival. However, if benthic forage species such as Yellow Perch begin to rebound then yearling/adult Walleye recruitment and growth may also respond positively. Continued Walleye fingerling or yearling stockings may be necessary to maintain adequate Walleye numbers in Green. The new Walleye bag limit was reduced from six to three fish on Green Lake in 2021. Only 1 Walleye over 20 inches is allowed.

Other species captured during the 2021 fall standard survey included low numbers of White Sucker (0.67 fish/gillnet), Common Carp (0.20 fish/trapnet) and Black Bullhead (0.08 fish/gillnet). Abundant numbers of large Yellow Bullhead (6.08 fish/gillnet, 0.96 pounds) were captured in the 2021 fall standard survey.

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking Walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the fall of 2022 for YOY Walleye abundance, and early September of 2021 for all fish species by standard survey nets and late November for Tullibee.

Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (maximum depth=110 feet), and moderately productivelake located near Spicer, MN in Kandiyohi County. Green Lake has excellent water quality and clarity (secchi disk=9 feet). The Middle Fork of the Crow River "MFCR" flows into Mud Lake(34-158), Nest Lake (34-154), and eventually into Green Lake along the northwest side. TheMFCR is a constant source of moderate/low nutrient loading to Green Lake. The immediatewatershed is primarily residential homes, mixed hardwoods, and wetlands. Green is highlydeveloped (663 homes, several resorts, county and city parks, a bible camp, and the city ofSpicer). The MFCR exits Green Lake along the northeast shore and connects to Lake Calhoun(34-0062). Water control structures affecting Green Lake water levels include the MFCR/MudReservoir Dam at New London, a dam at the MFCR inlet to Green Lake, a dam in the MFCR eastof Green and south of Calhoun, and a dam at the outlet of Calhoun. Shoalwater substrates aremostly sand and gravel in the lake. Boulder and rubble are common along several long shallowbars (Grate's, Hultgren's) and adjacent shoreline point areas. Marl and silt are common inthe outlet bay area. Hardstem bulrush stands are found in the outlet bay area and a smallstand along the south shore. There are various submergent vegetation species found withinGreen, however densities are light throughout most of the lake except for the outlet bayarea. Green Lake has been stocked with a variety of fish species and densities over theyears. Smallmouth bass were introduced in the 1940's. Tullibee "cisco" were introduced intoGreen during the late 1800's. Walleye fingerlings have been stocked in the past with thegreatest frequency compared to all other fish species. Experimental regulations (24 inchmaximum size for northern pike, catch and release fishing only for smallmouth and largemouthbass) were implemented in 1997 for developing trophy northern pike and smallmouth bassopportunities. Green Lake is a popular walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegillfishery. In addition, a two-three week gillnetting season is allowed for tullibee in mid tolate November each year. Walleye numbers within Green Lake have been both abundant and relatively stable duringthe last sixteen years. Likewise, anglers have experienced good walleye fishing in Greenthroughout the same time period. The 1997 walleye abundance (13.5 fish/gillnet) was above thehistorical average (9.2 fish/gillnet). However, the walleye average size has been small (<1.0 lbs.) the last two years. Walleye growth rates are slightly below average in Greencompared to other area lakes. The majority of walleye captured in the 1997 survey belongedto the 1994 year class which was due primarily to natural reproduction. Green Lake walleyefishing is often good throughout the entire summer unlike other area lakes. Green can be achallenging lake to fish for walleye due to the complex underwater structure present in thelake. Northern pike numbers in 1997 (3.4 fish/gillnet) were normal compared to similar lakesand the Green Lake historical average (2.9 fish/gillnet). However, the northern pike averageweight from the gillnets was small (1.8 lbs.). The largest northern pike caught and releasedfrom the trapnets was 37.7 inches. Anglers often have good success catching northern pike bytrolling near the shallow flats along the south portion of the lake during late summer. Smallmouth bass abundance in the 1997 spring electrofishing survey (25.1 fish/hour) wasabove the historical average (14.1 fish/hour). The 1997 smallmouth bass average size fromspring electrofishing was 12.2 inches. The largest smallmouth caught and released from springelectrofishing was 18.8 inches. Anglers have good success fishing for smallmouth bass alongthe northeast portion of Green Lake. Other fish species that provide good fishing success for anglers include bluegill,rockbass, and occasionally yellow perch and black crappie. Bluegill numbers in 1997 (11.9fish/trapnet) were below the historical average (55.1 fish/trapnet), however the average sizewas good (6.1 inches). The largest bluegill captured and released in the 1997 survey was 9.1inches. Anglers have the best success catching bluegill near the outlet bay area adjacent tothe bulrush stands. Green Lake is one of the most popular lakes both for fishing and recreational activities (i.e., boating, swimming, water skiing) in Kandiyohi County. The walleye population abundancehas been stable the last sixteen years. Although, the walleye average size has beenrelatively small (< 1.0 lbs.) the last two years. Green Lake has good walleye naturalreproduction. Current plans are to stock Green with walleye fingerlings only after twoconsecutive poor walleye natural year classes as documented by annual fall electrofishingsurveys. Priority management in Green will continue for walleye. Green Lake has the habitat,water quality, forage base (tullibee), and historical precedence to produce trophy northernpike. The 24 inch maximum size limit experimental regulation should enhance opportunities fornorthern pike to reach the trophy size range in Green. Likewise, Green has produced fairnumbers of large smallmouth bass in the past. The catch and release experimental regulationfor smallmouth bass should also enhance numbers of trophy sized fish within Green. Both thenorthern pike and smallmouth bass experimental regulations are part of a statewide study thatwill be finalized and evaluated in 2006. These regulations may remain in effect, modified,or removed depending upon how the regulations meet the specified goals for Green Lake. Othermanagement priorities for Green include protecting the existing stands of hardstem bulrush,assessing the tullibee population through annual fall gillnetting surveys, assessing walleyenatural reproduction by fall electrofishing surveys, assessing adult fish populations throughannual summer assessments, and protecting water quality by encouraging local landowners toimplement best management practices within the watershed (i.e. conservation tillage, plantingbuffer strips, restoring wetlands, proper manure/feedlot management, proper shorelandmanagement, using low/no phosphorus fertilizers, etc.).

Green is a large, deep, moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Greenis a popular walleye, northern pike, bluegill, and smallmouth bass fishery. Walleye fishinghas been good in recent years, however the average size has been small (< 1.25 lbs.). Greenhas good walleye natural reproduction occurring during most years in the abundant rock andgravel shoal water areas. Young of year "YOY" walleye numbers were abundant to moderate from1993-1996. Poor walleye natural reproduction was documented in 1997. Green Lake was laststocked with walleye fingerlings (43,827 marked fish 2,027 lbs.) in 1994. Green Lake wasstocked with 2,699,904 walleye fry in the 1996 spring which was a 10% return of the walleyeeggs taken from Green Lake for the 1996 state wide walleye hatching quotas. Experimentalfishing regulations were enacted during 1997 in order to increase the quality of size fornorthern pike and smallmouth bass in Green Lake. The smallmouth bass experimental regulationallows for catch and release fishing only. The northern pike experimental regulationprohibits the harvest of northern pike 24.0 inches or greater. The two experimentalregulations will be evaluated in 2008 at which time they will be maintained, modified, orremoved depending on the effectiveness of the regulations and public support. Local residentsreported excellent fishing success for catching smallmouth bass in 1998. Walleye abundance in 1998 (9.83 fish/gillnet) was similar to the Green historicalaverage (9.26 fish/gillnet). The 1998 walleye average weight (0.99 lbs., gillnets) was belowthe Green historical average (1.19 lbs.), but above the two previous surveys. Three walleyeyear classes (24% for 1996, 30% for 1995, 31% for 1994) comprised most of the 1998 walleyegillnet catch. There were no 1994 stocked walleye observed in the 1998 summer survey nets.Yearling walleye were abundant in the 1998 fall electrofishing survey (22.5 fish/hour,average length=10.1 inches). However, YOY walleye numbers were low (4.5 YOY/hour, averagelength=7.5 inches) in the 1998 fall night electrofishing survey. Northern pike abundance in 1998 (2.58 fish/gillnet) was similar to the Green historicalaverage (7.89 fish/gillnet). The northern pike average weight was 2.56 lbs in 1998. Thelargest northern pike captured in the 1998 survey nets was 40.0 inches. There were abundant numbers of smallmouth bass (4.25 fish/gillnet) and yellow perch(32.33 fish/gillnet) present in 1998. The smallmouth bass average size (11.7 inches, gillnetsand trapnets combined) increased in 1998 compared to the Green historical average (9.2inches). The largest smallmouth bass captured in the 1998 survey was 17.6 inches. Low numbersof bluegill (5.20 fish/trapnet) and rock bass (2.83 fish/gillnet) were present in 1998.However, the bluegill average size improved in 1998 (6.0 inches) compared to the Greenhistorical average (5.2 inches). Tullibee numbers (2.25 fish/gillnet) were present inmoderate numbers during 1998. Tullibee are an important forage fish for large northern pike. The Green Lake fishery appears to be in good condition for walleye, northern pike, andsmallmouth bass numbers. In addition, there are abundant forage species (yellow perch,tullibee, crayfish) present in Green. Although bluegill numbers are presently low, theaverage size has improved. The DNR Spicer Fisheries Office will continue to monitor GreenLake fish population numbers through annual summer netting surveys, spring basselectrofishing surveys and ice out northern pike trapping every two years, and annual YOYwalleye fall electrofishing surveys in order to evaluate the effectiveness of currentmanagement practices.

A standard survey in Green Lake was conducted during mid-September of 2022 using lake survey gillnets and trapnets. Standard surveys were done during the last week of July or first week of August prior to 2021. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass). Targeted surveys were conducted to determine if September gillnetting would more effectively sample the Walleye population than the standard July-August surveys in Green Lake during 2017-2020. Current and past September gillnetting surveys occurred during or after the fall turnover. We set 12 gillnets at standard summer stations during early September of 2022. Green Lake was mixed from surface to 98 feet deep with water temperatures near 71 F.; dissolved oxygen was 8.9 ppm near the surface, 8.4 ppm at 50 feet deep and 7.5 ppm near the bottom. The secchi reading was 9.0 feet during the early September survey. A fall electrofishing survey was conducted on October 20, 2022 to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye abundance in Green Lake. A creel survey was last conducted on Green Lake during the 2019 summer and 2019-2020 winter.

Green is a large (5,561 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), highly developed (690 homes) and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is currently infested with invasive species such as Curly-leaf Pondweed, Eurasian Watermilfoil (2000) and Zebra Mussels (2014). Green is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Smallmouth Bass, Black Crappie (recent years) and Bluegill. There are approximately 48 inlets that enter Green Lake. The Middle Fork Crow River is the largest inlet and enters Green along the north shore and exits along the east side eventually flowing into Calhoun Lake. Water levels were low during 2020-2022. Direct nutrient runoff into Green is primarily from highway runoff and residential sources, which include lake homes and the city of Spicer. There is also upstream agricultural row crop runoff that enters the Middle Fork Crow River. Submergent vegetation appeared less dense in 2021 and 2022 than previous survey years. Emergent vegetation such as Hardstem Bulrush is abundant in the outlet bay. A moderate stand of bulrush is present along the southeast shore. Zebra mussels were abundant on shoalwater substrates such as rubble and boulder throughout the littoral areas. Zebra Mussels have decreased free open water green algal abundance. This has resulted in lower densities of zooplankton, shifted energy and nutrient transfers from open water to bottom habitats, altered predator-prey relationships, decreased some fish species condition factors, and increased water clarity since 2014. Several other area lakes (Andrew, Diamond, Eagle, Elkhorn, George, Nest, Norway, and Games) were recently reported as infested with Zebra Mussels during 2017-2018.

Black Crappie gillnet catch rate (0.67 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (1.26 fish/gillnet) in the 2022 fall survey. Black Crappie trapnet catch rate was moderate (2.47 fish/trapnet) in the 2022 fall survey. The 2022 Black Crappie average sizes were small for fall gillnets (0.20 pounds and 7.2 inches), but moderate for fall trapnets (0.29 pounds and 7.8 inches). The historical average lengths are 8.0 inches and 8.2 inches respectively from gillnets and trapnets. The 2022 Black Crappie catch rate of preferred size (10.0 inches plus) was low (0.33 fish/trapnet). The largest Black Crappie captured was 12.2 inches. Black Crappie growth rates were slow compared to Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-3, but within the normal ranges for ages 4-7. The 2019 year class comprised 60% of the 2022 Black Crappie survey catch.

Bluegill trapnet catch rate (126.73 fish/trapnet) was above the historical average (44.94 fish/trapnet) in the 2022 fall survey. Bluegill average size was small (0.09 pounds and 4.7 inches) from trapnets. The historical average length is 5.5 inches from trapnets. The largest Bluegill captured was 10.7 inches. The 2022 Bluegill catch rate of preferred size (8.0 inches plus) was low (0.60 fish/trapnet). Bluegill growth rates were moderate compared to the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-5, but above the normal ranges for ages 6-8. The 2019 year class comprised 59% of the 2022 Bluegill survey catch.

Largemouth Bass gillnet catch rate (0.08 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (0.85 fish/gillnet) in the 2022 fall standard survey. The 2022 Largemouth Bass gillnet average size was large (2.04 pounds and 15.6 inches). Abundant numbers of small sized Largemouth Bass (1.73 fish/trapnet, 5.9 inches average) were captured in the 2022 fall trapnets. The historical average lengths are 10.4 inches and 8.7 inches respectively from gillnets and trapnets. Largemouth Bass growth rates were slow compared to other Spicer Area lakes. The 2020 year class comprised 67% of the 2022 survey catch.

Northern Pike gillnet catch rate (2.08 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (2.85 fish/gillnet) in the 2022 fall standard survey. The 2022 Northern Pike average size was moderate (2.80 pounds and 23.4 inches). The historical average length is 23.2 inches. Northern Pike appeared thin for their length in recent years. The 2022 Northern Pike catch rate of preferred size (28.0 inches plus) was low (0.08 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (0.43 fish/gillnet). The largest Northern Pike captured was 30.0 inches. Northern Pike growth rates were slow compared the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-8. The 2019 year class comprised 41% of the 2022 Northern Pike survey catch. Northern Pike possession limit regulations for Green in the North-central Zone are as follows: anglers can keep 10 Northern Pike, but not more than two pike longer than 26.0 inches; and all from 22.0 to 26.0 inches must be released. Northern Pike taken by spearing follow the same rules except one pike may be between 22.0 and 26.0 inches or two larger than 26.0 inches.

Rock Bass gillnet catch rate was high (8.92 fish/gillnet), but similar to the historical average (9.18 fish/gillnet) in the 2022 fall standard survey. The 2022 Rock Bass gillnet average size was large (0.45 pounds and 7.7 inches). The historical average length is 7.8 inches.

Smallmouth Bass gillnet catch rate (2.08 fish/gillnet) was slightly above the historical average (1.75 fish/gillnet) in the 2022 fall standard survey. The 2022 Smallmouth Bass gillnet average size (1.11 pounds and 11.1 inches) was moderate. The historical average length is 13.3 inches. The 2022 Smallmouth Bass fall catch rate of preferred size (14.0 inches plus) was moderate (0.67 fish/gillnet), but below the historical average (1.02 fish/gillnet). A minor summerkill of adult Smallmouth Bass was noted in Green due to a viral outbreak during July/August of 2021. Smallmouth Bass growth rates were below the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-4, but within or above the normal ranges for ages 5-8. The 2020 year class comprised 66% of the 2022 Smallmouth Bass survey catch.

Northern Crayfish (important prey species for Smallmouth Bass) numbers were high during the 2022 fall survey (20.50 crayfish/gillnet) compared to previous surveys from 2002-2020 (<3.00 crayfish/gillnet). There were also abundant Northern Crayfish (16.58 crayfish/gillnet) in the 2021 fall survey. Zebra Mussels are an important forage prey for Northern Crayfish. Zebra Mussels may cause a shift to greater numbers of bottom species such as Northern Crayfish and Yellow Perch which would be beneficial to Smallmouth Bass.

Tullibee gillnet catch rate was low (0.08 fish/gillnet) in the 2022 fall standard survey. Tullibee numbers were also low (0.17 fish/gillnet) in the 2021 fall survey. Tullibee were absent in the 2020 September and summer gillnet catches. The Tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 1.73 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2022 Tullibee average size was small (0.33 pounds and 9.1 inches). The historical average length is 10.70 inches. Tullibee growth rates were below the Spicer Area and Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-2.

Yellow Perch gillnet catch rate was low (3.25 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (10.98 fish/gillnet) in the 2022 fall standard survey. The 2022 Yellow Perch average size was small (0.13 pounds and 6.5 inches). The historical length is 6.5 inches. The 2022 fall catch rate of quality size (8.0 inches plus) Yellow Perch was also low (0.17 fish/gillnet). Yellow Perch growth rates were slow for ages 1-6. The 2018 year class comprised 65% of the 2022 Yellow Perch survey catch.

Walleye fry have been stocked into Green with mostly Spicer and Pike River strains of varied amounts (0.5 to 2.5 million fish) from 2000-2013. Approximately 1 million Spicer strain fry were recently stocked in 2016 and 2018. Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked fry were stocked in Green during 2000-2013, 2016 and 2018. Various combinations of Walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults were stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) from 2000-2017 into Green Lake. Pike River was the primary Walleye fingerling strain that was available and stocked into Green from 2000-2014. Spicer Area Walleye fingerling rearing ponds have been stocked with primarily the Spicer strain since 2015. Both Unmarked Spicer and Pike River Walleye strains were stocked into Green during 2015 (36,723 fingerlings, 2,497 pounds; 1,400 yearlings, 560 pounds). Unmarked Spicer strain fingerlings and yearlings were stocked into Green during the 2016 fall (26,365 fingerlings, 1,647 pounds; 4,641 yearlings, 828 pounds). Green Lake was stocked with Spicer strain fin clipped age 3+ adults (196 pounds, 192 fish) and ages 1+ fish (2,081 pounds, 3,936 fish) in the 2017 fall. Spicer strain (1,173 pounds, 16,064 fish) and Pike River strain (117 pounds, 936 fish) fingerlings were also stocked in the 2017 fall. Fin clipped Walleye yearlings (701 fish, 150 pounds) and adults (300 fish, 150 pounds) were stocked by private sources in 2019. In 2020 fall, Green was stocked with Spicer strain fin clipped Walleye adults (76 pounds, 39 fish) and yearlings (3,411 pounds, 7,765 fish). Green was stocked with 2,500 Spicer strain fin clipped Walleye (1,050 pounds) after the 2021 fall standard survey. Adults and yearlings comprised 1,844 fish (911 pounds) of the 2021 stocking. Fingerlings comprised 656 fish (139 pounds) of the 2021 stocking. In October of 2022, Walleye stocked (fin clipped) included adults (115 fish, 172 pounds), yearlings (342 fish, 145 pounds) and fingerlings (425 fish, 104 pounds).

Abundant YOY Walleye numbers (65.54 YOY/hour, 5.2 inches) due to natural reproduction were captured in 2022 fall electrofishing survey. This was the highest historical recorded YOY Walleye catch rate for Green Lake. Young of Year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye numbers due to natural reproduction were moderate (10.50 YOY/hour, 7.4 inches) in 2021. YOY Walleye were absent in the 2020 fall electrofishing survey. Low YOY Walleye numbers (<5.00 YOY/hour) were captured in 2013-2019 fall electrofishing surveys. Although, fall electrofishing survey techniques may be less effective for sampling YOY Walleye in large multi contoured lakes with high water clarity. Moderate YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2012 (12.00 YOY/hour, 6.9 inches) and 2011 (31.00 YOY/hour, 6.5 inches average length) fall electrofishing surveys. OTC marked fry captured as fingerlings comprised 40% of the 2013 and 55% of the 2012 fall electrofishing survey catches. OTC marked YOY Walleye (fry stocked) comprised 63.3% (19.62 YOY/hour) of the 2011 fall YOY Walleye survey catch.

Walleye gillnet catch rate (6.92 fish/gillnet) was slightly below the historical average (8.21 fish/gillnet) in the 2022 fall standard survey. The 2022 Walleye average size was moderate (1.49 pounds and 15.7 inches). The historical average length is 15.0 inches. The 2022 catch rate of quality size (15.0 plus inches) Walleye (4.67 fish/gillnet) was above the historical average (3.58 fish/gillnet). The 2022 fall catch rate of preferred size (20.0 inches plus) Walleye was low (0.50 fish/gillnet). Walleye growth rates were excellent compared to the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-8. However, Walleye growth rates were fair to poor compared to Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-8. Recent Walleye year classes have been due mostly to stocking since 2001. The 2022 Walleye fall standard survey catch was comprised of 2004 (1%), 2012 (2%), 2013 (2%), 2014 (1%), 2015 (2%), 2016 (1%) and 2017 (7%), 2018 (21%), 2019 (31%), 2020 (0%) and 2021 (30%) year classes. Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked Walleye (fry stocked) accounted for 28% of 2018 year class caught in the 2022 Walleye fall gillnet and trapnet catches. No other OTC marked fish from other year classes were captured in the 2022 fall gillnet and trapnets. Approximately 31% of 2019 Walleye year class (age 3) were fin clipped fish (yearling/adult stockings) in the 2022 Walleye fall survey catch. Fin clipped Walleye accounted for 7% of 2021 year class (656 fingerlings stocked) captured in the 2022 fall survey catch. All Walleye from the 2016 and 2014 year classes were fin clipped (yearling/adult stockings) in the 2022 survey catch. Zebra Mussels may negatively affect future Walleye fry stockings or natural reproduction by reducing zooplankton food availability, thus causing poor Walleye first year survival. However, if bottom forage species such as Yellow Perch begin to rebound then yearling/adult Walleye survival and growth may also respond positively. It is encouraging that good Walleye natural reproduction success was documented in 2022. If fingerling survival to adult size is poor, then continued Walleye fingerling or yearling stockings may be necessary to maintain adequate Walleye numbers in Green. The new Walleye bag limit was reduced from six to three fish on Green Lake in 2021. Only 1 Walleye over 20 inches is allowed.

Other species captured during the 2022 fall standard survey included low numbers of White Sucker (0.25 fish/gillnet), Common Carp (0.17 fish/gillnet) and Black Bullhead (1.00 fish/gillnet). Abundant numbers of moderate sized Yellow Bullhead (12.42 fish/gillnet, 0.64 pounds) were captured in the 2022 fall standard survey.

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking Walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the fall of 2023 for YOY Walleye abundance, and early September of 2023 for all fish species by standard survey nets and late November for Tullibee.

N. Pike population at state average, growth excellent. Walleye 3 times state average in numbers. LM Bass about at state average in number and growth. SM bass about at state average in numbers, good growth. Bluegill seven times the state average. Blk bullhead twelve times the state average in numbers. Yel perch two times the state average in numbers.

A fish population assessment of Green Lake was conducted in late July of 2001. Green is a large, deep, low-moderate productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegill. Also, Green Lake receives high recreational use during the summer months. Aquatic vegetation is generally limited in the lake. Low densities of Eurasian water milfoil have been documented in Green Lake near the Spicer public access and swimming beach since 2000. Efforts to chemically eradicate Eurasian water milfoil have been unsuccessful. Widespread and extensive matting of Eurasian water milfoil is unlikely to occur through out Green Lake. The dominant substrates (rock, rubble, gravel) present in the shoal water areas are not easily suitable for aquatic vegetation establishment. Experimental regulations for both northern pike and smallmouth bass were enacted in 1997 in order to increase the average size and produce trophy fisheries of smallmouth bass and northern pike in Green Lake. The northern pike experimental regulation (24 inch maximum size limit) prohibits the harvest of fish 24.0 inches and greater. The smallmouth and largemouth bass regulation was originally catch and release only. However, the bass regulation was modified to a 14 inch maximum harvest size limit in 2001. The bass regulation was changed because of increasing high numbers of smallmouth bass and the perceived negative effects on the walleye population in Green Lake. A summer creel survey was conducted on Green Lake during the 2001 summer (May 10 - September 30) as an on going evaluation of the two experimental regulations.Bluegill numbers were high in 2001 (61.4 fish/trapnet) and above the historical average (50.4 fish/trapnet). The 2001 bluegill average size was small (0.10 lbs. and 4.8 inches from trapnets). Bluegill growth rates were below average for fish 3 years and younger, but generally above average for fish 4 years and older compared to Spicer Area lakes. There were moderate numbers of quality size (6.0 inches) and larger bluegill in the 2001 summer assessment (8.2 fish/trapnet). The largest bluegill captured in the 2001 summer assessment was 9.9 inches. Northern pike numbers were low in 2001 (3.0 fish/gillnet), but the same as the historical average. The northern pike average size was moderate (3.57 lbs. and 24.2 inches from gillnets). Northern pike growth rates were generally above average compared to Spicer Area lakes. The northern pike population is also evaluated every other spring through ice out trapping at several major spawning runs. The northern pike average size has increased both in the summer and spring ice out assessments since the experimental regulation was enacted in 1997. The largest northern pike captured in the 2001 summer assessment was 34.3 inches.Smallmouth bass numbers were high in 2001 (2.8 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (1.8 fish/gillnet). The 2001 smallmouth bass average size was moderate to large (1.34 lbs. and 12.3 inches from gillnets). Smallmouth bass numbers of large fish (>14.0 inches) was also high for Green. Smallmouth bass growth rates were below average for fish 2 years and younger, but average or above for fish 3 years and older compared to the Green Lake historical averages. Smallmouth bass forage such as crayfish, were low in 2001 (1.7 crayfish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (17.9 crayfish/gillnet). Local anglers have reported excellent success catching large smallmouth bass in recent years. However, local anglers have expressed concern over the relatively high smallmouth population effect via competition on the presently low walleye population in Green Lake.Tullibee "cisco" numbers in 2001 (0.3 fish/gillnet) were below the historical average (3.1 fish/gillnet). The 2001 tullibee average size was moderate (0.59 lbs. and 10.6 inches from gillnets). Tullibee are an important forage species for both large northern pike and walleye.Yellow perch numbers were low to moderate in 2001 (14.9 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (20.7 fish/gillnet). The 2001 yellow perch average size was small (0.12 lbs. and 6.5 inches from gillnets). Walleye numbers were low to moderate in 2001 (7.8 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (9.6 fish/gillnet). The 2001 walleye average size was moderate (1.34 lbs. and 14.9 inches from gillnets). Walleye growth rates were below average compared to Spicer Area lakes. Walleye numbers of quality size (15.0 inches) and larger fish (4.2 fish/gillnet) were moderate for Green. Local anglers reported below average walleye angling success for numbers, but larger fish were the norm compared to previous years. Fishing pressure was low in 2001 for Green Lake.Walleye natural reproduction in Green is generally both frequent and good based on previous fall and summer surveys. However, walleye natural reproduction has been fair to poor in recent years. Low young of year "YOY" walleye numbers (4.7 YOY walleye/hour, 7.1 inches average size) were captured in the 2001 fall night electrofishing survey. The Green Lake historical average catch rate for YOY walleye in fall electrofishing surveys is 22.2 YOY walleye/hour. All YOY walleye sampled in the 2001 fall night electrofishing survey were marked fish from a 2001 stocking of walleye fry (1.04 million fish). The walleye fry stocking in 2001 was a 10% return of walleye eggs taken for statewide hatching operations. There were moderate yearling walleye numbers captured (19.0 yearling walleye/hour, 9.0 inches average length) during the 2001 fall night electrofishing survey. All yearling walleye were marked fish from fry (1.7 million fish) or fingerling (100,000 fish; 2,058 lbs.) stockings done in 2000. Unmarked walleye fingerlings (145,000 fish; 4,188 lbs.) were stocked during October of 2001 after the fall night electrofishing survey because of low documented YOY walleye numbers.
