Current fish management activities on Green include protecting the important aquatic vegetation such as bulrush through the permit process, monitoring and preventing the spread of Eurasian water milfoil if possible within and out of Green Lake, participating in the Middle Fork of the Crow River Watershed Project, monitoring both smallmouth bass and northern pike populations for the experimental regulations study, modifying the experimental regulations if necessary in the future for either smallmouth bass or northern pike, and stocking walleye fingerlings after two consecutive years of poor natural reproduction as documented by fall night electrofishing surveys. The Green Lake fishery will be surveyed in the 2002 spring for smallmouth bass and the 2002 summer for all species. Ice out trapping assessment for northern pike will occur in 2003.

THE 1991 WAE CATCH INDEX (7.56 PER GN, MEAN WEIGHT PER GN CAUGHT WAE WAS 1.37 LBS.) WAS VERY NEAR THE HISTORICAL MEANS (7.61 PER GN, MEAN WEIGHT PER GN CAUGHT WAE WAS 1.26 LBS.) AND WAS SIMILAR TO THE MAJORITY OF OTHER CLASS 27 LAKES. THE SIZE-CLASS DISTRIBUTION WAS WELL BALANCED AND IT APPEARS THAT THE 90,89, AND 88 YEAR-CLASSES WERE ALL MODERATE- TO-STRONG. THE 86 AND 85 YEAR-CLASSES APPEAR TO ALSO BE MODERATE-TO-STRONG AND COULD PROVIDE SOME QUALITY SIZE (>18.0 INCHES) FISH. WAE GROWTH RATES WERE BELOW THE LOCAL AVERAGE WHICH IS TYPICAL FOR GREEN LAKE. THE 1991 NOP CATCH INDEX (2.78 PER GN, MEAN WEIGHT PER GN CAUGHT NOP WAS 2.38 LBS.) WAS SIMILAR TO THE HISTORICAL MEANS (2.87 PER GN, MEAN WEIGHT PER GN CAUGHT NOP WAS 2.58 LBS.) BUT IS BELOW THE MAJORITY OF OTHER CLASS 27 LAKES IN TERMS OF NUMBERS. THE 1990 YEAR-CLASS LOOKED WEAK COMPARED TO THE 1989 YEAR- CLASS (DATA FROM 1990 SURVEY SUBSTANTIATES) WHICH SHOULD DOMINATE THE FISHERY IN 1992 (20-25 INCH FISH). THE GROWTH RATES OF NOP WERE AVERAGE FOR AGES 1-2 AND ABOVE AVERAGE FOR AGES 3-4. THE 1991 BLC TRAPNET CATCH INDEX WAS THE HIGHEST EVER RECORDED (2.20 PER TN), HOWEVER, TRAPNETS GENERALLY CATCH SMALLER/YOUNGER BLC THAN GILLNETS IN GREEN LAKE (GILLNET CATCH INDEX WAS 0.22 WHICH WAS SIMILAR TO THE 1990 SURVEY). THE DECLINE IN THE BLC FISHERY THROUGH THE 1980'S MAY GET A BOOST FROM THE RELATIVELY LARGE 1990 YEAR-CLASS IN 1994-1995 BASED ON THIS INFORMATION. GROWTH RATES FOR BLC WERE BELOW AVERAGE-TO-AVERAGE. BASED ON THE RELATIVELY LARGE 1991 TRAPNET CATCH INDEX COMPRISED PREDOMINANTLY OF YOUNG SMB (4.87 PER TN, 0.10 LBS. PER FISH), 1990 COULD BE A STRONG YEAR- CLASS. TIMING DURING SPRING ELECTROFISHING APPEARS VERY CRITICAL FOR LMB/SMB RESULTS (1990- 14.43 LMB PER HOUR, 2.00 SMB PER HOUR: 1991 - 26.40 SMB PER HOUR, 8.00 LMB PER HOUR). GROWTH RATES FOR SMB WERE AVERAGE AND GROWTH RATES FOR LMB WERE BELOW AVERAGE. THE SEEMINGLY HIGH ABUNDANCE OF CRAYFISH MAY BE A KEY FACTOR IN THE RELATIVELY FASTER SMB GROWTH RATES. THE 1991 BLG TRAPNET CATCH INDEX (109.67 PER TN) WAS THE HIGHEST RECORDED FOR GREEN LAKE AND IS HIGHER THAN THE MAJORITY OF OTHER CLASS 27 LAKES. OVERALL, GROWTH RATES ARE BELOW AVERAGE FOR AGES 1-3 AND AVERAGE FOR AGE 4, HOWEVER, THERE APPEARS TO BE A WIDE DIVERGENCE IN GROWTH RATES WITHIN A YEAR- CLASS. ALTHOUGH THE MAJORITY OF BLG WERE BELOW 6 INCHES, THERE WAS A FAIR NUMBER IN THE 6-7.5 RANGE. THE BLG (> 8 INCHES) THAT ARE OCCASIONALLY CAUGHT HAVE NOT BEEN SAMPLED WELL IN GREEN LAKE. THERE APPEARS TO BE A RELATIVELY LARGE 1987 YEAR- CLASS (1990 SURVEY RESULTS ALSO SUBSTANTIATE THIS) THAT COULD PROVIDE THE 1991 FALL TLC TESTNETTING RESULTS WERE VERY SIMILAR TO THE 1990 RESULTS IN TERMS OF RELATIVE DENSITY AND SIZE-CLASS DISTRIBUTION FOR BOTH MALES AND FEMALES. ALTHOUGH THE 1991 YEP GILLNET CATCH INDEX WAS SLIGHTLY LOWER THAN THE 1990 INDEX (SEE HISTORICAL CATCH SUMMARY AT THE END), THE DIFFERENCE DOES NOT APPEAR SIGNIFICANT AND IS WITHIN THE RANGE FOR MOST CLASS 27 LAKES. THE AGE-CLASS DISTRIBUTION SHOWED POSSIBLE LOW YEAR- CLASS STRENGTHS IN 1990 AND 1989 (1+ AND 2+ YEAR OLDS ARE GENERALLY SAMPLED MODERATELY WELL IN GREEN LAKE).

Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (maximum depth 110 feet), moderately productivelake located near Spicer, MN in Kandiyohi County. Green has excellent water quality comparedto most other lakes in Kandiyohi County. Water clarity is excellent and nutrient levels aremoderate to low. The Middle Fork of the Crow River (MFCR) inlet via Mud Lake (34-158) andNest Lake (34-0154) is a constant source of moderate nutrient loading to Green Lake. So farGreen has been able to assimilate incoming nutrients without any appreciable increase inproductivity. In addition to MFCR, there are seven other inlets of which all but one connectto shallow permanent lakes/marshes. The outlet (MFCR) is located on the northeast side of thelake and connects to Calhoun Lake via a marsh. The immediate watershed types are primarilymunicipal (residential homes), mixed hardwoods, and marshlands. Green is heavily developedwith 663 homes, several resorts/motels/bed&breakfasts, several condominiums/apartmentbuildings, bible camp, county park, city park, and the city of Spicer along the southwestshoreline. Only a small portion near the outlet is undeveloped. The lake shallow watersubstrate is dominated by sand and gravel throughout most of the lake, boulder and rubblecommon in various areas (shallow bars, shoreline), marl and silt in the outlet bay. There areseveral long shallow bars (Hultgren's, Lone Tree, Grate's, Castle Flats) located in the lake.Emergent vegetation (primarily hardstem bulrush with some common cattail, cane, and reedcanary grass) are restricted to the outlet area and a small stand near the "Spicer Castle"along the south shore. There is a variety of submergent vegetation species, but the densityis light throughout most of the lake with the exception of the outlet bay area. Water controlstructures affecting Green Lake water levels include the MFCR/Mud Lake Reservoir Dam at NewLondon, a stoplog dam at the MFCR inlet to Green Lake, a Type C with stoplogs south ofCalhoun, and a Type C solid sill at the Calhoun outlet. Green Lake has been intensivelystocked with a variety of species, densities, and frequencies over the years. Smallmouth basswere introduced in the early 1940's. Cisco "tullibee" were thought to be introduced intoGreen during the late 1800's. In the last ten years, stocking efforts have been devotedmostly to walleye. Historically, rescue operations have been common in adjacent connectedwinterkill lakes/marshes for northern pike. Prior to 1991, walleye were stocked almost everyyear. The current lake management plan is to stock walleye (about 2000 lbs) only after twoconsecutive poor natural year classes documented by fall electrofishing. Fall electrofishingsurveys have been conducted since 1993 to assess the contributions of natural reproductionand stocking to the walleye fishery in Green. Commercial removal has been limited in the lastten years to carp (16,160 lbs) and suckers (2,900 lbs). About 111 lbs of cisco were removedby state crews for an initial stocking at an East Metro Fisheries Area lake. In 1989, 310northern pike were removed by state crews for stocking local northern pike spawning areas(NPSA). Small amounts of walleye eggs (90,000 to 1,985,940) were removed by state crews forfingerling production in 1971, 1978-80, and 1986. Green is a popular lake for walleye,northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegill angling. In addition, tullibee gillnetting isallowed for a two-three week period in mid to late November. In recent years, Green has beenintensively sampled (consecutive lake surveys since 1989, spring electrofishing surveys forsmallmouth and largemouth bass, fall electrofishing surveys for YOY/Yearling walleye, creelsurveys in 1995 and 1996, spring northern pike assessment, ice out trapnetting for walleye,fall cisco gillnetting) to provide a better data base for developing future long termmanagement goals and objectives. Furthermore, experimental fishing regulations are plannedto be implemented in 1997 for developing trophy northern pike and smallmouth bassopportunities. Walleye abundance in 1995 (11.4 fish/gillnet) was above the normal range (4.0 - 9.6fish/gillnet) for similar lakes, and above the historical average of 8.5 fish/gillnet. The1995 average size (14.5, 1.2 lbs) was similar to the historical average (14.6 inches, 1.3lbs). The walleye population size structure has been fairly constant. Growth rates appearaverage to good. The largest fish caught was 24.2 inches in 1995. Walleye naturalreproduction was good in 1993 (46.0 YOY/hour) and 1994 (52.7 YOY/hour), but low in 1995 (22.0YOY/hour). Local lakes with documented natural reproduction averaged 51.0 YOY/hour in 1995.Green Lake walleye yearling abundance was 30.3 YRL/hour in 1993, 17.3 YRL/hour in 1994, and23.0 YRL/hour in 1995. The average size of young of year and yearling walleye caughtelectrofishing in 1995 was 6.2 and 9.2 inches respectively. The 1995 local lake young of yearand yearling walleye average sizes were 6.7 inches and 11.2 inches respectively. Green wasstocked with 43,827 pelvic fin clipped fingerlings (2,047 lbs = 1 lb/littoral acre) duringthe fall of 1994. Stocked fingerlings accounted for only 2.4% (1.3 YOY/hour) of the totalfingerling production in Green during 1994 (natural and stocked= 54.0 YOY/hour). However,this estimate may be conservative due to unequal spatial distributions and handling stressof stocked fish when fall electrofishing occurred two weeks after stocking in 1994. Northern pike abundance in 1995 (3.0 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range (3.0 -7.9 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes, and comparable to the historical average (2.8fish/gillnet). The largest fish captured in the summer survey was 34.6 inches. The averagesize in 1995 (20.9 inches, 2.6 lbs from gillnets) was similar to the historical average (21.7inches, 2.6 lbs.). Growth rates appear average to above average. Spawning runs occur inseveral inlet marshes (Alvig Slough, East Woodcock Lake), and also a large run at the outletmarsh area. Spring monitoring of the northern pike spawning runs have occurred from 1994-1996to provide information for the northern pike experimental regulations study. During thespring of 1994, 376 northern pike captured were marked with a left pelvic fin clip. About 22%(4 fish) of the northern pike (> 9 inches) captured in the 1994 summer survey nets had finclips. In the spring of 1995, 721 fish were tagged with a blue plastic spaghetti tag. About8% (3 fish) of the northern pike captured in the 1995 summer survey nets had a blue tag.There were no YOY northern pike caught during the fall electrofishing survey in 1995. Yellow perch abundance in 1995 (22.7 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range forsimilar lakes (7.1 - 33.9 fish/gillnet), and comparable to the historical average (20.4fish/gillnet). Yellow perch abundance was also similar in 1995 compared to 1994 (23.6fish/gillnet). The average size in 1995 (6.7 inches) was similar to the historical average(6.4 inches). Growth rates appear slightly below average compared to other local lakes. Cisco "tullibee" abundance in 1995 summer survey (7.7 fish/gillnet) was above the normalrange (0.5 - 5.2 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes, and above the historical average (4.3fish/gillnet). Abundance was up in 1995 compared to 1994 (3.6 fish/gillnet). The average sizein 1995 (12.0 inches) was above the historical average (9.6 inches). Smallmouth bass abundance in 1995 (0.4 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range (0.2 - 0.9 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes, and comparable to the historical average (0.5fish/gillnet). Smallmouth bass abundance in the 1995 spring electrofishing survey (9.0fish/hour) was also similar to the historical average (10.9 fish/hour). The average sizecaught in the 1995 gillnets was 13.3 inches. The average size caught in the 1995 springelectrofishing survey was 14.8 inches. The largest smallmouth bass caught was 18.5 inches(summer survey). Crayfish (important forage species of smallmouth bass) did not appearabundant in the 1995 survey (0.7 crayfish/gillnet). Green Lake will be part of a statewideexperimental regulations study on smallmouth bass in 1997. Largemouth bass spring electrofishing catch rate in 1995 was 0.4 fish/hour. Previouselectrofishing catch rates included 0.7 fish/hour in 1994, 1.9 fish/hour in 1993, 8.0fish/hour in 1991, and 57.7 fish/hour in 1990. The average size was 12.2 inches in the 1995electrofishing survey. Rock bass abundance in 1995 (1.6 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range (1.0 - 6.6fish/gillnet) for similar lakes, but below the historical average (6.2 fish/gillnet). Theaverage size in 1995 (8.3 inches, 0.7 lbs) was slightly above the historical average (7.9inches, 0.5 lbs). Black crappie abundance in 1995 (0 fish/gillnet, 0.3 fish/trapnet) was below the normalrange (0.2 - 1.1 fish/gillnet, 0.3 - 1.7 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes, and below thehistorical average (0.7 fish/gillnet, 0.6 fish/trapnet). Black crappie populations throughoutmost of Kandiyohi County have been low in recent years. Bluegill abundance in 1995 (29.5 fish/trapnet) was within the normal range (3.7 - 42.9fish/trapnet) for similar lakes, and above the historical average (62.7 fish/trapnet). Theaverage size in 1995 (5.8 inches) was above the historical average (4.9 inches). It appearsthat the population size structure and average size has improved slightly from previoussurveys. Important bluegill habitat include bulrush stands on the south shore (Spicer Castle)and the northeast outlet bay area. Black bullhead abundance in 1995 (4.1 fish/trapnet) was above the normal range (0.3 -2.1 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes, and above the historical average (1.9 fish/trapnet). Theaverage size in 1995 (6.2 inches) was below the historical average (8.7 inches). Yellowbullhead abundance in 1995 (0.2 fish/trapnet) was below the normal range (0.9 - 4.8fish/trapnet) for similar lakes, and below the historical average (0.5 fish/trapnet). Brownbullhead abundance in 1995 (0.6 fish/trapnet) was within the normal range (0.3 - 1.7fish/trapnet) for similar lakes, and the same as the historical average. Bowfin "dogfish" abundance in 1995 (0.4 fish/trapnet) was within the normal range (0.3 - 1.1 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes, but below the historical average (1.5 fish/trapnet).The average weight was 5.3 lbs in 1995 which is above the historical average (4.7 lbs). Carp abundance in 1995 (0.5 fish/trapnet) was within the normal range (0.2 - 1.0fish/trapnet) for similar lakes, but below the historical average (0.9 fish/trapnet). Theaverage size of carp caught in the trapnets was 11.7 lbs. One bigmouth buffalo (11.9 lbs) wascaught in a trapnet near the Spicer Castle. Green has the habitat, water quality, and forage base to potentially produce trophynorthern pike and smallmouth bass. In the past, abundant crayfish populations have beenimportant forage for producing smallmouth bass. Other abundant forage (cisco, yellow perch)have the potential to produce trophy northern pike. In addition, there usually is a cool,oxygenated layer present when the lake stratifies in mid summer (as evidenced by the ciscopopulation and relatively few summerkill events) which is conducive for producing trophynorthern pike. A statewide experimental regulation study for various species will includeGreen Lake. Experimental regulations will be implemented for smallmouth bass and northernpike by the beginning of the 1997 fishing opener. Related experimental regulations studyactivities include upcoming creel surveys in 1996-1997, annual spring bass electrofishingsurveys, and annual northern pike spawning run assessment netting. In addition, ice outtrapnetting and tagging of walleye will be conducted to get more information about populationsize and angler exploitation in conjunction with the creel surveys being conducted. Otherpriority management activities will include protecting present water quality, protecting andexpanding existing stands of hardstem bulrush, maintaining access to inlet and outlet marshesfor northern pike spawning, yearly assessment of cisco populations through fall gillnetting,and yearly evaluation of walleye natural reproduction through fall electrofishing. Walleyefingerling stocking on Green should only be considered after successive years of poor naturalreproduction as determined by fall electrofishing. The benefits of stocking as needed(successive years of poor natural reproduction) rather than on a prescribed schedule(stocking every even year) is that the valuable walleye fingerling resource can be used moreefficiently and effectively (higher rates) for other lakes. Furthermore, survival and growthof walleye in a lake may decrease when stocking occurs on top of good natural reproductiondue to more competition for limited resources (forage, habitat, etc.).

A population assessment of Green Lake was conducted in late July of 2004. Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegill. Green Lake receives high recreational use during the summer months. Approximately 628 homes/cabins were counted along the first tier shoreline area in addition to one bible camp, 22 condominiums/apartment buildings, one city park, and two county parks. There are six public access sites on Green Lake. Aquatic vegetation is generally limited in the lake. Low densities of Eurasian water milfoil have been documented in Green Lake primarily near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, and several isolated areas since 2000. Efforts to chemically eradicate Eurasian water milfoil have been unsuccessful. Widespread and extensive matting of Eurasian water milfoil is unlikely to occur through out Green Lake. The dominant substrates (boulder, rubble, gravel) present in the shoalwater areas are not suitable for aquatic vegetation establishment. Thirty-two inlets/tiles/culverts were identified draining into Green Lake during the 2003 resurvey. The largest inlet is the Middle Fork of the Crow River, which enters Green along the north shore via the Old Mill Inn Dam. The Middle Fork of the Crow River outlets near the northeast corner of Green and connects to Calhoun Lake. A Highway 23 four-lane construction project began adjacent to Green Lake during 2003. Significant runoff (sediment) from the Highway 23 construction project drained into Green Lake during several large rainfall events in late June and early July of 2003. One of the positive aspects of the Highway 23 project was the construction of retention ponds along the Highway 23 corridor to reduce or slow future runoff into Green Lake. Water clarity was poor during late August of 2003 (secchi=4.83 feet), but good during July of 2004 (secchi=13.20 feet). Green Lake is managed primarily for walleye, northern pike, tullibee, bluegill, and smallmouth bass. Walleye fingerling stocking is contingent in Green Lake after successive walleye natural reproduction or fry stocking failures.Experimental regulations for both northern pike and smallmouth bass were enacted in 1997 in order to increase the average size and produce trophy fisheries of smallmouth bass and northern pike in Green Lake. The northern pike experimental regulation (24 inch maximum size limit) prohibits the harvest of fish 24 inches and greater. The smallmouth and largemouth bass regulation was originally catch and release only. However, the bass regulation was modified to a 14 inch maximum harvest size limit in 2001. The bass regulation was modified again in the 2003 fall to a 14 inch maximum harvest size limit with one bass over 21 inches allowed. The bass regulation was changed because of increasing numbers of smallmouth bass and the perceived negative effects on the walleye population in Green Lake. A summer creel survey will be conducted on Green Lake during 2005 as an on going evaluation of the two experimental regulations. A public input meeting will occur during the 2005 fall to determine the fate of current experimental regulations for northern pike and bass on Green for 2006 and beyond.Bluegill numbers were moderate in 2004 (31.33 fish/trapnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes. The Green Lake bluegill historical average catch rate is 50.60 fish/trapnet. The 2004 bluegill average size was small (0.10 pounds and 4.92 inches) from the trapnets. The catch rate of quality size bluegill 6.00 inches and larger was low to moderate (6.93 fish/trapnet) in the 2004 assessment. The largest bluegill captured in the 2004 assessment was 9.02 inches from Green Lake. Northern pike numbers were low in 2004 (2.17 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and below the Green Lake northern pike historical average catch rate (2.95 fish/gillnet). The 2004 northern pike average size was moderate to large (3.86 pounds and 26.38 inches) from gillnets. The northern pike historical average length is 22.29 inches from gillnets. The northern pike captured in 2003 and 2004 were notably lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. Low numbers of forage fish (yellow perch and tullibee) were documented in 2003 and 2002 Green Lake surveys. Northern pike growth rates in Green were above the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-5. The 2001 northern pike year class comprised 30% of the 2004 total northern pike assessment catch. The northern pike population is also evaluated every other spring (2005) through ice out trapping. The northern pike average lengths have generally increased both in the summer and spring ice out surveys since the experimental regulation was enacted in 1997. The largest northern pike captured in the 2004 assessment was 40.94 inches from Green Lake.Smallmouth bass numbers were moderate to abundant in 2004 (2.17 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes. The smallmouth bass historical average catch rate is 1.96 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2004 smallmouth bass average size was large (1.95 pounds and 14.70 inches) from gillnets. The smallmouth bass historical average length is 13.19 inches from gillnets for Green Lake. The largest smallmouth bass captured in the 2004 assessment was 18.70 inches from Green Lake. The catch rate of smallmouth bass 14.00 inches and larger was moderate (1.67 fish/gillnet). The 2000 smallmouth bass year class comprised 18% of the total 2004 smallmouth bass assessment catch. Smallmouth bass growth rates in Green were below the Green Lake normal ranges for age 2-4. Crayfish, an important smallmouth bass forage species, were not caught in the 2004, 2003 or 2002 gillnets. The crayfish historical average catch rate is 12.6 crayfish/gillnet.Tullibee "cisco" numbers were low in 2004 (0.75 fish/gillnet) compared to the Green Lake tullibee historical average catch rate (2.67 fish/gillnet). The 2004 tullibee average size was small (0.25 pounds and 8.66 inches) from gillnets. The tullibee historical average weight is 0.43 pounds from gillnets. Yellow perch numbers were low in 2004 (2.75 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes. The yellow perch historical average catch rate is 18.96 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2004 yellow perch average size was small (0.12 pounds and 6.38 inches) from gillnets. The yellow perch historical average weight is 0.13 pounds from gillnets. Yellow perch growth rates in Green were below the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-5. The 2000 yellow perch year class comprised 32% of the 2004 total yellow perch assessment catch.Walleye numbers were low in 2004 (6.67 fish/gillnet) compared to the Green Lake walleye historical average catch rate (9.25 fish/gillnet). The 2004 walleye average size was moderate (1.25 pounds and 14.53 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average length is 14.63 inches from gillnets. The catch rate of walleye 15.00 inches and larger in 2004 (2.58 fish/gillnet) was below the historical average (4.05 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. The 2001 year class (stocked and natural reproduction) comprised 28% of the total 2004 walleye assessment catch. Walleye growth rates calculated from the 2004 Green assessment were above the Green Lake normal range for ages 1-8. A fall electrofishing survey of Green Lake was conducted on October 5, 2004. The 2004 fall electrofishing survey was conducted to evaluate walleye natural reproduction and a 2004 walleye fry stocking (2.06 million) in Green Lake. There were low young of year "YOY" walleye numbers (2.54 YOY/hour, 5.97 inches average length) captured in 2004. Other walleye naturally reproducing area lakes also had generally low YOY walleye catch rates in 2004 fall electrofishing surveys. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average catch rate and length are 17.22 YOY/hour and 6.78 inches respectively. The Spicer Area YOY walleye historical average catch rate is 70.22 YOY/hour from lakes fry stocked and lakes with natural reproduction. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY walleye for Green Lake occurred in 1994 (54.00 YOY/hour, 6.15 inches average size). Walleye fingerlings (63,160 fish, 2,383 pounds), yearlings (1,022 fish, 171 pounds), and adults (444 fish, 751 pounds) were stocked into Green Lake during early October of 2004 in response to poor walleye natural reproduction and fry stocking results for 2003 and 2004. Green Lake has been stocked annually with walleye fry from 2000-2004. Various combinations of walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked yearly (2,000 - 4,000 pounds/year) since 2000 into Green Lake.Rock bass numbers were abundant in 2004 (12.33 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes. The rock bass historical average catch rate is 7.07 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2004 rock bass average size was small (0.36 pounds and 7.36 inches) from gillnets. The rock bass historical average weight is 0.45 pounds from gillnets.Largemouth bass numbers were moderate in 2004 (0.42 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes. The Green Lake largemouth bass historical average catch rate is 0.18 fish/gillnet. The 2004 largemouth bass average size was small to moderate (0.95 pounds and 11.35 inches) from gillnets. The largemouth bass historical average weight is 0.64 pounds from gillnets.Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on a periodic basis, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives, and stocking various fish species as warranted. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the 2005 spring ice out for northern pike, 2005 fall for walleye natural reproduction, and 2005 summer for all fish species by survey nets and creel survey.

A population assessment of Green Lake was conducted in late July of 2007. Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegill. Green Lake receives high recreational use during the summer months. Green Lake is managed primarily for walleye, northern pike, tullibee, bluegill, and smallmouth bass.

Overall aquatic vegetation densities and frequency of occurrences were generally greater in 2007 than 2003. Water level and precipitation conditions were higher during 2003 compared to drought conditions in 2007 summer. Water clarity was poor during the late summer of 2003 (4.83 feet) compared to 2007 (7.20 feet). The water clarity average from June-September of 2007 (11.5 feet) for Green was above the historical average (10.8 feet). Aquatic vegetation densities generally increase during low water due to increased water clarity conditions and light penetration to substrate surface areas that were previously inaccessible. The maximum depth of vegetation was greater in 2007 (40 feet) than in 2003 (30 feet) or 1994 (35 feet). Aquatic vegetation species that increased in frequency occurrence and mean abundance from 2003 to 2007 included clasping-leaf pondweed, coontail, river pondweed, bushy pondweed, Eurasian milfoil, and bladderwort. Chara (muskgrass) frequency occurrence remained relatively unchanged in 2007 (94%) compared to 2003 (96%) and 1994 (92%), but mean abundance in the transects was 32.1% for 1994, 29.3% for 2003, and 44.3% for 2007. Vegetation species that were relatively unchanged in occurrence or mean abundance from 2003 to 2007 were curly-leaf pondweed, northern milfoil, and hardstem bulrush. Notable vegetation species that decreased in frequency and mean occurrence from 2003 to 2007 included filamentous algae, sago pondweed, water moss, variable-leaf pondweed, and stonewort.

Low densities of Eurasian water milfoil have been documented in Green Lake primarily near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, and several isolated areas since 2000. Efforts to chemically eradicate various Eurasian water milfoil stands were unsuccessful in 2000, 2001 and 2007. Eurasian milfoil occurred in 16% of the 2007 transects compared to 4% in the 2003 transects. Mean abundance of Eurasian milfoil within the transects increased from 1.3% in 2003 to 5.3% in 2007. Small widely scattered new Eurasian milfoil stands were observed in off shore "break" areas at a mean depth of 8.6 feet during 2007. Most large stands of Eurasian milfoil on Green Lake have been located near storm water inlets. Watershed projects that may reduce sediment and nutrient inputs from storm water inlets will be important for controlling Eurasian milfoil. Widespread-extensive matting of Eurasian water milfoil is unlikely to occur through out Green Lake due to the presence of relatively low nitrogen (ammonium) nutrient levels and unsuitable dominant substrates (boulder, rubble, gravel) present in the shoalwater areas.

Experimental regulations for northern pike, smallmouth bass, and largemouth bass were enacted in Green Lake during 1997 as part of a statewide research study. The goals were to evaluate the success or failure of certain types of experimental regulations, and produce trophy fisheries of bass and northern pike in Green Lake. A public input meeting in regards to the future of Green Lake experimental regulations occurred during the 2005 fall. In December of 2005, the DNR decided to end all experimental regulations on Green Lake (largemouth bass, smallmouth bass and northern pike) and return to statewide regulations as of the May 13, 2006 for northern pike and May 27, 2006 for bass. This decision was based both on public input and the analyzed data collected from netting and creel surveys.

Bluegill numbers were high in 2007 (51.64/trapnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, but comparable to the Green historical average (49.36 fish/trapnet). The 2007 bluegill average size was moderate (0.13 pounds and 5.54 inches) from the trapnets. The bluegill historical average length is 5.21 inches from trapnets. There were moderate numbers of quality size (6.00 inches) and larger bluegill (16.38 fish/trapnet) in the 2007 trapnets.

Black crappie numbers were moderate to high in 2007 (1.83 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and above the Green historical average (0.78 fish/gillnet). The 2007 black crappie average size was moderate (0.47 pounds and 8.85 inches) from gillnets. The black crappie historical average length is 7.75 inches from gillnets in Green. There were moderate to high numbers of quality size (8.00 inches) and larger black crappie (1.25 fish/gillnet) in the 2007 gillnets. Growth rates were near or below the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-6. The 2005 black crappie year class comprised 65% of the 2007 black crappie gillnet catch.

Northern pike numbers were low in 2007 (1.92 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and below the Green historical average (2.82 fish/gillnet). The 2007 northern pike average size was large (5.14 pounds and 28.12 inches) from gillnets. The northern pike historical average length is 23.03 inches from gillnets. Northern pike captured in 2003-2006 surveys were notably lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. Large northern pike (>24 inches) condition factors were near or below the Green normal range since 1999 except for 2001 and 2002. Low numbers of forage fish (yellow perch and tullibee) were documented in Green Lake surveys from 2003-2007. There were moderate to high numbers of preferred size (28.00 inches) and larger northern pike (0.83 fish/gillnet) in the 2007 gillnets. Spearing pressure and harvest of large northern pike was high during the 2006-07 winter following the return to statewide regulations. Northern pike growth rates were near or above the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-3, near or below the normal ranges for ages 4-6, and within the normal ranges for ages 7-8. Growth rates were generally above the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-8. Several year classes (2001-2004) were present in similar numbers during the 2007 gillnet catch.

Smallmouth bass numbers were high in 2007 (1.50 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, but below the Green historical average (1.98 fish/gillnet). The 2007 smallmouth bass size was large (2.00 pounds and 15.19 inches) from gillnets. The smallmouth bass historical average length is 13.40 inches from gillnets. There were moderate to high numbers of preferred size (14.00 inches) and larger smallmouth bass (1.25 fish/gillnet) in the 2007 gillnets. The 2002 smallmouth bass year class comprised 63% of the 2007 smallmouth bass gillnet catch. Smallmouth bass growth rates were near or below the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-5, but within the normal ranges for ages 6-7. Smallmouth bass condition factors have been near or below the Green normal ranges since 2000. Crayfish, an important smallmouth bass forage species, were not captured in 2007, low in 2006 (0.1 crayfish/gillnet) and 2005 (0.2 crayfish/gillnet). No crayfish were caught in the 2004, 2003 or 2002 gillnets. The crayfish historical average catch rate is 9.7 crayfish/gillnet for Green.

Tullibee "cisco" numbers were low to moderate in the 2007 (1.00 fish/gillnet) summer compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and below the Green historical average (2.41 fish/gillnet). The 2007 summer tullibee average size was large (1.28 pounds and 14.10 inches) from gillnets. The tullibee historical average weight is 0.47 pounds from gillnets.

Yellow perch numbers were low in 2007 (3.75 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and below the Green historical average (17.08 fish/gillnet). The 2007 yellow perch average size was moderate (0.12 pounds and 6.59 inches) from gillnets. The yellow perch historical average weight is 0.13 pounds from gillnets. Yellow perch growth rates were within the Spicer Area normal ranges, but above the Green normal ranges for ages 1-4. The 2005 (56%)and 2004 (33%) yellow perch year classes comprised the majority of the 2007 yellow perch gillnet catch. Yellow perch condition factors have been near or below the Green normal range since 2003.

Walleye numbers were high in 2007 (12.00 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and above the Green historical average (9.17 fish/gillnet). The 2007 walleye average size was moderate to small (1.10 pounds and 13.86 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average length is 14.62 inches from gillnets. There were moderate numbers of quality size (15.00 inches) and larger walleye (3.25 fish/gillnet) in the 2007 gillnets. The 2004 year class (stocked and natural reproduction) comprised 41% of the total 2007 walleye gillnet catch. The 2006 and 2005 year classes comprised 24% and 20% respectively of the 2007 gillnet catch. Walleye growth rates were generally below the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-8, but at or above the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-8. Walleye condition factors have been above the Green normal range since 1999.

A fall electrofishing survey of Green Lake was conducted during early October of 2007. The 2007 fall electrofishing survey was conducted to evaluate walleye natural reproduction and a 2007 walleye fry (OTC marked) stocking (1.04 million) in Green Lake. The walleye fry were stocked as a 10% return of walleye eggs taken for the statewide propagation program. There were low young of year "YOY" walleye numbers (6.00 YOY/hour, 7.01 inches average length) captured in 2007. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average catch rate and length are 14.78 YOY/hour and 6.85 inches. The Spicer Area YOY walleye historical average catch rate is 71.24 YOY/hour from lakes fry stocked and lakes with natural reproduction. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY walleye for Green occurred in 1994 (54.00 YOY/hour, 6.15 inches average size). Walleye fingerlings (50,385 fish, 2,640 pounds), yearlings (27,232 fish, 3,279 pounds), and adults (4,270 fish, 2,281 pounds) were stocked into Green during early April-November of 2007. Green Lake has been stocked annually with walleye fry from 2000-2007 except for 2002. Various combinations of walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked yearly (2,000  4,000 pounds/year) since 2000 into Green Lake. During the 1990s, walleye fry were stocked in 1996 and fingerlings/yearlings/adults were stocked in 1994, 1992, 1990.

Rock bass numbers were high in 2007 (8.58 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and above the Green historical average (7.31 fish/gillnet). The 2007 rock bass average size was moderate (0.33 pounds and 7.10 inches) from gillnets. The rock bass historical average weight is 0.43 pounds from gillnets.

Largemouth bass numbers were high in 2007 (2.58 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, and above the Green historical average (0.52 fish/gillnet). The 2007 largemouth bass average size was small (0.56 pounds and 9.25 inches) from gillnets. Largemouth bass growth rates were below or near the low end of the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 2-6, but within the Green normal ranges. The 2005 largemouth bass year class comprised 55% of the 2007 largemouth bass assessment gillnet catch.

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the 2008 fall for walleye natural reproduction, and 2008 summer for all fish species by survey nets.

A population assessment of Green Lake was conducted in early August of 2011. Green is a large (5,406 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Water levels were high during the 2011 spring and summer, but normal by late fall. Water clarity was moderate (8.0 feet) for Green Lake on August 3, 2011. The 2011 summer weather was wet and hot with high temperatures above 90 F during several weeks during July. Dissolved oxygen levels were below 2.0 ppm in depths below 32 feet during early August of 2011. A combination of inadequate oxygen levels (< 2ppm) and potentially lethal high temperatures (> 72 F) in water depths below 30 feet were conducive for a tullibee "cisco" fish kill during a relatively short time period of late July thru early August of 2011. A few local residents reported dead tullibee near shore areas of Green during 2011. We observed only a few dead tullibees during the 2011 population assessment. A major summerkill of tullibee occurred during the same time period on nearby Lake Koronis in 2011 with pelicans feeding greatly on the dead fish. Green is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and bluegill. Green Lake receives high recreational use during the summer months. Green Lake is managed primarily for walleye and secondarily for northern pike, yellow perch, cisco "tullibee", bluegill, and smallmouth bass.

The threats of present (Eurasian water milfoil, curly-leaf pondweed) and potential exotic invasive species introductions (i.e. zebra mussels, quagga mussels, spiny water flea, faucet snail, etc.) are of a major concern to local residents in Kandiyohi County. Eurasian water milfoil "EWM" was first documented in Green Lake at several isolated sites during 2000. Initial DNR attempts to chemically eradicate EWM were unsuccessful. Eurasian water milfoil has spread throughout the lake in scattered stands especially near the Spicer public access, swimming beach, city dock, Indian Beach Lagoon, storm water inlet areas and off shore "break" areas since 2000.

The lake association has continued to chemically and physically eradicate various EWM stands in recent years with relatively minimal long term success. New developments in chemical control of EWM (i.e. granular triclopyr treatment) were attempted in Green Lake during 2010, but initial results for 2010 appeared to be unsuccessful in eradicating EWM probably due to continual mixing and wave action, which probably dilutes the herbicide concentrations in EWM infested areas. In 2011, Eurasian milfoil stands appeared less prevalent than during previous years. It is unknown if chemical treatments in 2010 and 2011 or high water conditions negatively affected the establishment of Eurasian milfoil stands. Submergent vegetation densities are often greater during low water level years due to increased light penetration to previously deeper substrate areas of the lake. Often times, algal populations dominate over submergent vegetation in a lake during high water level conditions due to an influx of nutrients (phosphorus) and more turbid water conditions.

EWM and curly-leaf pondweed tend to thrive in disturbed areas (i.e. previously chemically or mechanically treated areas, storm water inlets) or during years of minimal snowfall and maximum light penetration when competition from native species is minimal. Many large stands of EMW on Green Lake have been located near storm water inlets. Watershed projects that may reduce sediment and nutrient inputs from storm water inlets will also be important for controlling EMW in these patchy areas. Widespread-extensive matting of EMW on the surface is unlikely to occur throughout Green Lake unlike some milfoil infested lakes with protected bay areas (i.e. Minnetonka) due to frequent windswept conditions, the presence of relatively low nitrogen (ammonium) nutrient levels and unsuitable dominant substrates (boulder, rubble, gravel) present in the majority of shoal water areas of Green Lake. DNR Aquatic invasive species interns will continue to randomly monitor boats entering and leaving the many access sites in an attempt to educate and prevent the spread of exotics into Kandiyohi County Lakes.

Bluegill numbers were moderate in 2011 (31.47/trapnet) and within the normal ranges for Green and similar lakes. The Green Lake bluegill historical average catch rate is 47.77 fish/trapnet. The 2011 bluegill average size was moderate (0.20 pounds and 6.08 inches) from trapnets. The bluegill historical average weight is 0.12 pounds from trapnets. The 2011 catch rate of quality size (6.00 inches) and larger bluegill (20.38 fish/trapnet) was high and above the historical average (12.59 fish/trapnet). The 2011 catch rate of preferred size (8.00 inches) and larger bluegill (0.80 fish/trapnet) was low.

Black crappie numbers were high in 2011 gillnets (3.08 fish/gillnet) and trapnets (3.40 fish/trapnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green and similar lakes. The Green Lake black crappie historical average catch rates are 0.99 fish/gillnet and 0.69 fish/trapnet. The 2011 black crappie average sizes were small for gillnets (0.16 pounds and 5.99 inches), but moderate for trapnets (0.45 pounds and 8.95 inches). The black crappie historical average lengths are 7.82 inches for gillnets and 7.66 inches for trapnets in Green. The 2011 catch rate of quality size (8.00 inches and larger) black crappie (2.93 fish/trapnet) was high and above the historical average (0.34 fish/trapnet).

Northern pike numbers were low to moderate in 2011 (2.33 fish/gillnet) and near the low ends of the normal ranges for Green and similar lakes. The Green Lake northern pike historical average catch rate is 2.72 fish/gillnet. The 2011 northern pike average size was moderate (3.76 pounds and 24.39 inches) from gillnets. The northern pike historical average weight and length are 3.28 pounds and 23.17 inches from gillnets. The 2011 catch rate of preferred size (28.00 inches) and larger northern pike (0.33 fish/gillnet) was low, but similar to the historical average (0.42 fish/gillnet). Northern pike captured in 2003, 2004 2005, 2007 and 2009 assessments were notably lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. The 2011 northern pike condition factor (0.658) was above the Green Lake normal range. Low numbers of forage fish (yellow perch and tullibee) were documented in Green Lake assessments from 2003-2011. Northern pike growth rates were within the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-8. The 2007-2009 year classes each comprised 24% of the 2011 northern pike gillnet and trapnet catch.

Smallmouth bass numbers were moderate in 2011 (1.83 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for Green, but above the normal range for similar lakes. The smallmouth bass historical average catch rate is 1.94 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2011 smallmouth bass average size was moderate to large (1.37 pounds and 12.51 inches) from gillnets. The smallmouth bass historical average weight and length are 1.76 pounds and 13.92 inches from gillnets for Green Lake. The 2011 catch rate of preferred size (14.00 inches) and larger smallmouth bass (1.25 fish/gillnet) was high, but near the historical average (1.22 fish/gillnet). The 2011 smallmouth bass condition factor (1.472) was within the normal range for Green. Smallmouth bass condition factors have been near or below the Green Lake normal ranges since 2000 except for 2011. The 2005 year class comprised 32% of the 2011 smallmouth bass gillnet catch. Smallmouth bass growth rates were within the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-2, but below the normal ranges for ages 3-8.

Crayfish, an important smallmouth bass forage species, were not captured in 2007-2009. Low numbers of crayfish were captured in 2011 (1.1 crayfish/gillnet), 2010 (0.3 crayfish/gillnet), 2006 (0.1 crayfish/gillnet) and 2005 (0.2 crayfish/gillnet). No crayfish were caught in the 2002-2004 gillnets. The crayfish historical average catch rate is 7.5 crayfish/gillnet for Green.

Tullibee "cisco" numbers were moderate in the 2011 summer (1.50 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Green and similar lakes. The tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 2.39 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. A majority of the tullibee were captured in summer gillnet stations located along the east and south portions of the lake at a depth of approximately 30 feet. The 2011 summer tullibee average size was moderate (0.96 pounds and 12.65 inches) from gillnets. The tullibee historical average weight is 0.58 pounds from gillnets.

There were low numbers of tullibee in 2011 DNR fall test nets and 2010 fall special assessment (3.8 fish/gillnet). The 2010 tullibee average size was small (0.77 pounds and 11.66 inches) for Green in the 2010 fall. The fall tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 79.9 fish/gillnet and 12.44 inches for Green Lake. The 2007 and 2006 year classes comprised 41% and 27% of the 2010 fall tullibee catch in Green Lake. In 2011 fall, private netters had poor netting success for tullibee. The lack of adult tullibee on the spawning grounds from early November to early December of 2010 and 2011 as sampled by both DNR and private netters during the open season is not a good indication for the long term sustainability of the tullibee population in Green Lake. Hopefully, cool summers will occur during the next several years, which may result in a good hatch and survival of tullibee in Green Lake if adequate brood stock numbers are still present.

Yellow perch numbers were low in 2011 (2.50 fish/gillnet) and below the normal ranges for Green and similar lakes. The yellow perch historical average catch rate is 14.91 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2011 yellow perch average size was small (0.11 pounds and 6.17 inches) from gillnets. The yellow perch historical average weight is 0.13 pounds from gillnets. There were no yellow perch of quality size (8.00 inches) and larger in the 2011 gillnets. Yellow perch growth rates were below the Green Lake and Spicer Area lakes normal ranges for ages 1-8. The 2006 and 2007 yellow perch year classes each comprised about 30% of the 2011 yellow perch gillnet catch.

Walleye numbers were high in 2011 (14.42 fish/gillnet) and above the normal ranges for Green and similar lakes. The walleye historical average catch rate is 9.16 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2011 walleye average size was moderate (1.18 pounds and 14.15 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average weight and length are 1.26 pounds and 14.66 inches from gillnets. The 2011 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches) and larger walleye (5.25 fish/gillnet) was moderate, but above the historical average (3.88 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. The 2011 catch rate of preferred size (20.00 inches) and larger walleye (1.00 fish/gillnet) was low, but similar to the historical average (0.74 fish/gillnet). The 2011 walleye condition factor (0.914 Fulton K-Factor) was above the normal range for Green. Growth rates were within the Green Lake normal ranges for ages 1-3 and above the normal ranges for ages 4-8. The recent walleye year classes since 2001 are due mostly to stocking of fingerlings and fry. The 2008 and 2009 walleye year classes comprised about 28% and 23% respectively of the 2011 walleye gillnet and trapnet catch.

A fall electrofishing assessment of Green Lake was conducted on September 27, 2011. The 2011 fall electrofishing assessment was conducted to evaluate walleye natural reproduction and a 2011 walleye fry stocking in Green Lake. Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked walleye fry (about 2 million) were stocked in Green each year during 2009-2011. The walleye fry were stocked in part as a 10% return of walleye eggs taken for the statewide propagation program.

Moderate numbers of young of year "YOY" walleye were captured in 2011 fall electrofishing survey (31.00 YOY/hour, 6.46 inches average length). OTC marked YOY walleye (fry stocked) comprised 63.3% (19.62 YOY/hour) of the 2011 fall survey catch. Yearling walleye numbers (3.00 fish/hour, 9.71 inches) were low in the 2011 fall survey. There were low numbers of YOY walleye (11.00 YOY/hour, 6.60 inches average length) captured in 2010. Walleye yearling numbers were low to moderate (9.00 fish/hour, 9.18 inches average length) in the 2010 fall electrofishing survey. Marked fish from 2009 and 2010 stockings accounted for 55% of YOY walleye catch and 13% of the yearling walleye catch in the 2010 fall electrofishing survey. The Spicer Area YOY walleye historical average catch rate is 82.54 YOY/hour. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average YOY walleye catch rate and length are 14.46 YOY/hour and 6.74 inches. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY walleye for Green occurred in 1994 (54.00 YOY/hour, 6.15 inches average size). Walleye unmarked fingerlings (66,000 fish, 3,081 pounds) and OTC marked fry (2,357,895 fish) were stocked into Green during early April-November of 2011. Green Lake has been stocked annually with walleye fry (1-2 million) from 2000-2011 except for 2002. Various combinations of walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) since 2000 into Green Lake. During the 1990's, walleye fry were stocked in 1996 and larger walleye (fingerlings and adults) were stocked in 1994, 1992 and 1990.

Rock bass numbers were high in 2011 (11.75 fish/gillnet) and above the normal ranges for Green and similar lakes. The rock bass historical average catch rate is 7.83 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2011 rock bass average size was moderate (0.34 pounds and 7.09 inches) from gillnets. The rock bass historical average weight is 0.42 pounds from gillnets.

Largemouth bass numbers were moderate in 2011 (0.42 fish/gillnet) and within the normal ranges for Green and similar lakes. The largemouth bass historical average catch rate is 0.64 fish/gillnet for Green. The 2011 largemouth bass average size was moderate (0.90 pounds and 11.28 inches) from gillnets. The largemouth bass historical average weight is 0.68 pounds from gillnets. Growth rates were generally below the Green Lake and Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-7.

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the 2012 fall for walleye natural reproduction, and 2012 summer for all fish species by assessment nets.

A standard survey of Green Lake was conducted during early August of 2015. A creel survey was also conducted on Green Lake during 2014-15 winter and 2015 summer. Green is a large (5,561 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), highly developed (690 homes) and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. It is a popular recreational lake. Green is also a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Smallmouth Bass, Black Crappie (recent years) and Bluegill. A broad band (3-36 feet) of ideal temperatures (<74 F) and dissolved oxygen levels (>3 ppm) for tullibee were present in Green during late summers for 2013-2015. Water clarity was moderate (8.5 feet) for Green Lake on August 3, 2015. Local residents reported excellent water clarity (>20 feet deep) during the 2015-16 winter. Late ice on (December 27, 2015) and poor ice conditions occurred which resulted in reduced observed winter angling pressure (fish house counts) on Green and many other local lakes during the early part of the 2015-16 winter. Ice off occurred on March 22, 2016 which was the second earliest occurrence for Green Lake.

Climate change effects have been noticeable for ice covered days, water clarity, habitat and species density changes in Green Lake during recent decades. Periphyton (algae, diatoms) and dead plant material now cover the boulder/rubble substrates generally all year long with the exception of some narrow (<1 foot deep) windswept near shore areas. This has favored warm water species (Black Crappie, bass species, Bluegill and Rock Bass) which are nest spawners, unlike broadcast spawners such as Walleye and Tullibee "Cisco". In addition, increased densities of submergent vegetation such as invasive Eurasian watermilfoil have provided added habitat/cover for all fish species. Water clarity and occasional late summer blue-green algae bloom events are also expected to increase in the future due to the effects of the recent zebra mussel infestation in Green during 2014.

The threats of present (zebra mussels, Eurasian watermilfoil, and curly-leaf pondweed) and potential exotic invasive species introductions (i.e. starry stonewort, quagga mussels, spiny water flea, faucet snail, etc.) are of a major concern to local residents in Kandiyohi County. One adult zebra mussel was found on a dock along the southeast shore of Green during the early summer of 2014. No additional zebra mussels were found until the fall of 2014. Numerous small young zebra mussels were found attached on docks and boat lifts scattered throughout Green Lake in 2015. Eradication of zebra mussels is improbable once mussels spread throughout a lake due to their ability to reproduce large numbers of young zebra mussel "veligers" by a small number of adults. Green Lake will continue to be monitored to document impacts zebra mussels may have on the lake ecology (i.e. water clarity, substrate effects, aquatic vegetation, plankton abundance, native species responses, etc.).

Bluegill numbers were abundant (44.87 fish/trapnet) in 2015. Bluegill average size was moderate (5.8 inches) and has improved in recent years. Black Crappie numbers (1.75 fish/gillnet) and average size (0.4 pounds and 8.0 inches) have also improved in Green. Abundant numbers of small sized (10.1 inches average) Largemouth Bass are also present in Green. Rock Bass numbers (14.67 fish/gillnet) were at a historical high in 2015. Scattered patches of submergent vegetation (Eurasian watermilfoil) and edges of weed lines (10-15 feet deep) have provided good habitat and fishing areas for Largemouth Bass, Bluegill and Black Crappie. In recent years, good crappie fishing has occurred during the spring and fall on Green.

Northern Pike numbers (1.50 fish/gillnet) were below the normal range in 2015. The Northern Pike average size was moderate (3.9 pounds and 25.0 inches). Green has the ability to produce trophy size Northern Pike due in part to the tullibee forage base. However, Northern Pike have been generally lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the surveys prior to 2003. Important forage fish numbers of Yellow Perch (1.67 fish/gillnet) and Tullibee (0.92 fish/gillnet) were low in Green Lake during 2015 and previous assessments since 2003.

Smallmouth Bass numbers in 2015 (1.08 fish/gillnet) were moderate compared to previous years. The Smallmouth Bass average size is large (1.58 pounds and 13.85 inches). Green is a popular fishing lake for large sized Smallmouth Bass by local and tournament anglers. Crayfish, an important Smallmouth Bass forage species, have been present in low numbers since 1999. Crayfish numbers may increase in the future due to an abundant new forage species "zebra mussel" present in Green. Research has identified crayfish and Pumpkinseed as potential predators on smaller zebra mussels.

Walleye numbers in 2015 (5.25 fish/gillnet) were within the normal range but below the Green Lake historical average (8.94 fish/gillnet). The 2015 Walleye average size was moderate (1.1 pounds and 14.0 inches). The 2011 and 2013 year classes comprised the majority of the Walleye survey catch in 2015. Local anglers had moderate Walleye fishing success during the 2014-15 winter, 2015 summer and fall as reported to creel clerks. Natural reproduction has been poor since the mid 1990's as measured by fall electrofishing surveys. Recent Walleye year classes have been due mostly to stocking since 2001. Green Lake was stocked annually with Walleye fry (1-4 million) from 2000-2013 except for 2002. No Walleye fry were stocked in 2014 or 2015 due to the cessation of egg take operations on Green Lake. Walleye fry stocked during previous years were part of a 10% return of Walleye eggs taken for the statewide propagation program. Walleye fingerlings (38,121 fish, 3,057 pounds) were last stocked into Green during 2015. Various combinations of Walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) since 2000 into Green Lake.

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking Walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be surveyed again in the 2016 summer for all fish species by assessment nets and the 2016 fall for Walleye natural reproduction by electrofishing.

A standard survey of Green Lake was conducted during early August of 2016. A fall electrofishing survey was conducted on September 28, 2016 to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye abundance in Green Lake. A creel survey was conducted on Green Lake during 2015. Green is a large (5,561 acres), deep (110 feet maximum), highly developed (690 homes) and moderately productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Smallmouth Bass, Black Crappie (recent years) and Bluegill. There are approximately 48 inlets that enter Green Lake. The Middle Fork Crow River is the largest inlet and enters Green along the north shore and exits along the east side eventually flowing into Calhoun Lake. Direct nutrient runoff into Green is primarily from highway runoff and residential sources, which include lake homes and the city of Spicer. There is also upstream agricultural row crop runoff that enters into the Middle Fork Crow River. Water levels were high during the summer and fall of 2016 due to frequent rainfall events. Water clarity was excellent (12.7 feet) for Green Lake on July 28, 2016. A broad band (3-36 feet) of ideal temperatures (<74 degrees Fahrenheit "F") and dissolved oxygen levels (>3 ppm) for Tullibee were present in Green during late summers for 2013-2015. There was adequate dissolved oxygen (>3 ppm) and temperature conditions (<74 F) for Tullibee at depths of 27-35 feet during the August 2015 survey and 40-60 feet during the 2016 survey. The most frequently observed submergent and algal vegetation species or groups included Chara, Stonewort, Eurasian Watermilfoil, River Pondweed, Water Moss, Clasping-leaf Pondweed, Sago Pondweed and Curly-leaf Pondweed. Emergent vegetation such as Hardstem Bulrush is abundant in the outlet bay. A moderate stand of bulrush is also present along the southeast shore. Shoalwater substrates are mostly sand, rubble, gravel and boulder. Recent ice on dates were December 10, 2016 and December 27, 2015. Snow and mild temperatures resulted in poor conditions (<6 inches of ice), thus limiting access on Green and many other local lakes during December of 2016. Recent ice off dates were March 21, 2017 and March 22, 2016 which were the second and third earliest occurrences for Green Lake.

Climate change effects have been noticeable for both habitat and species density changes in Green Lake during recent decades. Periphyton (algae, diatoms) and dead plant material now cover the boulder/rubble substrates generally all year long with the exception of some narrow (<1 foot deep) windswept near shore areas. This has favored warm water species (Black Crappie, Largemouth Bass, Bluegill, Rock Bass) which are nest spawners, unlike broadcast spawners such Walleye and Tullibee "Cisco". In addition, increased densities of submergent vegetation such as invasive Eurasian Watermilfoil (first documented in 2000) have provided added habitat/cover for all fish species.

The threats of present (Zebra Mussels, Eurasian Watermilfoil, and Curly-leaf Pondweed) and potential exotic invasive species introductions (i.e. Starry Stonewort, Quagga Mussels, Spiny Water Flea, Faucet Snail, etc.) are of a major concern to local residents in Kandiyohi County. One adult Zebra Mussel was found on a dock along the southeast shore of Green during the early summer of 2014. No additional Zebra Mussels were found until the fall of 2014. Numerous small young Zebra Mussels were found attached on docks and boat lifts scattered throughout Green Lake in 2015. Eradication of Zebra Mussels is improbable once Mussels spread throughout a lake due to their ability to reproduce large numbers of young Zebra Mussel "veligers" by a small number of adults. Green Lake will continue to be monitored to document impacts Zebra Mussels may have on the lake ecology (i.e. water clarity, substrate effects, aquatic vegetation, plankton abundance, native species responses, etc.). Water clarity and occasional late summer blue-green algae bloom events are also expected to increase in the future due to the potential effects of the recent Zebra Mussel infestation in Green.

Bluegill numbers were moderate in 2016 (23.53 fish/trapnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, but below the historical average (45.39 fish/trapnet). Bluegill average size was large (0.28 pounds and 7.0 inches) from trapnets. The Bluegill historical average weight is 0.14 pounds from trapnets. There were abundant numbers of Bluegill (20.92 fish/trapnet) 6.0 inches and larger in the trapnets.

Black Crappie numbers were moderate in 2016 (0.92 fish/gillnet, 1.07 fish/trapnet) compared to the historical averages (1.26 fish/gillnet and 0.77 fish/trapnet). Black Crappie average sizes were moderate from gillnets (0.57 pounds and 9.3 inches), but slightly smaller from trapnets (0.37 pounds and 8.0 inches). Black Crappie growth rates were excellent.

Northern Pike numbers were low in 2016 (2.33 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and the historical average (2.71 fish/gillnet). Northern Pike average size was moderate (2.89 pounds and 23.4 inches) from gillnets. The Northern Pike historical average weight and length are 3.17 pounds and 23.4 inches from gillnets. Northern Pike have been generally lean in appearance compared to fish captured in the assessments prior to 2003. Low numbers of forage fish (Yellow Perch and Tullibee) have been documented in Green Lake surveys from 2003-2016. Northern Pike growth rates were poor for ages 1-3, but moderate for ages 4-7. The 2013 year class comprised 39% of the 2016 Northern Pike catch.

Smallmouth Bass numbers were low in 2016 (1.08 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (1.82 fish/gillnet). Smallmouth Bass average size was large (2.16 pounds and 15.6 inches) from gillnets. The Smallmouth Bass historical average weight and length are 1.55 pounds and 13.4 inches from gillnets for Green Lake. Smallmouth Bass condition factors have been generally poor since 2001. Smallmouth Bass growth rates were poor for ages 1-7. Crayfish, an important Smallmouth Bass forage species, have been present in low numbers since 1999. Crayfish numbers may increase in the future due to a new forage species "Zebra Mussel" present in Green. In response, this may also provide a greater forage base "crayfish" for Smallmouth Bass. The 2010 and 2011 year classes each comprised 29% of the 2016 Smallmouth Bass gillnet catch.

Tullibee numbers were low in the 2016 summer survey (0.17 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (2.06 fish/gillnet). The 2016 summer Tullibee average size was small (0.42 pounds and 10.8) inches from gillnets. The Tullibee historical summer average weight is 0.60 pounds from gillnets. The 2012 Tullibee year class comprised 100% of the 2016 Tullibee summer survey catch. Tullibee numbers were also low (10.33 fish/gillnet, 13.7 inches average) in the 2015 fall assessment. The inconsistency of Tullibee natural reproduction and inadequate adult Tullibee numbers on the spawning grounds as sampled by the DNR is not a good indication for the long term sustainability of the Tullibee populations in Green.

Yellow Perch numbers were low in 2016 (0.67 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and the historical average (12.73 fish/gillnet). Local anglers have reported seeing numerous small Yellow Perch amongst the chara beds with cameras during the summer or while spearing in the winter. Our standard gillnets may not effectively sample these small (<5.0 inches) Yellow Perch. Predation pressures from various species (i.e. Rock Bass, Largemouth Bass, Walleye, etc.) may have also selected for smaller sized and earlier reproducing Yellow Perch restricted to near bottom cover consisting of dense chara beds in Green. Yellow Perch average size was moderate to small (0.11 pounds and 6.6 inches) from gillnets.

Walleye numbers were low in 2016 (5.33 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (8.82 fish/gillnet) for Green Lake. The 2016 Walleye average size was moderate (1.21 pounds and 14.8 inches) from gillnets. The Walleye historical average weight and length are 1.26 pounds and 14.7 inches from gillnets. Walleye condition factors were poor in 2016. Growth rates were also poor compared to other Spicer Area lakes, but variable by age compared to Green Lake historical values. Recent Walleye year classes have been due mostly to stocking since 2001. The 2016 walleye survey catch was comprised primarily of 2011 (19%), 2012 (19%), 2013 (32%) and 2014 (19%) year classes. The 2011 Walleye year class was successful in many area lakes.

Green Lake was stocked annually with Walleye fry (1-4 million) from 2000-2013 except for 2002. OTC marked Walleye fry (1-2 million) were stocked in Green each year during 2000-2001, 2007-2013 and 2016. No Walleye fry were stocked in 2014 or 2015 due to the cessation of egg take operations on Green Lake. Walleye fry stocked during previous years were mostly part of a 10% return of Walleye eggs taken for the statewide propagation program. Walleye unmarked Spicer strain fingerlings and yearlings (18,413 fish, 1,784 pounds) were stocked into Green during the 2016 fall. Various combinations of Walleye fingerlings, yearlings, or adults have been stocked annually (2,000-4,000 pounds/year) since 2000 into Green Lake.

No YOY Walleye were captured during the 2016 or 2015 fall electrofishing surveys. Low YOY Walleye numbers were captured in the 2014 (4.0 YOY/hour, 7.6 inches average length) and 2013 (5.0 YOY/hour, 6.40 inches average length) fall electrofishing surveys. OTC marked fry captured as fingerlings comprised 40% of the 2013 and 55% (=6.6 YOY/hour) of the 2012 fall electrofishing surveys. Moderate numbers of YOY Walleye were captured in a previous 2011 fall electrofishing survey (31.0 YOY/hour, 6.5 inches average length). OTC marked YOY Walleye (fry stocked) comprised 63% (=19.6 YOY/hour) of the 2011 fall YOY Walleye survey catch. The Green Lake fall electrofishing historical average YOY Walleye catch rate and length are 12.3 YOY/hour and 6.8 inches. The highest fall electrofishing catch rate of YOY Walleye for Green occurred in 1994 (54.0 YOY/hour, 6.2 inches average size). Yearling Walleye numbers were moderate to low in the 2014 (6.0 fish/hour) and 2016 (3.0 fish/hour) fall surveys. No yearling Walleye were captured in the 2015 fall electrofishing survey.

Rock Bass numbers were abundant in 2016 (13.08 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range of similar lakes. It was the highest recorded value for Green Lake. The Rock Bass historical average catch rate is 8.59 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. The 2016 Rock Bass average size was moderate (0.41 pounds and 7.8 inches from gillnets.

Largemouth Bass numbers were abundant in 2016 (1.17 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and the historical average (0.79 fish/gillnet). Largemouth Bass average size was moderate (0.72 pounds and 10.5 inches) from gillnets. The Largemouth Bass historical average weight is 0.69 pounds from gillnets. Largemouth Bass growth rates were poor for ages 1-5, but moderate for older fish.

Other species captured included low numbers of White Sucker (0.50 fish/gillnet), Common Carp (0.27 fish/trapnet), Pumpkinseed (0.07 fish/trapnet), Hybrid Sunfish (1.40 fish/trapnet) and Black Bullhead (0.17 fish/gillnet). Moderate numbers of large Yellow Bullhead were captured in 2016 (3.00 fish/gillnet, 1.01 pounds average weight).

An Index of Biotic Integrity "IBI" survey was conducted from August 2-3, 2016 on Green Lake. One measure of a lake's health is the community of fish, plants and aquatic life it sustains. Certain species can't survive without clean water and a healthy habitat while other species are tolerant of degraded conditions. Examples of fish that require clean water are Tullibee, Rock Bass, and Bluegill. Species that are tolerant to degraded habitat are Black Bullhead, Common Carp, and Green Sunfish. The more intolerant fish to degraded habitat you have in the sample, the higher the score will be. An index of biological integrity (IBI) is a score that compares the types and numbers of fish or plants observed in a lake to what is expected for a healthy lake.

Seine hauls were conducted at 24 IBI stations with a bag seine of 50 foot width and 1/8 inch bar mesh in depths of 3.5 feet or less. Near shore electrofishing was conducted at 23 of 24 IBI Stations with a back-pack unit in water depths generally less than 2 feet deep. One electrofishing station was not sampled due to windy conditions. The 24 IBI Stations were spaced equally apart around the entire shoreline of the lake in a variety of near shore habitats. Each station was approximately 100 feet long. Two back-pack electrofishing runs were conducted with the initial run of 100 feet near the shore-water interface in depths of < 1 foot and the second run of 100 feet long about 10-20 feet from shore in depths up to 2 feet.

Approximately 21 different fish species (14 species from back-pack electrofishing, 19 species from seining) were captured from electrofishing and seining combined. Fish species captured included gamefish (i.e. Smallmouth Bass and Largemouth Bass), panfish (Bluegill, Yellow Perch, Pumpkinseed, Rock Bass, Green Sunfish, and Hybrid Sunfish), large non-gamefish (Yellow Bullhead) and small non-gamefish (Iowa Darter, Johnny Darter, Brook Silverside, Blacknose Shiner, Banded Killifish, Golden Shiner, Logperch, Longnose Dace, Spotfin Shiner, Spottail Shiner, Bluntnose Minnow and Tadpole Madtom). Young of year species captured included Brook Silverside, Largemouth Bass and Smallmouth Bass in seine hauls. Rock Bass and Yellow Bullhead were only captured by electrofishing. The various species captured in Green is indicative of species present in most riverine connected Spicer Area lakes.

Current fish management activities on Green Lake include monitoring the fish population on an annual basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives to maintain or improve water quality, and stocking Walleye to meet long-range goals. The Green Lake fishery will be sampled in the fall of 2017 for YOY Walleye abundance, and the summer of 2017 for all fish species by standard survey nets.

A targeted survey of Tullibee (Cisco) in Green Lake was conducted during mid-late November of 2017 using lake survey gillnets. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass).

Green is a large (5,561 acres), and deep (110 feet maximum) lake located in Kandiyohi County. Green is currently infested with invasive species such as Curly-leaf Pondweed, Eurasian Watermilfoil and Zebra Mussels. A standard survey (summer gillnets and trapnets) of Green Lake was also conducted during late July through early August of 2017. A fall electrofishing survey was conducted on September 27, 2017 to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye abundance in Green Lake. Another targeted fall gillnetting survey was conducted for Walleye during late September of 2017.

Tullibee were believed to be initially introduced into Green during the 1880's. Koronis is the only other Spicer Area lake with a self-sustaining Tullibee population. Tullibee spawn in 3-6 feet of water over bottom substrates consisting of large rock during late November to early December when the water temperature reaches 41 degrees Fahrenheit "F" or less. Spawning substrates in both Green and Koronis during recent years have been covered by periphyton/algae except in shallow (<1 foot) windswept shoal areas. Climate changes may be negatively affecting Tullibee natural reproduction/recruitment success in these lakes due to degrading spawning habitat and increasing numbers of warm water fish species (i.e. Rock Bass, Pumpkinseed, Smallmouth Bass, Largemouth Bass, etc.) which prey upon Tullibee eggs, fry or fingerlings.

Adult Tullibee are susceptible to summerkill in Green Lake if oxygen levels drop (<2 ppm) in the cooler deeper areas (<74 F) of the lake for an extended time (1-3 weeks) during late July to early August. Young Tullibee can tolerate warmer temperatures than adult Tullibee. The last reported summerkill on Green prior to 2011 was a minor event during 1995. Low dissolved oxygen (<2 ppm) levels were present at depths where preferred adult Tullibee temperatures (<74 F) occurred for a short time period in the 2010 late summer. Although no summerkill of Tullibee was reported for Green, a minor summerkill of adult Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2010. A major summerkill of Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2011, but only a minor kill occurred in Green during the 2011 summer. Drought conditions and extremely high air temperatures were the norm for the Spicer Area during July and early August of 2012. There were no apparent summerkills in Green or Koronis during 2012, but adult numbers were so low that summerkill events may not have been recognizable, especially due to the large numbers of pelicans living on Lake Koronis islands. A narrow band (1-3 feet) of marginal temperatures (<74 F) and dissolved oxygen levels (1-3 ppm) was present in depths of 25-30 feet in Green during late July and early August of 2012. Dissolved oxygen levels and temperatures in Green were at potential summerkill levels of 2 ppm and 74 F on both July 30th and August 9th of 2012. Summer temperature and oxygen conditions were more conducive for Tullibee survival during 2013-2017.

Zebra Mussels were first observed in Green Lake in 2014. Presently, Zebra Mussels are abundant within the lake. It is unknown the extent Zebra Mussels will affect Tullibee and corresponding forage base. Green has been the only lake in the Spicer Area open to the public for fall gillnetting of Tullibee during late November or early December each year since the late 1980's. Green Lake has been closed for Tullibee gillnetting since 2012 due to the low numbers sampled in recent years. Tullibee are an important forage fish for trophy northern pike in Green.

Tullibee were not present in the previous 2017 summer standard survey catch. The Tullibee historical average summer catch rate is 2.06 fish/gillnet for Green Lake. A targeted September gillnetting survey was conducted primarily to assess the Walleye population. There were 12 gillnets set at standard summer stations during September of 2017. In addition, 2 special gillnets were also set in deeper water (40-50 feet deep), adjacent to standard sets near Hultgren's and Gratz's Bars. Tullibee (5.50 fish/special gillnet, 11.43 inches) were only captured at these two sites during the September gillnetting survey.

Tullibee numbers were low (0.50 fish/gillnet, 11.25 inches) in the 2017 November survey. Tullibee abundance was higher in the 2012 (8.33 fish/gillnet, 13.61 inches) and 2015 (10.33 fish/gillnet, 13.66 inches) fall surveys. Moderate numbers of Tullibee were captured in nearby Lake Koronis (19.67 fish fish/gillnet, 14.17 inches) in the 2015 fall, but low numbers in 2017 (10.33 fish/gillnet, 14.41 inches). The fall Tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 70.30 fish/gillnet and 12.48 inches for Green Lake.
